{"title_page": "Emma Stone", "text_new": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American actress}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{Use American English|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n | name        = Emma Stone\n | image       = Emma Stone at the 39th Mill Valley Film Festival (cropped).jpg\n | alt         = A picture of Emma Stone as she looks at the camera.\n | caption     = Stone at the 2016 [[Mill Valley Film Festival]]\n | birthname   = Emily Jean Stone\n | birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1988|11|6}}\n | birth_place = [[Scottsdale, Arizona]], U.S.<!--As per WP:LINKDIRECT and Template:infobox person, birth/death place indicates city, state, then country. No need to spell out \"United States; 'U.S.' is fine.-->\n | occupation  = Actress\n | yearsactive = 2004\u2013present\n | partner     = [[Dave McCary]] (2017\u2013present; engaged)\n | works       = [[List of Emma Stone performances|Performances]]\n | awards      = [[List of awards and nominations received by Emma Stone|Full list]]\n | signature   = Emma Stone Signature.svg\n }}\n'''Emily Jean''' \"'''Emma'''\" '''Stone''' (born November 6, 1988) is an American actress. The recipient of [[List of awards and nominations received by Emma Stone|numerous accolades]], including an [[Academy Award]] and a [[Golden Globe Award]], she was the world's highest-paid actress in 2017. Stone has appeared in [[Celebrity 100|''Forbes'' Celebrity 100]] in 2013 and in 2017, she was featured by ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' as one of the [[Time 100|100 most influential people in the world]].\n\nBorn and raised in [[Scottsdale, Arizona]], Stone began acting as a child, in a theater production of ''[[The Wind in the Willows]]'' in 2000. As a teenager, she relocated to Los Angeles with her mother and made her television debut in ''[[The New Partridge Family|In Search of the New Partridge Family]]'' (2004), a reality show that produced only an unsold pilot. After small television roles, she made her film debut in ''[[Superbad (film)|Superbad]]'' (2007), and received positive media attention for her role in ''[[Zombieland]]'' (2009). The 2010 teen comedy ''[[Easy A]]'' was Stone's first starring role, earning her nominations for the [[BAFTA Rising Star Award]] and a [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Comedy or Musical|Golden Globe Award for Best Actress]]. This breakthrough was followed with further success in the romantic comedy ''[[Crazy, Stupid, Love]]'' (2011) and the drama ''[[The Help (film)|The Help]]'' (2011).\n\nStone gained wider recognition as [[Gwen Stacy]] in the 2012 superhero film ''[[The Amazing Spider-Man (2012 film)|The Amazing Spider-Man]]'', and [[The Amazing Spider-Man 2|its 2014 sequel]]. She was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress]] for playing a recovering drug addict in the black comedy ''[[Birdman (film)|Birdman]]'' (2014), and her [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] debut came in a revival of the musical ''[[Cabaret (musical)|Cabaret]]'' (2014\u20132015). She won the [[Academy Award for Best Actress]] for playing an aspiring actress in the romantic musical ''[[La La Land (film)|La La Land]]'' (2016). Stone portrayed [[Billie Jean King]] in the biographical sports film ''[[Battle of the Sexes (2017 film)|Battle of the Sexes]]'' (2017) and [[Abigail Masham]] in the historical comedy-drama ''[[The Favourite (film)|The Favourite]]'' (2018), receiving a third Academy Award nomination for the latter. She has since starred in the [[Netflix]] dark comedy miniseries ''[[Maniac (miniseries)|Maniac]]'' (2018) and the comedy sequel ''[[Zombieland: Double Tap]]'' (2019).\n\n==Early life==\nEmily Jean Stone was born on November 6, 1988, in [[Scottsdale, Arizona]], to Krista Jean Stone ([[Given name#Name at birth|n\u00e9e]] Yeager), a homemaker, and Jeffrey Charles Stone, the founder and CEO of a general-contracting company.<ref name=\"F.Y.I.\">{{cite web|title=Emma Stone Biography|url=http://www.biography.com/people/emma-stone-20874773|publisher=[[FYI (U.S. TV channel)|FYI]]|accessdate=March 17, 2016|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160423201239/http://www.biography.com/people/emma-stone-20874773|archivedate=April 23, 2016| url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"vanityfair1\">{{cite news|last1=Diehl |first1=Jessica |last2=Wolfe |first2=Alexandra |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2011/08/emma-stone-201108 |title=Hollywood Is Her Oyster |accessdate=March 17, 2016 |work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160312131935/http://www.vanityfair.com/news/2011/08/emma-stone-201108 |archivedate=March 12, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Stone lived on the grounds of the [[Camelback Inn]] resort from the age of 12 to 15.<ref>{{cite web|last=Barker |first=Lynn |url=http://www.teenhollywood.com/2008/08/19/rockin-with-emma-stone |title=\"Rockin'\" with Emma Stone |publisher=TeenHollywood.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140417044401/http://www.teenhollywood.com/2008/08/19/rockin-with-emma-stone|archivedate=April 17, 2014 |date=August 19, 2008 |accessdate=September 8, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"people\">{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/emma_stone/biography/0,,20517671,00.html |title=Emma Stone Biography |website=[[People (magazine)|People]] |date= |accessdate=September 8, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160419122505/http://www.people.com/people/emma_stone/biography/0%2C%2C20517671%2C00.html |archivedate=April 19, 2016 |df= }}</ref> She has a younger brother, Spencer.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Thomas |first1=Leah |title=Emma Stone Brings Brother Spencer to the Golden Globes, Adding to the Trend of the Night |url=http://www.bustle.com/articles/57994-emma-stone-brings-brother-spencer-to-the-golden-globes-adding-to-the-trend-of-the-night |accessdate=March 17, 2016 |work=[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]] |date=January 12, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160325033423/http://www.bustle.com/articles/57994-emma-stone-brings-brother-spencer-to-the-golden-globes-adding-to-the-trend-of-the-night |archivedate=March 25, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Her paternal grandfather, Conrad Ostberg Sten, was from a Swedish family that [[Anglicisation|anglicized]] their surname to \"Stone\" when they immigrated to the United States through [[Ellis Island]]. She also has German, English, Scottish, and Irish ancestry.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=David |first1=Elliot |year=2010 |title=Emma Stone |journal=Wonderland |issue=23 |pages=177\u2013181}}</ref>\n\n[[File:ValleyYouthTheatre.jpg|thumb|right|Stone appeared in sixteen productions at [[Valley Youth Theatre]].]]\nAs an infant, Stone had [[baby colic]] and cried frequently; she consequently developed [[Vocal fold nodule|nodules]] and calluses on her vocal cords while she was a child.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wilner|first=Norman|date=July 27, 2011|title=Q&A: Emma Stone|url=http://www.nowtoronto.com/daily/movies/story.cfm?content=181989|work=[[Now (newspaper)|Now]]|accessdate=November 13, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120620013944/http://www.nowtoronto.com/daily/movies/story.cfm?content=181989|archivedate=June 20, 2012}}</ref> Stone has described herself as having been \"loud\" and \"bossy\" while growing up.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.wmagazine.com/people/celebrities/2011/01/emma_stone_easy_a_actress/ |title=Emma Stone |last=Hirschberg |first=Lynn |date=January 2011 |work=[[W (magazine)|W]] |access-date=April 12, 2016 |via= |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425004045/http://www.wmagazine.com/people/celebrities/2011/01/emma_stone_easy_a_actress/ |archivedate=April 25, 2016 |df= }}</ref> She was educated at Sequoya Elementary School and attended [[Scottsdale Unified School District|Cocopah Middle School]] for the sixth grade. Although she did not like school, she has stated that her controlling nature meant that \"I made sure I got all [[Grading (education)|As]]\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Schuman |first=Michael A. |title=Emma!: Amazing Actress Emma Stone |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mrWUAgAAQBAJ |year=2013 |publisher=Enslow Publishers |isbn=978-0-7660-4113-4 |pages=11\u201312 |accessdate=May 16, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170131104515/https://books.google.com/books?id=mrWUAgAAQBAJ |archivedate=January 31, 2017 |df= }}</ref> Stone suffered [[panic attack]]s as a child,<ref name=\"WSJ-IrrationalMan-2015\">{{cite news|last1=Eells |first1=Josh |title=Emma Stone Talks 'Irrational Man,' the Sony Hack and Keeping Her Personal Life Private |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/emma-stone-talks-irrational-man-the-sony-hack-and-keeping-her-personal-life-private-1434547660 |accessdate=March 16, 2016 |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=June 17, 2015 |url-access=subscription  |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160316045141/http://www.wsj.com/articles/emma-stone-talks-irrational-man-the-sony-hack-and-keeping-her-personal-life-private-1434547660 |archivedate=March 16, 2016 |df= }}</ref> which she says caused a decline in her social skills.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fisher |first1=Luchina |title=Emma Stone Has History of Panic Attacks |url=https://abcnews.go.com/blogs/entertainment/2012/06/emma-stone-has-history-of-panic-attacks/ |accessdate=March 23, 2016 |publisher=[[ABC News]] |date=June 21, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160326092353/http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/entertainment/2012/06/emma-stone-has-history-of-panic-attacks/ |archivedate=March 26, 2016 |df= }}</ref> She underwent therapy but states that it was her participation in local theater plays that helped cure the attacks.<ref name=\"WSJ-IrrationalMan-2015\" />\n\n{{quote|The first time I had a panic attack I was sitting in my friend's house, and I thought the house was burning down. I called my mom and she brought me home, and for the next three years it just would not stop. I would go to the nurse at lunch most days and just wring my hands. I would ask my mom to tell me exactly how the day was going to be, then ask again 30 seconds later. I just needed to know that no one was going to die and nothing was going to change. | Stone | ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', June 2015<ref name=\"WSJ-IrrationalMan-2015\" />}}\n\nStone started acting at age four;<ref name=\"people\" /> she wanted a career in [[sketch comedy]] initially, but shifted her focus toward musical theater, and took voice lessons for several years.<ref name=\"Blackbook2009\" /> Her acting debut, at the age of 11, came in a stage production of ''[[The Wind in the Willows]]'', playing the part of Otter.<ref>{{cite news|title=Emma Stone: Before She Was Famous |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/11/04/emma-stone-before-she-was-famous-theater-productions_n_1076798.html |accessdate=March 15, 2016 |work=[[The Huffington Post]] |date=January 4, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160322100722/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/11/04/emma-stone-before-she-was-famous-theater-productions_n_1076798.html |archivedate=March 22, 2016 |df= }}</ref> The actress was [[Homeschooling|homeschooled]] for two years, during which time she appeared in sixteen productions at Phoenix's [[Valley Youth Theatre]]\u2014including ''[[The Princess and the Pea]]'', ''[[Alice's Adventures in Wonderland]]'', and ''[[Joseph and the Amazing Technicolor Dreamcoat]]''<ref name=\"F.Y.I.\" />\u2014and performed with the theater's [[improvisational theatre|improvisational comedy]] troupe.<ref name=\"EastValleyTribune\">{{cite news|last=Outhier|first= Craig |date=August 16, 2008|url=http://www.eastvalleytribune.com/article_9aeedb12-8c94-54f1-b507-9ff97ffb0cc3.html|title=Emma Stone explores comedy with latest roles|work=[[East Valley Tribune]]|accessdate=October 2, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120919164526/http://www.eastvalleytribune.com/article_9aeedb12-8c94-54f1-b507-9ff97ffb0cc3.html|archivedate=September 19, 2012}}</ref> Around this time, she traveled to Los Angeles and auditioned unsuccessfully for a role in [[Nickelodeon]]'s ''[[All That]]''.<ref name=\"breakout\">{{cite book|last=Owings |first=Lisa |title=Emma Stone: Breakout Movie Star |url=https://archive.org/details/emmastonebreakou0000owin |url-access=registration |year=2014 |publisher=ABDO Publishing Company |isbn=978-1-62968-026-2 |page=22; 33 |accessdate=May 16, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Her parents later sent her for private acting lessons with a local acting coach, who had worked at the [[William Morris Agency]] in the 1970s.<ref name=\"vanityfair1\" />\n\nStone attended [[Xavier College Preparatory (Arizona)|Xavier College Preparatory]]{{nsmdns}}an all-girl [[Catholic school|Catholic high school]]{{nsmdns}}as a freshman, but [[High school dropouts|dropped out]] after one semester to become an actress.<ref name=\"F.Y.I.\" /> She prepared a [[Microsoft PowerPoint|PowerPoint]] presentation for her parents titled \"Project Hollywood\" (featuring [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]'s 2003 song \"[[Hollywood (Madonna song)|Hollywood]]\") to convince them to let her move to California to pursue an acting career.<ref name=\"Blackbook2009\" /> In January 2004, she moved with her mother to an apartment in Los Angeles. She recalls: \"I went up for every single show on the [[Disney Channel]] and auditioned to play the daughter on every single sitcom\", adding, \"I ended up getting none.\"<ref name=\"people\" /> Between auditions for roles, she enrolled in online high-school classes, and worked part-time at a dog-treat bakery.<ref name=\"vanityfair1\" /><ref name=\"WSJ-IrrationalMan-2015\" />\n\n==Career==\n===Early career (2004\u20132008)===\nWhen Stone registered for the [[Screen Actors Guild]], the name \"Emily Stone\" was already taken. She initially chose to go by \"Riley Stone\", but after guest-starring in the [[NBC]] drama ''[[Medium (TV series)|Medium]]'' and the [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] sitcom ''[[Malcolm in the Middle]]'', she decided that she was more comfortable with \"Emma\".<ref name=\"breakout\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Printing \u2013 Emma Stone \u2013 Interview Magazine |url=http://www.interviewmagazine.com/film/emma-stone/print/ |accessdate=August 21, 2016 |work=[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816012839/http://www.interviewmagazine.com/film/emma-stone/print |archivedate=August 16, 2016 |df= }}</ref> She chose to use \"Emma\" in honor of [[Emma Bunton]] of [[the Spice Girls]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/emma-stone-reveals-hilariously-bad-reason-stopped-using-real-name-094537813.html|title=Emma Stone reveals the hilariously bad reason she stopped using her real name|access-date=2018-11-17|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190606155337/https://finance.yahoo.com/news/emma-stone-reveals-hilariously-bad-reason-stopped-using-real-name-094537813.html|archive-date=June 6, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> She made her television debut as Laurie Partridge on the [[VH1]] talent competition reality show ''In Search of the New Partridge Family'' (2004). The resulting show, retitled ''[[The New Partridge Family]]'' (2004), remained an unsold pilot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/427693/emma-stone-flashback-see-star-sing-on-partridge-family-reality-competition-in-pre-fame-days |title=Emma Stone Flashback: See Star Sing on Partridge Family Reality Competition in Pre-Fame Days |publisher=[[E!]] |date=June 7, 2013 |accessdate=March 24, 2016 |author=Grossberg, Josh |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160508123457/http://www.eonline.com/news/427693/emma-stone-flashback-see-star-sing-on-partridge-family-reality-competition-in-pre-fame-days |archivedate=May 8, 2016 |df= }}</ref> She followed this with a guest appearance in [[Louis C.K.]]'s [[HBO]] series ''[[Lucky Louie]]''.<ref name=\"WSJ-IrrationalMan-2015\" /> She auditioned to star as [[Claire Bennet]] in the NBC science fiction drama [[Heroes (U.S. TV series)|''Heroes'']] (2007) but was unsuccessful and later called this her \"rock bottom\" experience.<ref name=\"vanityfair1\" /> In April 2007, she played [[List of Drive characters#Violet Trimble|Violet Trimble]] in the Fox action drama ''[[Drive (2007 TV series)|Drive]]'', but the show was canceled after seven episodes.<ref name=\"F.Y.I.\" />\n\nStone made her feature film debut in [[Greg Mottola]]'s comedy ''[[Superbad (film)|Superbad]]'' (2007), co-starring [[Michael Cera]] and [[Jonah Hill]]. The film tells the story of two high school students who go through a series of comic misadventures after they plan to buy alcohol for a party. To play the role of Hill's romantic interest, she dyed her hair red.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.teenvogue.com/gallery/emma-stone-hair-styles |title=Emma Stone's Best Hair Moments |work=[[Teen Vogue]] |accessdate=March 23, 2016 |author=Duan, Noel |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160411050337/http://www.teenvogue.com/gallery/emma-stone-hair-styles |archivedate=April 11, 2016 |df= }}</ref> A reviewer for ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' found her \"appealing\", but felt that her role was poorly written.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/superbad-158043 |title=Superbad |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=March 23, 2016 |author=Farber, Stephen |date=August 6, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408205811/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/superbad-158043 |archivedate=April 8, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Stone has described the experience of acting in her first film as \"amazing&nbsp;... [but] very different than other experiences I've had since then\".<ref name=\"AccessHollywood6-4-2008\">{{cite news|url=http://www.accesshollywood.com/article/9785/rising-star-emma-stone/|title=Rising Star: Emma Stone|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080609021459/http://www.accesshollywood.com/article/9785/rising-star-emma-stone/|archivedate=June 9, 2008|work=[[Access Hollywood]]|date=June 4, 2008|accessdate=June 5, 2008}}</ref> The film was a commercial success, and earned her the [[Young Hollywood Award]] for Exciting New Face.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=superbad.htm |title=Superbad |publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=March 23, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408184959/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=superbad.htm |archivedate=April 8, 2016 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.lexpress.fr/culture/cinema/emma-stone-une-muse-qui-ne-craint-pas-les-defis_1723443.html | title=Emma Stone, une muse qui ne craint pas les d\u00e9fis | work=[[L'Express]] | date=October 14, 2015 | accessdate=March 23, 2016 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151019031823/http://www.lexpress.fr/culture/cinema/emma-stone-une-muse-qui-ne-craint-pas-les-defis_1723443.html | archivedate=October 19, 2015 | language=French}}</ref>\n\nThe following year, Stone starred in the comedy ''[[The Rocker (film)|The Rocker]]'' (2008) playing Amelia Stone, the \"straight face\" [[bass guitar]]ist in a band; she learned to play the bass for the role.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/new/Interview-Emma-Stone-And-Teddy-Geiger-of-The-Rocker-9109.html |title=Interview: Emma Stone And Teddy Geiger Of The Rocker |publisher=Cinemablend.com |accessdate=March 24, 2016 |author=McConnell, Mariana |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160402011602/http://www.cinemablend.com/new/Interview-Emma-Stone-And-Teddy-Geiger-of-The-Rocker-9109.html |archivedate=April 2, 2016 |df= |date=June 9, 2008 }}</ref> The actress, who describes herself as \"a big smiler and laugher\", has admitted that she found it difficult portraying a character whose personality traits were so different from her own. The film, and her performance, received negative reviews from critics and was a commercial failure.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Rocker |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/10009055-rocker/ |publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=March 24, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160312080953/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/10009055-rocker/ |archivedate=March 12, 2016 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Hendrix |first1=Graddy |title=Rainn Wilson on His New Spiritual Book and How The Rocker's Epic Flop Changed His Life for the Better |url=https://www.vulture.com/2010/10/the_vulture_transcript_rainn_w.html |accessdate=March 23, 2016 |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |date=October 29, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160406052037/http://www.vulture.com/2010/10/the_vulture_transcript_rainn_w.html |archivedate=April 6, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Her next release, the romantic comedy ''[[The House Bunny]]'', performed better at the box-office, becoming a moderate commercial success.<ref>{{cite news|title=French auds flock to 'Barcelona' |url=https://variety.com/2008/film/news/french-auds-flock-to-barcelona-1117993958/ |accessdate=March 23, 2016 |work=Variety |date=October 14, 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160404124644/http://variety.com/2008/film/news/french-auds-flock-to-barcelona-1117993958/ |archivedate=April 4, 2016 |df= }}</ref> The film sees her play the president of a sorority, and perform a [[cover version]] of [[the Waitresses]]' 1982 song \"[[I Know What Boys Like (song)|I Know What Boys Like]]\".<ref name=\"Sullivan2008\">{{cite news |last1=Sullivan |first1=Kevin |date=June 2, 2008 |url=http://www.northbynorthwestern.com/story/the-house-bunny/ |title=An interview with Emma Stone of The House Bunny |work=[[North by Northwestern]] |accessdate=June 4, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120312165049/http://www.northbynorthwestern.com/story/the-house-bunny/ |archivedate=March 12, 2012 |df= }}</ref> Reviews for the film were generally negative,<ref>{{cite web|title=The House Bunny |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/house_bunny |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=March 24, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160313030016/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/house_bunny/ |archivedate=March 13, 2016 |df= }}</ref> though she was praised for her supporting role,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/richard-brody/the-talent-in-the-house |title=The Talent in the House |work=[[The New Yorker]] |date=March 29, 2012 |accessdate=May 18, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160924132227/http://www.newyorker.com/culture/richard-brody/the-talent-in-the-house |archivedate=September 24, 2016 |df= }}</ref> and ''[[TV Guide]]''{{'s}} Ken Fox wrote of Stone that: \"She's positively incandescent, lighting up a movie that would be pretty dim without her.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fox |first1=Ken |title=The House Bunny |url=https://www.tvguide.com/movies/house-bunny/review/293511/ |accessdate=March 24, 2016 |work=[[TV Guide]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160407025625/http://www.tvguide.com/movies/house-bunny/review/293511/ |archivedate=April 7, 2016 |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Breakthrough (2009\u20132011)===\n[[File:EmmaStoneSept09.jpg|thumb|Stone at the ''[[Zombieland]]'' world premiere in 2009]]\n\nStone appeared in three films released in 2009. The first of these was opposite [[Matthew McConaughey]], [[Jennifer Garner]] and [[Michael Douglas]] in [[Mark Waters (director)|Mark Waters]]' ''[[Ghosts of Girlfriends Past]]''. Loosely based on [[Charles Dickens]]' 1843 [[novella]] ''[[A Christmas Carol]]'', the romantic comedy has her playing a ghost who haunts her former boyfriend. Critical reaction to the film was negative, though it was a modest commercial success.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=ghostsofgirlfriendspast.htm |title=Ghosts of Girlfriends Past (2009) |publisher=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=March 25, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160407014245/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=ghostsofgirlfriendspast.htm |archivedate=April 7, 2016 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Ghosts of Girlfriends Past (2009) |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=March 25, 2016 |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1193906-ghosts_of_girlfriends_past |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408110619/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1193906-ghosts_of_girlfriends_past/ |archivedate=April 8, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Her most financially profitable venture that year was [[Ruben Fleischer]]'s $102.3 million-grossing horror comedy film ''[[Zombieland]]'',<ref>{{cite web|title=2009 Yearly Box Office Results |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?yr=2009 |publisher=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=March 26, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160406233637/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?yr=2009 |archivedate=April 6, 2016 |df= }}</ref> in which she features alongside [[Jesse Eisenberg]], [[Woody Harrelson]] and [[Abigail Breslin]]. In the film, she appeared as a con artist and survivor of a [[zombie apocalypse]], in a role which ''[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]''{{'s}} Chris Hewitt found to be \"somewhat underwritten\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hewitt |first1=Chris |title=Zombieland Review |url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/zombieland/review/ |accessdate=March 26, 2016 |work=[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]] |date=October 9, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625030310/http://www.empireonline.com/movies/zombieland/review/ |archivedate=June 25, 2016 |df= }}</ref> In a more positive review, the critic for ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' wrote: \"[T]he hugely promising Stone{{nbsp}}... [is] a tough cookie who projects the aura of being wiser than her years.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Robey |first1=Tim |title=Zombieland, review |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/6273649/Zombieland-review.html |accessdate=April 11, 2016 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=October 8, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160424003803/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/6273649/Zombieland-review.html |archivedate=April 24, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Stone's third release in 2009 was [[Kieran Mulroney|Kieran and Michelle Mulroney's]] ''[[Paper Man (2009 film)|Paper Man]]'', a comedy-drama which disappointed critics.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lawrence|first1=Will|title=The heart of Stone|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/movies/the-heart-of-stone-30192722.html|accessdate=May 16, 2016|work=[[Irish Independent]]|date=April 18, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160610191804/http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/movies/the-heart-of-stone-30192722.html|archive-date=June 10, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nStone provided the voice of an [[Australian Shepherd]] in ''[[Marmaduke (film)|Marmaduke]]'' (2010), a comedy from director [[Tom Dey]], which is based on [[Brad Anderson (cartoonist)|Brad Anderson]]'s [[Marmaduke|long-running comic strip of the same name]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kit |first1=Borys |date=November 3, 2009 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-wilson-idUSTRE5A20K120091103 |title=Owen Wilson signs on for 'Marmaduke' |publisher=Reuters |accessdate=November 7, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305213159/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-wilson-idUSTRE5A20K120091103 |archivedate=March 5, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Her breakthrough came the same year with a starring role in ''[[Easy A]]'', a teen comedy directed by [[Will Gluck]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wilner|first1=Norman|url=https://nowtoronto.com/movies/cover-story/emma-stone/ |title=Emma Stone|work=Now|date=September 9, 2010|accessdate=September 16, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160114112247/https://nowtoronto.com/movies/cover-story/emma-stone/|archivedate=January 14, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Emma Stone On 'Obsessing' Over Her Breakout Role In 'Easy A' |url=http://www.accesshollywood.com/videos/emma-stone-on-obsessing-over-her-breakout-role-in-easy-a-23090/ |accessdate=March 27, 2016 |work=Access Hollywood |date=August 31, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160409071552/http://www.accesshollywood.com/videos/emma-stone-on-obsessing-over-her-breakout-role-in-easy-a-23090/ |archivedate=April 9, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Partially based on [[Nathaniel Hawthorne]]'s 1850 historical romance novel ''[[The Scarlet Letter]]'', the film tells the story of Olive Penderghast (Stone), a high school student who becomes embroiled in a comic sex scandal after a false rumor circulates that she is sexually [[promiscuous]]. Stone read the script before the project was optioned for production, and pursued it with her manager while production details were being finalized. She found the script \"so different and unique from anything I'd read before\", saying that it was \"funny and sweet\". When Stone discovered that the film had begun production, she met with Gluck, expressing her enthusiasm for the project. A few months later, the audition process started and she met again with Gluck, becoming one of the first actresses to audition.<ref name=\"collider\">{{cite web|last1=Roberts|first1=Sheila|date=September 11, 2010|url=https://collider.com/emma-stone-interview-easy-a/48258/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304084823/http://collider.com/emma-stone-interview-easy-a/|archivedate=March 4, 2016|title=Emma Stone Interview Easy A|publisher=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|accessdate=July 1, 2011}}</ref> The film received positive critical reviews, and Stone's performance was considered its prime asset.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Thorpe |first1=Vanessa |title=Lies, paranoia and jealousy on the internet's social networks inspire Hollywood |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2010/oct/24/easya-social-network-chatroom-catfish |accessdate=August 21, 2016 |work=The Guardian |date=October 23, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920225141/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2010/oct/24/easya-social-network-chatroom-catfish |archivedate=September 20, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Anna Smith of ''[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]'' commented: \"Stone gives a terrific performance, her knowing drawl implying intellect and indifference with underlying warmth.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Smith |first1=Anna |title=Easy A |url=https://www.timeout.com/london/film/easy-a |accessdate=March 27, 2016 |work=[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]] |date=October 19, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160413204448/http://www.timeout.com/london/film/easy-a |archivedate=April 13, 2016 |df= }}</ref> With a total box office of $75 million, the film was a commercial success.<ref>{{cite web|title=Easy A (2010) |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=easya.htm |publisher=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=March 27, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304203436/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=easya.htm |archivedate=March 4, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Stone was nominated for a [[BAFTA Rising Star Award]] and a [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy|Golden Globe Award for Best Actress in a Musical or Comedy]], and won the [[MTV Movie Award for Best Comedic Performance]].<ref name=\"EasyA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bafta.org/awards/film/2011-film-awards,1572,BA.html#jump23 |title=Nominees Are Announced Orange Wednesdays Rising Star Award |publisher=[[British Academy of Film and Television Arts]] |date=January 6, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110110061729/http://www.bafta.org/awards/film/2011-film-awards%2C1572%2CBA.html |archivedate=January 10, 2011 |accessdate=March 24, 2016 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}<br />{{cite news|first=Amy |last=Kaufmann |title=Golden Globes 2011 nominations: Newcomers Emma Stone, Jennifer Lawrence and Mila Kunis react |date=December 15, 2010 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |url=http://theenvelope.latimes.com/awards/globes/la-et-globes-newcomers-20101215,0,5904052.story |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101218181041/http://theenvelope.latimes.com/awards/globes/la-et-globes-newcomers-20101215%2C0%2C5904052.story |archivedate=December 18, 2010 |accessdate=December 19, 2010 |url-status=dead |df= }}<br />{{cite web|title=2011 MTV Movie Awards |url=http://www.mtv.com/ontv/movieawards/2011/ |publisher=MTV |accessdate=March 24, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160323083848/http://www.mtv.com/ontv/movieawards/2011/ |archivedate=March 23, 2016 |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn October 2010, Stone hosted an episode of NBC's late-night sketch comedy ''[[Saturday Night Live]]''; her appearances included a sketch playing off her resemblance to [[Lindsay Lohan]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Setoodeh |first=Ramin |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2011/09/01/emma-stone-s-lindsay-lohan-problem.html |title=Emma Stone's Lohan Problem |work=[[The Daily Beast]] |date=September 1, 2011 |accessdate=October 4, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161005131215/http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2011/09/01/emma-stone-s-lindsay-lohan-problem.html |archivedate=October 5, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Stone described it as \"the greatest week of my life\".<ref name=\"people\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=SNL Season 36 Episode 04 \u2013 Emma Stone, Kings of Leon. |url=http://www.nbc.com/saturday-night-live/season-36/episode/4-emma-stone-with-kings-of-leon-60496 |accessdate=August 1, 2016 |publisher=[[NBC]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822050025/http://www.nbc.com/saturday-night-live/season-36/episode/4-emma-stone-with-kings-of-leon-60496 |archivedate=August 22, 2016 |df= }}</ref> She hosted it again in 2011, appeared in an episode in 2014, and in [[Saturday Night Live 40th Anniversary Special|its 40th anniversary special]] in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|last1=McGee |first1=Ryan |title=Recap: 'Saturday Night Live' \u2013 Emma Stone and Coldplay |url=http://www.hitfix.com/blogs/monkeys-as-critics/posts/recap-saturday-night-live-emma-stone-and-coldplay |publisher=[[HitFix]] |date=November 13, 2011 |accessdate=March 25, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160325092321/http://www.hitfix.com/blogs/monkeys-as-critics/posts/recap-saturday-night-live-emma-stone-and-coldplay |archivedate=March 25, 2016 |df= }}<br />{{cite news|last1=Monde |first1=Chinderah |title=Andrew Garfield, Emma Stone spoof 'Amazing Spider-Man 2' with awkward make-out sessions on 'Saturday Night Live' |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv/andrew-garfield-emma-stone-awkwardly-kiss-snl-article-1.1779073 |accessdate=March 25, 2016 |work=[[New York Daily News]] |date=May 4, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160405193939/http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv/andrew-garfield-emma-stone-awkwardly-kiss-snl-article-1.1779073 |archivedate=April 5, 2016 |df= }}<br />{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/jon-hamm-emma-stone-star-wars-snl-1201646236/ |title=Watch: Jon Hamm, Emma Stone Audition for 'Star Wars: The Force Awakens' on 'SNL' |date=November 22, 2015 |accessdate=March 25, 2016 |author=Stedman, Alex |work=Variety |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160225104850/http://variety.com/2015/tv/news/jon-hamm-emma-stone-star-wars-snl-1201646236/ |archivedate=February 25, 2016 |df= }}</ref> A brief appearance in the sex comedy ''[[Friends with Benefits (film)|Friends with Benefits]]'' (2011) reunited her with Gluck.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Siegel |first1=Tatiana |date=July 13, 2010 |url=https://variety.com/2010/film/news/a-rod-goes-from-big-leagues-to-bigscreen-1118021649/ |title=A-Rod goes from big leagues to bigscreen |work=Variety |accessdate=August 1, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004214849/http://variety.com/2010/film/news/a-rod-goes-from-big-leagues-to-bigscreen-1118021649/ |archivedate=October 4, 2013 |df= }}</ref> She followed this with a supporting role in [[Glenn Ficarra]] and [[John Requa]]'s romantic comedy ''[[Crazy, Stupid, Love]]'' (2011) alongside [[Steve Carell]], [[Ryan Gosling]] and [[Julianne Moore]]. The film features her as a law school graduate, and the love interest of Gosling's character. Despite finding \"some inevitable collapses into convention\" in the film, Drew McWeeny of [[HitFix]] wrote that Stone \"ties the whole film together\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=McWeeny |first1=Drew |title=Review: Ryan Gosling, Emma Stone, and Steve Carell excel in smart, adult 'Crazy, Stupid, Love' |url=http://www.hitfix.com/blogs/motion-captured/posts/review-gosling-stone-and-carell-excel-in-smart-adult-crazy-stupid-love |publisher=HitFix |accessdate=March 27, 2016 |date=July 21, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160406053141/http://www.hitfix.com/blogs/motion-captured/posts/review-gosling-stone-and-carell-excel-in-smart-adult-crazy-stupid-love |archivedate=April 6, 2016 |df= }}</ref> At the [[2012 Teen Choice Awards]], she won the [[Teen Choice Award for Choice Movie Actress \u2013 Comedy|Choice Movie Actress \u2013 Comedy]] award for her performance in the film.<ref>{{cite news|first=Philiana |last=Ng |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/teen-choice-awards-breaking-dawn-snow-white-huntsman-337825 |title=Teen Choice Awards 2012: ''Breaking Dawn'', ''Snow White'' Lead Second Wave of Nominees |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=March 27, 2016 |accessdate=June 14, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120615201747/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/teen-choice-awards-breaking-dawn-snow-white-huntsman-337825 |archivedate=June 15, 2012 |url-status=live |df=mdy}}</ref> ''Crazy, Stupid, Love'' was a box office success, grossing $142.9 million worldwide with a production budget of $50 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=crazystupidlove.htm |title=Crazy, Stupid, Love. (2011) |publisher=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=March 29, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160417102459/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=crazystupidlove.htm |archivedate=April 17, 2016 |df= }}</ref>\n\nDisillusioned at being [[typecasting (acting)|typecast]] as the \"sarcastic interest of the guy\", Stone co-starred with [[Viola Davis]] in [[Tate Taylor]]'s period drama ''[[The Help (film)|The Help]]'' (2011), a film she found to be challenging.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/entertainment/film-tv/news/stone-typecasting-is-frustrating-28675472.html | title=Stone: Typecasting is frustrating | work=[[Belfast Telegraph]] | date=October 28, 2011 | accessdate=April 10, 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190601211625/https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/entertainment/film-tv/news/stone-typecasting-is-frustrating-28675472.html | archive-date=June 1, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The film is based on [[Kathryn Stockett]]'s [[The Help|2009 novel of the same name]] and is set in 1960s [[Jackson, Mississippi]]. She met with Taylor to express a desire to work in the film. Taylor has said: \"Emma was completely awkward and dorky, with her raspy voice, and she sat down and we got a little intoxicated and had a blast, and I just thought, 'God! God! This is Skeeter.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ew.com/gallery/summer-movies-we-cant-wait-see/477434_help-august-12 |title=Summer Movies We Can't Wait To See |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=June 2, 2011 |accessdate=March 29, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161114144359/http://www.ew.com/gallery/summer-movies-we-cant-wait-see/477434_help-august-12 |archivedate=November 14, 2016 |df= }}</ref> She was cast as Eugenia \"Skeeter\" Phelan, an aspiring writer learning about the lives of the African-American maids. In preparation for the part, she trained to speak in a [[Southern American English|Southern dialect]]; she also educated herself on the [[Civil Rights Movement]] through literature and film.<ref name=\"speakeasy\">{{cite news|title='Paper Man' Co-Star Emma Stone on Playing Skeeter Phelan in 'The Help' |last=Kung |first=Michelle |date=April 12, 2010 |newspaper=The Wall Street Journal |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2010/04/12/paper-man-co-star-emma-stone-on-playing-skeeter-phelan-in-the-help/ |accessdate=April 18, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100418211049/https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2010/04/12/paper-man-co-star-emma-stone-on-playing-skeeter-phelan-in-the-help/ |archivedate=April 18, 2010 |df= }}</ref> With a worldwide gross of $216 million against a budget of $25 million, ''The Help'' became Stone's most commercially successful film to that point.<ref>{{cite web|title=Emma Stone |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/people/chart/?id=emmastone.htm |publisher=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=March 29, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160409101708/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/people/chart/?id=emmastone.htm |archivedate=April 9, 2016 |df= }}</ref> The film, and her performance, received positive reviews from critics.<ref name=\"mojo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.watchmojo.com/video/id/13852/ |title=Top 10 Emma Stone Performances |date=June 3, 2015 |publisher=[[WatchMojo.com]] |accessdate=March 27, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160409091659/http://www.watchmojo.com/video/id/13852/ |archivedate=April 9, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Writing for ''Empire'', Anna Smith thought that Stone was \"well-meaning and hugely likable\" despite finding flaws in the character.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Smith |first1=Anna |title=The Help Review |url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/help-2/review/ |accessdate=April 11, 2016 |work=Empire |date=October 26, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160918025349/http://www.empireonline.com/movies/help-2/review/ |archivedate=September 18, 2016 |df= }}</ref> The film was nominated for an [[Academy Award for Best Picture]],<ref name=\"OAcademyAwards\">{{cite news|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130226215926/http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/legacy/ceremony/84th-winners.html|archivedate=February 26, 2013|url=http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/legacy/ceremony/84th-winners.html |title=The 84th Academy Awards (2012) Nominees and Winners |accessdate=March 29, 2016|publisher=[[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]]}}</ref> and won Best Ensemble Cast from the [[Women Film Critics Circle]] and the [[Broadcast Film Critics Association]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Adams |first1=Ryan |title=The Women Film Critics Circle Awards |url=http://www.awardsdaily.com/2011/12/19/the-women-film-critics-circle-awards/ |publisher=[[Awards Daily]] |accessdate=March 29, 2016 |date=December 19, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160411133735/http://www.awardsdaily.com/2011/12/19/the-women-film-critics-circle-awards/ |archivedate=April 11, 2016 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=17th Annual Critics' Choice Movie Awards (2012) |url=http://www.criticschoice.com/movie-awards/17th-annual-critics-choice-movie-awards-2012/ |publisher=[[Broadcast Film Critics Association]] |accessdate=March 29, 2016 |date=December 13, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121107224146/http://www.criticschoice.com/movie-awards/17th-annual-critics-choice-movie-awards-2012/ |archivedate=November 7, 2012 |df= }}</ref>\n\n===''The Amazing Spider-Man'', ''Birdman'', and Broadway (2012\u20132015)===\nStone declined a role in the action comedy film ''[[21 Jump Street (film)|21 Jump Street]]'' after signing on to [[Marc Webb]]'s 2012 film ''[[The Amazing Spider-Man (2012 film)|The Amazing Spider-Man]]'', a [[Reboot (fiction)|reboot]] of [[Sam Raimi]]'s [[Spider-Man in film#Sam Raimi films|''Spider-Man'' series]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2437995/emma-stone-21-jump-street-reboot/ |title=Exclusive: Emma Stone Not Starring in '21 Jump Street' Reboot |publisher=MTV |date=November 24, 2010 |accessdate=April 6, 2016 |author=Ditzian, Eric |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160415145956/http://www.mtv.com/news/2437995/emma-stone-21-jump-street-reboot/ |archivedate=April 15, 2016 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Kroll |first1=Justin |last2=Stewart |first2=Andrew |date=September 23, 2010 |url=https://variety.com/2010/biz/news/emma-stone-tangled-in-sony-s-web-1118024559/ |title=Emma Stone tangled in Sony's web |work=Variety |accessdate=March 23, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305074025/http://variety.com/2010/biz/news/emma-stone-tangled-in-sony-s-web-1118024559/ |archivedate=March 5, 2016 |df= }}</ref> She portrayed [[Gwen Stacy]], the love interest of the [[Spider-Man|title character]] (played by [[Andrew Garfield]]).<ref>{{cite news |first=Chris |last=Garcia |date=July 28, 2011 |title=Emma Stone has grown up since 'Easy A,' starring opposite Ryan Gosling in 'Crazy, Stupid, Love' Lya|work=New York Daily News |url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2011-07-28/entertainment/29840506_1_emma-stone-andrew-garfield-gwen-stacy |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121028171524/http://articles.nydailynews.com/2011-07-28/entertainment/29840506_1_emma-stone-andrew-garfield-gwen-stacy|archivedate=October 28, 2012|accessdate=March 23, 2016}}</ref> Stone returned to a blond hair color for the role, having dyed it red previously.<ref name=\"blonde\">{{cite web|url=http://news.instyle.com/2010/12/06/emma-stone-goes-blonde-for-spiderman/ |title=Emma Stone goes blonde for Spiderman |website=[[InStyle]] |date=December 6, 2010 |accessdate=March 23, 2016 |first=Kendall |last=Herbst |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120513051933/http://news.instyle.com/2010/12/06/emma-stone-goes-blonde-for-spiderman/ |archivedate=May 13, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy}}</ref><ref name=\"MTV Emma\">{{cite news|url=http://splashpage.mtv.com/2010/11/24/spider-man-emma-stone-gwen-stacy/ |title='Spider-Man' Star Emma Stone on Going Blonde, Science Class, And Becoming Gwen Stacy |publisher=MTV |date=November 24, 2010 |accessdate=November 30, 2011 |first=Erik |last=Ditzian |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120612155349/http://splashpage.mtv.com/2010/11/24/spider-man-emma-stone-gwen-stacy/ |archivedate=June 12, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy}}</ref> She told ''[[The Vancouver Sun]]'' that she felt responsible to educate herself about Spider-Man and admitted that she had not read the comics: \"My experience was with the Sam Raimi movies&nbsp;... I always assumed that [[Mary Jane Watson|Mary Jane]] was his first love\",<ref name=\"other woman\">{{cite news |last1=Lacker |first1=Chris |url=https://vancouversun.com/touch/interview+emma+stone+plays+spider+first+love/5152459/story.html?rel=5155561 |title=Interview: Emma Stone Plays Spider-Man's First Love |date=July 24, 2011 |accessdate=April 9, 2016 |work=[[The Vancouver Sun]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160805180300/http://www.vancouversun.com/touch/interview%2Bemma%2Bstone%2Bplays%2Bspider%2Bfirst%2Blove/5152459/story.html?rel=5155561 |archivedate=August 5, 2016 |df= }}</ref> adding that she was only familiar with Stacy's character from [[Bryce Dallas Howard]]'s portrayal in ''[[Spider-Man 3]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nbcchicago.com/blogs/popcornbiz/Amazing-Spider-Emma-Stone-Marc-Webb-144255585.html |title=\"Spider-Man\" Director and Star Talk Up \"Amazing\" New Film |publisher=[[WMAQ-TV|NBC Chicago]] |date=April 2, 2012 |accessdate=April 24, 2012 |last=Huver |first=Scott |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120331215138/http://www.nbcchicago.com/blogs/popcornbiz/Amazing-Spider-Emma-Stone-Marc-Webb-144255585.html |archivedate=March 31, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref><ref name=\"Empire\">{{cite news|url=https://www.empireonline.com/news/story.asp?NID=31646 |title=Emma Stone on the Amazing Spider-Man |work=Empire |accessdate=November 26, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111228061738/http://www.empireonline.com/news/story.asp?nid=31646 |archivedate=December 28, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=mdy}}</ref> ''The Amazing Spider-Man'' was a commercial success and was [[2012 in film|the seventh highest-grossing film of 2012]] with global revenues of $757.9 million.<ref>{{cite web|title=2012 Worldwide Grosses |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?view2=worldwide&yr=2012&p=.htm |publisher=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=March 25, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160402034443/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?view2=worldwide&yr=2012&p=.htm |archivedate=April 2, 2016 |df= }}</ref> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''{{'s}} [[Lisa Schwarzbaum]] found Stone \"irresistible\",<ref>{{cite news|last1=Schwarzbaum |first1=Lisa |title=The Amazing Spider-Man |url=https://www.ew.com/article/2012/07/04/amazing-spider-man |accessdate=April 9, 2016 |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=July 4, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160405081326/http://www.ew.com/article/2012/07/04/amazing-spider-man |archivedate=April 5, 2016 |df= }}</ref> and [[Ian Freer]] of ''Empire'' magazine was particularly impressed with Stone's and Garfield's performances.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Freer |first1=Ian |title=The Amazing Spider-Man Review |url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/amazing-spider-man/review/ |accessdate=March 25, 2016 |work=Empire |date=July 3, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160406223101/http://www.empireonline.com/movies/amazing-spider-man/review/ |archivedate=April 6, 2016 |df= }}</ref> At the annual [[People's Choice Awards]] ceremony, she was nominated for three awards, including Favorite Movie Actress.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peopleschoice.com/pca/awards/nominees/index.jsp?year=2013|title=People's Choice Awards 2013 Nominees & Winners|publisher=[[People's Choice Awards]]|accessdate=March 24, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160128023759/http://www.peopleschoice.com/pca/awards/nominees/index.jsp?year=2013|archivedate=January 28, 2016}}</ref> Later that year, Stone voiced a role in the crime-based video game, ''[[Sleeping Dogs (video game)|Sleeping Dogs]]'', which earned her a [[Spike Video Game Award]] for Best Performance by a Human Female.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Horgan |first1=Richard |title=Xbox Users Set to Play with a Unique Awards Show Component \u2013 'Samuel L. Jackson Mode' |url=http://www.adweek.com/fishbowlny/2012-video-game-awards-spike-samuell-jackson-mark-burnett/186503 |accessdate=January 25, 2017 |work=[[Adweek]] |date=December 7, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170128135139/http://www.adweek.com/fishbowlny/2012-video-game-awards-spike-samuell-jackson-mark-burnett/186503 |archivedate=January 28, 2017 |df= }}</ref>\n\nStone began 2013 with a voice role in [[DreamWorks Animation|DreamWorks]]' ''[[The Croods]]'', an animated feature nominated for an [[Academy Award for Best Animated Feature]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oscar.go.com/nominees?cid=AMPAS_oscarnominees |title=2014 Oscar Nominees |publisher=[[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]] |accessdate=March 30, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160506020834/http://oscar.go.com/nominees?cid=AMPAS_oscarnominees |archivedate=May 6, 2016 |df= }}</ref> This followed with an appearance in ''[[Movie 43]]'', an [[anthology film]] which consists of sixteen short stories\u2014she played the title role in the segment entitled \"Veronica\".<ref>{{cite news|first=M. Scot |last=Skinner |title=After 'Hours', a Q & A with star |date=November 4, 2010 |newspaper=[[Arizona Daily Star]] |url=http://tucson.com/entertainment/movies/article_4ab2465e-9a9f-58c7-9b54-c18b2d60d8e1.html |accessdate=November 7, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307081337/http://tucson.com/entertainment/movies/article_4ab2465e-9a9f-58c7-9b54-c18b2d60d8e1.html|archivedate=March 7, 2016}}</ref> The actress collaborated with Ryan Gosling and [[Sean Penn]] in Ruben Fleischer's ''[[Gangster Squad (film)|Gangster Squad]]'' (2013), a crime thriller set in Los Angeles during the 1940s.<ref>{{cite news|first1=Jeff |last1=Sneider |first2=Justin |last2=Kroll |title=Emma Stone rounds up 'Gangster Squad' |date=July 26, 2011 |magazine=Variety |url=https://variety.com/2011/film/news/emma-stone-rounds-up-gangster-squad-1118040460/ |accessdate=August 15, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130731201616/http://variety.com/2011/film/news/emma-stone-rounds-up-gangster-squad-1118040460/ |archivedate=July 31, 2013 |df= }}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]''{{'}} [[A. O. Scott]] dismissed the film as \"a hectic jumble of fedoras and zoot suits\", but praised her pairing with Gosling.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/01/11/movies/gangster-squad-with-sean-penn-ryan-gosling-and-emma-stone.html |title=These Law Enforcers Will Stop at Nothing |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=January 10, 2013 |accessdate=April 5, 2016 |author=Scott, A. O. |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170516073551/http://www.nytimes.com/2013/01/11/movies/gangster-squad-with-sean-penn-ryan-gosling-and-emma-stone.html |archivedate=May 16, 2017 |df= }}</ref> Stone expressed a desire to work with Gosling on more projects.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Radish|first1=Christina|url=https://collider.com/ryan-gosling-emma-stone-gangster-squad-interview/220638/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150622002414/http://collider.com/ryan-gosling-emma-stone-gangster-squad-interview/220638/|archivedate=June 22, 2015|title=Josh Brolin, Ryan Gosling, Emma Stone, and Director Ruben Fleischer Talk Gangster Squad|publisher=Collider.com|date=January 8, 2013|accessdate=April 5, 2016}}</ref>\n[[File:Emma Stone by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|left|180px|Stone at [[WonderCon]] in 2012]]\nIn 2014, Stone reprised the role of Gwen Stacy in ''[[The Amazing Spider-Man 2]]''. In an interview with ''[[Total Film]]'', the actress explained that her character was not dependent on the film's protagonist. \"She saves him more than he saves her. She's incredibly helpful to Spider-Man&nbsp;... He's the muscle, she's the brains.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Emma Stone talks saving Spidey in The Amazing Spider-Man 2|url=http://www.totalfilm.com/news/emma-stone-talks-saving-spidey-in-the-amazing-spider-man-2|accessdate=April 6, 2016|work=[[Total Film]]|date=January 4, 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140701013428/http://www.totalfilm.com/news/emma-stone-talks-saving-spidey-in-the-amazing-spider-man-2|archivedate=July 1, 2014}}</ref> Her performance was well received by critics;<ref>{{cite news|last=Silman |first=Anna |title=Review Roundup: The Amazing Spider-Man 2 Belongs to Emma Stone |url=https://www.vulture.com/2014/05/review-roundup-amazing-spider-man-2-emma-stone.html |accessdate=May 4, 2014 |work=[[New York (magazine)|Vulture.com]] |date=May 3, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140504140535/http://www.vulture.com/2014/05/review-roundup-amazing-spider-man-2-emma-stone.html |archivedate=May 4, 2014 |df= }}</ref> an ''Empire'' reviewer praised her for standing out in the film: \"Stone is the [[Heath Ledger]] of this series, doing something unexpected with an easily dismissed supporting character.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Newman |first1=Kim |title=The Amazing Spider-Man 2 Review |url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/amazing-spider-man-2/review/ |accessdate=May 14, 2016 |work=Empire |date=April 16, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160524190307/http://www.empireonline.com/movies/amazing-spider-man-2/review/ |archivedate=May 24, 2016 |df= }}</ref> The role earned her the Favorite Movie Actress award at the [[2015 Kids' Choice Awards]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/kids-choice-awards-complete-winners-783761 |title=Kids' Choice Awards 2015: The Complete Winners List |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=March 28, 2015 |accessdate=April 1, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160209001551/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/kids-choice-awards-complete-winners-783761 |archivedate=February 9, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Later that year, Stone took on a role in [[Woody Allen]]'s romantic comedy ''[[Magic in the Moonlight]]'', a modest commercial success.<ref name=\"Woody\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/aug/21/arthouse-blues-indie-films-terrible-summer |title=Arthouse blues: why did indie films have such a terrible summer? |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=August 21, 2015 |accessdate=April 7, 2016 |author=Smith, Nigel M |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416183345/http://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/aug/21/arthouse-blues-indie-films-terrible-summer |archivedate=April 16, 2016 |df= }}</ref> A. O. Scott criticized her role, and pairing with [[Colin Firth]], describing it as \"the kind of pedantic nonsense that is meant to signify superior intellect\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Scott |first1=A. O. |title=Metaphysical Sleight of Heart |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/25/movies/magic-in-the-moonlight-another-woody-allen-odd-couple.html |accessdate=May 14, 2016 |work=The New York Times |date=July 24, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160715090504/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/25/movies/magic-in-the-moonlight-another-woody-allen-odd-couple.html |archivedate=July 15, 2016 |df= }}</ref>\n\nThe [[black comedy]]-drama ''[[Birdman (film)|Birdman]]'', from director [[Alejandro Gonz\u00e1lez I\u00f1\u00e1rritu]], was Stone's final film release in 2014. Co-starring [[Michael Keaton]] and [[Edward Norton]], the film features her in the role of Sam Thomson, the recovering-addict daughter of actor Riggan Thomson (Keaton), who becomes his assistant. I\u00f1\u00e1rritu created the character based on his experience with his daughter.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mitchell |first1=Elvis |title=Alejandro Gonz\u00e1lez I\u00f1\u00e1rritu |url=http://www.interviewmagazine.com/film/alejandro-gonzalez-inarritu/ |accessdate=April 8, 2016 |work=Interview |date=September 10, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160414004601/http://www.interviewmagazine.com/film/alejandro-gonzalez-inarritu/ |archivedate=April 14, 2016 |df= }}</ref> ''Birdman'' was critically acclaimed,<ref>{{cite news|last1=McMillan |first1=Graeme |title=The Secret Life of the Other Birdman |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/secret-life-birdman-775822 |accessdate=May 14, 2016 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=February 23, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822124933/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/secret-life-birdman-775822 |archivedate=August 22, 2016 |df= }}</ref> and was the most successful film at the [[87th Academy Awards]]; it was nominated for nine awards, winning four, including Best Picture.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/2015 |title=The 87th Academy Awards (2015) Nominees and Winners |accessdate=February 23, 2015 |publisher=Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences (AMPAS) |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150223171100/http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/2015 |archivedate=February 23, 2015 |df= }}</ref> [[The Movie Network]] considered it one of Stone's best performances to date and [[Robbie Collin]] of ''The Daily Telegraph'' was impressed with a monologue she delivers, which he thought was \"like a knitting needle to the gut\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Brian |first1=Greg |title=Was 2014 the Most Significant Breakthrough Year for Emma Stone? Oscar Chances for 'Birdman' |url=http://www.themovienetwork.com/article/was-2014-most-significant-breakthrough-year-emma-stone-oscar-chances-birdman |publisher=[[The Movie Network]] |accessdate=April 9, 2016 |date=November 13, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160407213529/http://www.themovienetwork.com/article/was-2014-most-significant-breakthrough-year-emma-stone-oscar-chances-birdman |archivedate=April 7, 2016 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/2016/04/14/birdman-spectacular/ |title=Birdman: 'spectacular' |date=February 23, 2015 |work=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=April 30, 2016 |author=Collin, Robbie |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160502150729/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/2016/04/14/birdman-spectacular/ |archivedate=May 2, 2016 |df= }}</ref> She received numerous accolades for her portrayal, including nominations for an [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Academy]], a [[BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Supporting Role|BAFTA]], a [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actress \u2013 Motion Picture|Golden Globe]], a [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Supporting Role|Screen Actors Guild]], and a [[Critics' Choice Movie Award|Critics' Choice Movie]] award for Best Supporting Actress.<ref name=\"awards\">{{cite web|url=https://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/2015 |title=The 87th Academy Awards (2015) Nominees and Winners |publisher=Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences |accessdate=March 24, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151201224651/http://oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/2015 |archivedate=December 1, 2015 |df= }}<br />{{cite web|url=http://www.bafta.org/film/awards/supporting-actress-nominees-in-2015 |title=Supporting Actress Nominees in 2015 |publisher=British Academy of Film and Television Arts |accessdate=April 1, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160409132541/http://www.bafta.org/film/awards/supporting-actress-nominees-in-2015 |archivedate=April 9, 2016 |df= }}<br />{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/birdman-grand-budapest-pace-noms-for-critics-choice-awards-1201379383/ |title='Birdman,' 'Grand Budapest' Top Critics Choice Awards Nominations |work=Variety |date=December 15, 2014 |first=Tim |last=Gray |accessdate=March 31, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141216035611/http://variety.com/2014/film/news/birdman-grand-budapest-pace-noms-for-critics-choice-awards-1201379383/ |archivedate=December 16, 2014 |df= }}<br />{{cite web|title=72nd Annual Golden Globes Nominations |url=http://www.goldenglobes.com/articles/72nd-annual-golden-globes-nominations |publisher=[[Golden Globe Awards]] |accessdate=March 24, 2016 |date=December 11, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160407092619/http://www.goldenglobes.com/articles/72nd-annual-golden-globes-nominations |archivedate=April 7, 2016 |df= }}<br />{{cite web|title=The 21st Annual Screen Actors Guild Awards |url=http://www.sagawards.org/awards/nominees-and-recipients/21st-annual-screen-actors-guild-awards |publisher=[[Screen Actors Guild Awards]] |accessdate=March 31, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160316113714/http://sagawards.org/awards/nominees-and-recipients/21st-annual-screen-actors-guild-awards |archivedate=March 16, 2016 |df= }}</ref>\n\nFrom November 2014 to February 2015, Stone starred in a revival of the [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] musical ''[[Cabaret (musical)|Cabaret]]'' as [[Sally Bowles]], taking over the role from [[Michelle Williams (actress)|Michelle Williams]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2014/legit/reviews/broadway-review-emma-stone-in-cabaret-1201372234/ |title=Broadway Review: Emma Stone in 'Cabaret' |author=Stasio, Marilyn |date=December 5, 2014 |accessdate=April 8, 2016 |work=Variety |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305014529/http://variety.com/2014/legit/reviews/broadway-review-emma-stone-in-cabaret-1201372234/ |archivedate=March 5, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Considering it to be \"the most nerve-racking thing ever\", Stone told the ''Entertainment Weekly'' magazine that she listened to a French radio station to mentally prepare herself for the role.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2014/10/emma-stone-cabaret-taylor-swift |title=Emma Stone Is Mentally Preparing for the Moment Taylor Swift Sees Her Sing in Broadway's Cabaret |work=Vanity Fair |date=October 14, 2014 |accessdate=April 21, 2016 |author=Miller, Julie |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160413050737/http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2014/10/emma-stone-cabaret-taylor-swift |archivedate=April 13, 2016 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2015/01/emma-stone-cabaret-sally-bowles-pre-show-rituals |title=Here's What Emma Stone Does Before Each Cabaret Performance on Broadway |date=January 9, 2015 |accessdate=April 21, 2016 |author=Miller, Julie |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160412224855/http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2015/01/emma-stone-cabaret-sally-bowles-pre-show-rituals |archivedate=April 12, 2016 |df= }}</ref> ''Variety''{{'}}s Marilyn Stasio was critical of her singing and found her performance \"a bit narrow as an emotional platform, but a smart choice for her acting skills, the perfect fit for her sharp intelligence and kinetic energy.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Stasio |first1=Marilyn |title=Broadway Review: Emma Stone in 'Cabaret' |url=https://variety.com/2014/legit/reviews/broadway-review-emma-stone-in-cabaret-1201372234/ |accessdate=April 21, 2016 |work=Variety |date=December 5, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305014529/http://variety.com/2014/legit/reviews/broadway-review-emma-stone-in-cabaret-1201372234/ |archivedate=March 5, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Both of Stone's 2015 films{{nsmdns}}the romantic comedy-drama ''[[Aloha (2015 film)|Aloha]]'', and the mystery drama ''[[Irrational Man (film)|Irrational Man]]''{{nsmdns}}were critical and commercial failures, and her roles were panned by critics.<ref name=\"Woody\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=crowe2014.htm |title=Aloha |publisher=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=April 7, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160406031957/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=crowe2014.htm |archivedate=April 6, 2016 |df= }}<br />{{cite web|title=Irrational Man |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/irrational_man/ |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=May 16, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160510220256/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/irrational_man |archivedate=May 10, 2016 |df= }}<br />\n{{cite web|title=Aloha |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/aloha_2015 |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=May 16, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160517040533/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/aloha_2015 |archivedate=May 17, 2016 |df= }}</ref> In [[Cameron Crowe]]'s ''Aloha'', she took on the role of an air force pilot alongside [[Bradley Cooper]], and in the Woody Allen-directed ''Irrational Man'', she portrayed the romantic interest of [[Joaquin Phoenix]]'s character, a philosophy professor. The former was controversial for [[racebending|whitewashing]] the cast, as Stone's character was meant to be of Asian, Hawaiian, and Swedish descent; Stone later regretted the project, acknowledging whitewashing as a widespread problem in Hollywood.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rosen |first1=Christopher |title=Emma Stone says she understands Hollywood whitewashing after Aloha controversy |url=https://www.ew.com/article/2015/07/16/emma-stone-aloha-whitewashing |accessdate=April 7, 2016 |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=July 16, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160405112215/http://www.ew.com/article/2015/07/16/emma-stone-aloha-whitewashing |archivedate=April 5, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Despite the criticism, she was nominated for Choice Movie Actress \u2013 Comedy at the [[2015 Teen Choice Awards]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Teen Choice Awards 2015 Winners: Full List |url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/teen-choice-awards-winners-2015-full-list-1201571268/ |accessdate=April 7, 2016 |work=Variety |date=August 16, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160110215656/http://variety.com/2015/tv/news/teen-choice-awards-winners-2015-full-list-1201571268/ |archivedate=January 10, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Stone also appeared in the music video for [[Win Butler|Win Butler's]] single \"Anna\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Geslani |first1=Michael |title=Emma Stone is absolutely magnetic in Will Butler's \"Anna\" video \u2014 watch |url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2015/10/emma-stone-is-absolutely-magnetic-in-will-butlers-anna-video-watch/ |website=Consequence of Sound |accessdate=11 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161227161413/http://consequenceofsound.net/2015/10/emma-stone-is-absolutely-magnetic-in-will-butlers-anna-video-watch/ |archive-date=December 27, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===''La La Land'' and beyond (2016\u2013present)===\nDuring her ''Cabaret'' show, Stone met director [[Damien Chazelle]], who, impressed with her performance, cast her in his musical comedy-drama ''[[La La Land (film)|La La Land]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://deadline.com/2016/11/emma-stone-mel-gibson-la-la-land-hacksaw-ridge-lionsgate-contenders-1201847486/ |title= Emma Stone Reveals Unorthodox 'La La Land' Audition; Mel Gibson on 'Hacksaw Ridge' Inspiration&nbsp;\u2013 The Contenders |first= Matthew |last= Grobar |website= Deadline Hollywood |date= November 5, 2016 |accessdate= February 24, 2018 |archive-url= https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http://deadline.com/2016/11/emma-stone-mel-gibson-la-la-land-hacksaw-ridge-lionsgate-contenders-1201847486/&date=2018-06-22 |archive-date= June 22, 2018 |url-status= live }}</ref> The project, which marked her third collaboration with Gosling, featured Stone as Mia Dolan, an aspiring actress living in Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2016/03/07/ryan-gosling-emma-stone-la-la-land-release-date/ |title=Ryan Gosling, Emma Stone musical La La Land pushed to December |first=Devan |last=Coggan |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=March 7, 2016 |accessdate=April 7, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160407094609/http://www.ew.com/article/2016/03/07/ryan-gosling-emma-stone-la-la-land-release-date |archivedate=April 7, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Stone borrowed several real-life experiences for her character, and in preparation, watched ''[[The Umbrellas of Cherbourg]]'' and films of [[Fred Astaire and Ginger Rogers]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=McGovern |first1=Joe |title='La La Director' Director On the 'Timeless Glamour' of Ryan Gosling & Emma Stone |url=https://www.ew.com/article/2016/08/30/ryan-gosling-emma-stone-la-la-land |accessdate=November 7, 2016 |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=August 30, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161119070241/http://www.ew.com/article/2016/08/30/ryan-gosling-emma-stone-la-la-land |archivedate=November 19, 2016 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Alter, Ethan |title=Emma Stone on Reteaming With Ryan Gosling in 'La La Land' and Her New Appreciation of Los Angeles |url=https://www.yahoo.com/movies/emma-stone-on-reteaming-with-ryan-gosling-in-la-la-land-and-her-new-appreciation-of-los-angeles-120240431.html |publisher=[[Yahoo! Movies]] |date=September 16, 2016 |accessdate=November 7, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161110023416/https://www.yahoo.com/movies/emma-stone-on-reteaming-with-ryan-gosling-in-la-la-land-and-her-new-appreciation-of-los-angeles-120240431.html |archivedate=November 10, 2016 |df= }}</ref> For the [[La La Land (soundtrack)|musical's soundtrack]], she recorded six songs.{{efn|\"[[Another Day of Sun]]\", \"[[City of Stars]]\", \"Someone in the Crowd\", \"A Lovely Night\", \"[[Audition (The Fools Who Dream)]]\" and \"City of Stars (Humming)\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Desta |first1=Yohana |title=Emma Stone Shows Off Her Delicate Singing Voice in Soaring La La Land Trailer |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2016/08/emma-stone-singing-la-la-land |accessdate=January 12, 2017 |work=Vanity Fair |date=August 23, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161028083421/http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2016/08/emma-stone-singing-la-la-land |archivedate=October 28, 2016 |df= }}</ref>}} ''La La Land'' served as the opening film at the 2016 Venice Film Festival, and received highly positive reviews.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Vivarelli |first1=Nick |title=Damien Chazelle's 'La La Land' to Open Venice Film Festival in Competition |url=https://variety.com/2016/film/festivals/damien-chazelles-la-la-land-to-open-venice-film-festival-in-competition-1201797771/ |accessdate=September 3, 2016 |date=June 17, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160908012048/http://variety.com/2016/film/festivals/damien-chazelles-la-la-land-to-open-venice-film-festival-in-competition-1201797771/ |archivedate=September 8, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Besides being Stone's highest-rated film on the review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]],<ref name=\"rotten\">{{cite web|title=Emma Stone |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/celebrity/770683296 |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=July 30, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160910050042/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/celebrity/770683296 |archivedate=September 10, 2016 |df= }}</ref> the film was successful at the box office, earning over $440 million against its $30 million budget.<ref>{{cite web|title=La La Land (2016) |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=lalaland.htm |publisher=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=March 28, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170128222455/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=lalaland.htm |archivedate=January 28, 2017 |df= }}</ref> Writing for ''[[The Guardian]]'', [[Peter Bradshaw]] reviewed, \"Stone has never been better: superbly smart, witty, vulnerable, her huge doe eyes radiating intelligence even, or especially, when they are filling with tears.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bradshaw |first1=Peter |title=La La Land review \u2013 Gosling and Stone sparkle in a gorgeous musical romance |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/jan/12/la-la-land-review-ryan-gosling-emma-stone-musical-romance-movie |accessdate=January 12, 2017 |work=The Guardian |date=January 12, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170112204822/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/jan/12/la-la-land-review-ryan-gosling-emma-stone-musical-romance-movie |archivedate=January 12, 2017 |df= }}</ref> Stone received an [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Academy]], [[BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Leading Role|BAFTA]], [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Comedy or Musical|Golden Globe]] and a [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Leading Role|SAG]] Award for Best Actress.<ref name=\"la la\">{{citation|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/awards/7647883/golden-globes-2017-winners-list |work=Billboard |date=January 8, 2017 |accessdate=January 8, 2017 |title=Here Is the 2017 Golden Globes Winners List |first=Taylor |last=Weatherby |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170109184352/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/awards/7647883/golden-globes-2017-winners-list |archivedate=January 9, 2017 |df= }}<br>{{cite news|title=Baftas 2017: full list of winners |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/feb/12/baftas-2017-film-full-list-of-winners |accessdate=February 12, 2017 |work=The Guardian |date=February 12, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170212225353/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/feb/12/baftas-2017-film-full-list-of-winners |archivedate=February 12, 2017 |df= }}<br>{{cite news|title=Oscar winners 2017: the full list updated live |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/feb/27/oscar-winners-2017-the-full-list-academy-awards |work=The Guardian |date=February 26, 2017 |accessdate=February 27, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170227032811/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/feb/27/oscar-winners-2017-the-full-list-academy-awards |archivedate=February 27, 2017 |df= }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Emma Stone (30498079137) (cropped).jpg|thumb|Stone at an event for ''[[Maniac (miniseries)|Maniac]]'' in 2018]]\n\nStone's sole film release of 2017 was the sports drama ''[[Battle of the Sexes (2017 film)|Battle of the Sexes]]'', based on the 1973 [[Battle of the Sexes (tennis)|eponymous match]] between tennis players [[Billie Jean King]] (Stone) and [[Bobby Riggs]] (Steve Carell). In preparation, Stone met with King, watched old footage and interviews of her, trained with a dialect coach to speak in King's accent, and drank high-calorie protein shakes to gain {{convert|15|lb}}.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Coggan|first1=Devan|title=Emma Stone on Preparing to Play Billie Jean King: 'I Was a Real Creep'|url=https://ew.com/movies/2017/08/15/emma-stone-battle-of-the-sexes-interview/|accessdate=September 20, 2017|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=August 15, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170921000701/http://ew.com/movies/2017/08/15/emma-stone-battle-of-the-sexes-interview/|archivedate=September 21, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Randone|first1=Amanda|title=How Emma Stone Gained 15 Pounds for Battle of the Sexes|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/881311/how-emma-stone-gained-15-pounds-for-battle-of-the-sexes|publisher=E!|accessdate=September 20, 2017|date=September 19, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170919205622/http://www.eonline.com/news/881311/how-emma-stone-gained-15-pounds-for-battle-of-the-sexes|archivedate=September 19, 2017}}</ref> The film premiered to positive reviews at the [[2017 Toronto International Film Festival]], and certain critics considered Stone's performance to be the best of her career.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Giles|first1=Jeff|title=American Made Is Certified Fresh|url=https://editorial.rottentomatoes.com/article/american-made-is-certified-fresh/|publisher=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=December 20, 2017|date=September 28, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171126190012/https://editorial.rottentomatoes.com/article/american-made-is-certified-fresh/|archivedate=November 26, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Benjamin Lee of ''The Guardian'' praised her for playing against type, and credited her for being \"strong\" and \"convincing\" in the part.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lee|first1=Benjamin|title=Battle of the Sexes review \u2013 Emma Stone serves up rousing, timely tennis drama|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/sep/11/battle-of-the-sexes-review-toronto-film-festival-tiff|accessdate=September 20, 2017|work=The Guardian|date=September 11, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170919185458/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/sep/11/battle-of-the-sexes-review-toronto-film-festival-tiff|archivedate=September 19, 2017}}</ref> Even so, the film earned less than its $25 million budget.<ref>{{cite news|author=Ende, Maura|title='Battle of the Sexes' has important messages about prejudice, sexuality|url=https://buffalonews.com/2017/10/11/battle-sexes-important-messages-prejudice-sexuality/|work=[[The Buffalo News]]|date=October 11, 2017|accessdate=September 20, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920084021/https://buffalonews.com/2017/10/11/battle-sexes-important-messages-prejudice-sexuality/|archive-date=September 20, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Stone received her fourth Golden Globe nomination for it, and attended the ceremony with King.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Pett |first1=Stephanie |title=Emma Stone Brings Billie Jean King, Who she Played in Battle of the Sexes, as Globes Date |url=https://people.com/movies/golden-globes-2018-emma-stone-brings-billie-jean-king/ |accessdate=September 8, 2018 |magazine=People |date=January 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180908164839/https://people.com/movies/golden-globes-2018-emma-stone-brings-billie-jean-king/ |archive-date=September 8, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Stone and [[Rachel Weisz]] starred as [[Abigail Masham]] and [[Sarah Churchill, Duchess of Marlborough|Sarah Churchill]], two cousins fighting for the affection of [[Anne, Queen of Great Britain|Queen Anne]] ([[Olivia Colman]]), in [[Yorgos Lanthimos]]'s historical comedy-drama ''[[The Favourite (film)|The Favourite]]''. Stone found it challenging being an American among a British cast, and had difficulty in mastering the accent.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Galloway |first1=Stephen |title=Telluride: Emma Stone Reveals Her Acting Breaking Points |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/emma-stones-reveals-acting-breaking-points-1139241 |accessdate=September 6, 2018 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=September 2, 2018 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904190438/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/emma-stones-reveals-acting-breaking-points-1139241 |archive-date=September 4, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The film premiered at the [[75th Venice International Film Festival]] in August.<ref>{{cite magazine |first=Ariston |last=Anderson |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/venice-film-festival-unveils-full-lineup-1129426 |title=Venice to Kick Off Awards Season With New Films From Coen Brothers, Luca Guadagnino and Alfonso Cuaron |magazine=The Hollywood Reporter |date=July 25, 2018 |accessdate=September 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180725121213/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/venice-film-festival-unveils-full-lineup-1129426 |archive-date=July 25, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Michael Nordine of [[IndieWire]] praised Stone for taking on a bold role after ''La La Land'', and termed the three leading ladies \"a majestic triumvirate in a period piece that's as tragic as it is hilarious.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Nordine |first1=Michael |title='The Favourite' Review: Yorgos Lanthimos' Royal Drama Is His Crowning Achievement \u2014 Venice |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2018/08/the-favourite-review-yorgos-lanthimos-emma-stone-venice-1201998762/ |publisher=IndieWire |accessdate=September 7, 2018 |date=August 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180907221353/https://www.indiewire.com/2018/08/the-favourite-review-yorgos-lanthimos-emma-stone-venice-1201998762/ |archive-date=September 7, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> For ''The Favourite'', Stone received her fifth Golden Globe nomination and third Oscar nomination.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/golden-globe-nominations-2019-1203082075/|title=Golden Globe Nominations: Complete List|date=December 6, 2018|work=Variety|access-date=December 6, 2018|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/74T7WuEQQ?url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/golden-globe-nominations-2019-1203082075/|archive-date=December 6, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/oscar-nominations-2019-complete-list-nominees-1172407|title=Oscars: Nominations List|date=January 22, 2019|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=January 22, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190122160706/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/oscar-nominations-2019-complete-list-nominees-1172407|archive-date=January 22, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> That September, she featured in and served as an executive producer for the [[Netflix]] dark comedy miniseries ''[[Maniac (miniseries)|Maniac]]'', co-starring Jonah Hill and directed by [[Cary Fukunaga]]. Stone and Hill played two strangers, Annie Landsberg and Owen Milgrim, whose lives are transformed due to a mysterious pharmaceutical trial. An admirer of Fukunaga's work, Stone agreed to the project without reading the script.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Jeffery |first1=Morgan |title=Emma Stone opens up about Maniac rewrites |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/ustv/news/a866529/emma-stone-maniac-netflix-interview/ |website=Digital Spy |accessdate=September 21, 2018 |language=en |date=September 21, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180921191143/http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/ustv/news/a866529/emma-stone-maniac-netflix-interview/ |archive-date=September 21, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Lucy Mangan]] of ''The Guardian'' praised Stone and Hill for playing against type and for delivering career-best performances;<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mangan |first1=Lucy |title=Maniac review \u2013 Jonah Hill and Emma Stone hit career highs in NYC dystopia |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2018/sep/21/maniac-review-jonah-hill-emma-stone-netflix-cary-fukunaga |accessdate=September 21, 2018 |work=The Guardian |date=September 21, 2018 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180921075620/https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2018/sep/21/maniac-review-jonah-hill-emma-stone-netflix-cary-fukunaga |archive-date=September 21, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Judy Berman of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' was similarly impressed with their growth as actors since ''Superbad'' and took note of the complexity in their performances.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Berman |first1=Judy |title=Maniac Is the Most Exciting Netflix Drama Since Stranger Things |url=http://time.com/5400995/maniac-netflix-review-emma-stone-jonah-hill/ |accessdate=September 21, 2018 |magazine=Time |date=September 20, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180921123618/http://time.com/5400995/maniac-netflix-review-emma-stone-jonah-hill/ |archive-date=September 21, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the same year, Stone appeared alongside [[Paul McCartney]] in a music video for his song \"[[Who Cares (Paul McCartney song)|Who Cares]]\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Grow |first1=Kory |title=See Paul McCartney, Emma Stone Shrug Off Bullies in 'Who Cares' Video |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/see-paul-mccartney-emma-stone-shrug-off-bullies-in-who-cares-video-771060/ |work=Rolling Stone |date=December 19, 2018 |accessdate=March 11, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190605062109/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/see-paul-mccartney-emma-stone-shrug-off-bullies-in-who-cares-video-771060/ |archive-date=June 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nStone reprised her role of Wichita in ''[[Zombieland: Double Tap]]'' (2019), which received mixed reviews and grossed $122 million worldwide.<ref>{{cite web |title= Zombieland: Double Tap (2019) |website= Rotten Tomatoes |url= https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/zombieland_double_tap/ |accessdate= November 14, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url= https://www.boxofficemojo.com/title/tt1560220/ |title= Zombieland: Double Tap (2019) |website= Box Office Mojo |access-date=January 17, 2020}}</ref> She will next star in ''[[Cruella (film)|Cruella]]'', a live-action spin-off of ''[[One Hundred and One Dalmatians]]'', in which she will portray [[Cruella de Vil]] (originally played by [[Glenn Close]] in the [[101 Dalmatians (1996 film)|1996 adaptation]]).<ref>{{cite web|last1=D'Alessandro |first1=Anthony |title=Disney Puts A Slew Of Dates On Hold For 'Jungle Book 2', 'Maleficent 2', 'Dumbo', 'Cruella' & More |url=https://deadline.com/2016/04/disney-fairy-tale-live-action-films-release-dates-jungle-book-2-cruella-dumbo-1201743988/ |accessdate=May 14, 2016 |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=April 25, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160513151039/http://deadline.com/2016/04/disney-fairy-tale-live-action-films-release-dates-jungle-book-2-cruella-dumbo-1201743988/ |archivedate=May 13, 2016 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Fleming Jr.|first1=Mike|title=Craig Gillespie In Talks To Direct Emma Stone In 'Cruella'|url=https://deadline.com/2018/12/emma-stone-craig-gillespie-cruella-director-live-action-1202514016/|accessdate=December 5, 2018|website=Deadline.com|date=December 4, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190606173711/https://deadline.com/2018/12/emma-stone-craig-gillespie-cruella-director-live-action-1202514016/|archive-date=June 6, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> She is also set to return as the voice of Eep in the sequel to ''The Croods'' and to star in the drama ''Love May Fail'', based on [[Matthew Quick]]'s 2015 novel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/11/emma-stone-love-may-fail-tristar-matthew-quick-silver-linings-playbook-1201627457/ |title=Emma Stone Boarding 'Love May Fail' As Hannah Minghella Brings Matthew Quick Book To TriStar |first=Mike, Jr. |last=Flemming |date=November 17, 2015 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=November 19, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151119045022/http://deadline.com/2015/11/emma-stone-love-may-fail-tristar-matthew-quick-silver-linings-playbook-1201627457/ |archivedate=November 19, 2015 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Kroll |first1=Kroll |title='Croods 2,' Revived as Animated Sequel, and Jason Blum's 'Spooky Jack' Get Release Dates |url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/croods-2-spooky-jack-release-dates-1202563635/ |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |website=Variety.com |date=September 19, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190604034547/https://variety.com/2017/film/news/croods-2-spooky-jack-release-dates-1202563635/ |archive-date=June 4, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|title='Sing 2' To Croon Summer 2021; 'The Croods 2' Moves To Holiday Season 2020|url=https://deadline.com/2019/04/sing-2-croods-2-release-date-changes-1202594951/|accessdate=July 5, 2019|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=April 12, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190828024514/https://deadline.com/2019/04/sing-2-croods-2-release-date-changes-1202594951/|archive-date=August 28, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nStone moved from Los Angeles to [[Greenwich Village]], New York City, in 2009.<ref name=\"Blackbook2009\">{{cite news|last=Barna|first=Ben|date=October 2, 2009|url=http://www.blackbookmag.com/article/zombielands-emma-stone-dreams-of-snl-and-mexican-food/11382|title='Zombieland's' Emma Stone Dreams of SNL and Mexican Food|work=[[BlackBook]] magazine|accessdate=October 2, 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111022221855/http://www.blackbookmag.com/article/zombielands-emma-stone-dreams-of-snl-and-mexican-food/11382|archivedate=October 22, 2011}}</ref> In 2016, she moved back to Los Angeles.<ref name=\"WSJ-IrrationalMan-2015\" /> Despite frequent media coverage, the actress has refused to speak about her private life. Concerned with living a \"normal\" life, she has said that she finds little value in media attention.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Malik |first1=Sonam |title=SAG Awards: 'The Amazing Spider-Man' Actress Emma Stone Spotted without Beau Andrew Garfield |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/sag-awards-amazing-spider-man-actress-emma-stone-spotted-without-beau-andrew-garfield-621647 |accessdate=March 16, 2016 |work=[[International Business Times]] |date=January 27, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160323003909/http://www.ibtimes.co.in/sag-awards-amazing-spider-man-actress-emma-stone-spotted-without-beau-andrew-garfield-621647 |archivedate=March 23, 2016 |df= }}</ref> She has expressed her fondness for her profession,<ref name=\"WSJ-IrrationalMan-2015\" /> and has cited actress [[Diane Keaton]] as an influence, who is (in Stone's words) \"one of the most covered-up actresses of all time\". She has also named actress and singer-songwriter [[Marion Cotillard]] as one of her inspirations.<ref name=\"vanityfair1\" />\n\n[[File:Emma Stone, Andrew Garfield 2014 (cropped).jpg|thumb|Stone with [[Andrew Garfield]] at ''[[The Amazing Spider-Man 2]]'' premiere in Sydney, 2014]]\n\nStone has a close relationship with her family.<ref name=\"vanityfair1\" /> She says: \"I am blessed with a great family and great people around me that would be able to kick me in the shins if I ever for one minute got lost up in the clouds. I've been really lucky in that sense.\"<ref name=\"Ask quote\">{{cite web|title=Emma Stone|url=http://www.askmen.com/celebs/women/celeb_profiles_actress_100/111_emma_stone.html|publisher=[[AskMen]]|accessdate=April 8, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090602071935/http://www.askmen.com/celebs/women/celeb_profiles_actress_100/111_emma_stone.html|archivedate=June 2, 2009}}</ref> During the production of ''The Amazing Spider-Man'' in 2010, Stone dated co-star [[Andrew Garfield]].<ref name=\"Emma Stone\">{{cite press release| url= http://www.sonypictures.com/corp/press_releases/2010/10_10/10052010_estone.html|title=Spider-Man Gets His Girl: Emma Stone To Play Female Lead|publisher=[[Sony Pictures]]|date=October 5, 2010|accessdate=March 19, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101009111726/http://www.sonypictures.com/corp/press_releases/2010/10_10/10052010_estone.html|archivedate=October 9, 2010}}</ref> Their relationship was reported in the media, with various speculations. The couple refused to talk about it publicly, though they made several appearances together. In 2014, on an occasion in New York, Stone and Garfield encouraged [[paparazzi]] to visit websites that spread awareness of causes such as [[autism]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Boy with Autism Thanks Emma Stone for Spreading Awareness |url=https://www.autismspeaks.org/news/news-item/boy-autism-thanks-emma-stone-spreading-awareness |publisher=[[Autism Speaks]] |accessdate=March 20, 2016 |date=June 20, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160329231255/https://www.autismspeaks.org/news/news-item/boy-autism-thanks-emma-stone-spreading-awareness |archivedate=March 29, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In 2015, they were reported to have broken up.<ref>{{cite news|title=Emma Stone and Andrew Garfield Have Reportedly Split For Good |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2015/10/emma-stone-andrew-garfield-break-up |accessdate=February 20, 2016 |work=Vanity Fair |date=October 27, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160302044751/http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2015/10/emma-stone-andrew-garfield-break-up |archivedate=March 2, 2016 |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"LA Times\">{{cite news|last1=Saad |first1=Nardine |title=Emma Stone, Andrew Garfield split 'a couple of months ago,' reports say |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/gossip/la-et-mg-emma-stone-andrew-garfield-split-20151027-story.html |date=October 28, 2015 |accessdate=February 20, 2016 |work=Los Angeles Times |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160220103816/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/gossip/la-et-mg-emma-stone-andrew-garfield-split-20151027-story.html |archivedate=February 20, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Since 2017, Stone has been in a romantic relationship with ''Saturday Night Live'' segment director [[Dave McCary]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Juneau |first1=Jen |title=He's Her Favourite! Emma Stone and Boyfriend Dave McCary Make Rare Appearance at SAG Awards |url=https://people.com/movies/sag-awards-2019-emma-stone-dave-mccary-rare-appearance/ |website=People |accessdate=17 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417115133/https://people.com/movies/sag-awards-2019-emma-stone-dave-mccary-rare-appearance/ |archive-date=April 17, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> They became engaged in December 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/movies/emma-stone-engaged-dave-mccary/|title=Emma Stone Engaged to SNL Writer Dave McCary After 2 Years of Dating|work=People|author=Ashley Boucher|date=December 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Stone, she suffers from [[asthma]], which she discovered after having difficulty breathing while filming ''Easy A''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Warner |first1=Kara |title=Emma Stone Recalls Asthma Attack During 'Easy A' Fake-Sex Scenes |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1647971/emma-stone-recalls-asthma-attack-during-easy-a-fake-sex-scenes/ |accessdate=March 16, 2016 |publisher=MTV News |date=September 15, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408212317/http://www.mtv.com/news/1647971/emma-stone-recalls-asthma-attack-during-easy-a-fake-sex-scenes/ |archivedate=April 8, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Her mother was diagnosed with [[triple-negative breast cancer]] and was cured in 2008.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Masica |first1=Kristen |title=Emma Stone: My Mom's Cancer Diagnosis 'Was Terrifying' |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20702530,00.html |accessdate=April 9, 2016 |work=People |date=May 22, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160513222906/http://www.people.com/people/article/0%2C%2C20702530%2C00.html |archivedate=May 13, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Stone and her mother celebrated by getting tattoos of birds' feet, designed by [[Paul McCartney]], a reference to [[the Beatles]]' \"[[Blackbird (Beatles song)|Blackbird]]\", which is a song she and her mother love.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Abrams |first1=Natalie |title=Emma Stone Has Paul McCartney Design Mother-Daughter Tattoo |url=https://www.tvguide.com/news/emma-stone-tattoo-1024493/ |accessdate=March 20, 2016 |work=TV Guide |date=October 18, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401225622/http://www.tvguide.com/news/emma-stone-tattoo-1024493/ |archivedate=April 1, 2016 |df= }}</ref> She appeared in a [[Revlon]] campaign that promoted breast cancer awareness.<ref name=\"eonline\">{{cite web|last1=Serfe |first1=Gina |title=Emma Stone Poses With Breast Cancer Survivor Mom in New Awareness Campaign |url=http://www.eonline.com/news/345364/emma-stone-poses-with-breast-cancer-survivor-mom-in-new-awareness-campaign |publisher=E! |accessdate=March 20, 2016 |date=September 12, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160508104714/http://www.eonline.com/news/345364/emma-stone-poses-with-breast-cancer-survivor-mom-in-new-awareness-campaign |archivedate=May 8, 2016 |df= }}</ref> In 2011, the actress featured in a collaborative video between ''[[Star Wars (film series)|Star Wars]]'' and [[Stand Up to Cancer]], which aimed to raise funds for cancer research.<ref>{{cite news|title='Star Wars' stands up to cancer, with the help of Andy Samberg, Emma Stone, Seth Rogen, and more! \u2013 Exclusive Video |url=https://www.ew.com/article/2011/09/15/star-wars-stand-up-to-cancer-exclusive-video |accessdate=March 20, 2016 |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=September 15, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160309090928/http://www.ew.com/article/2011/09/15/star-wars-stand-up-to-cancer-exclusive-video |archivedate=March 9, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Two years later, she attended an event by [[Gilda's Club]], an organization working for a similar purpose.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mcnally|first1=Kelby|title=Emma Stone goes au-naturel for charity event|url=http://www.express.co.uk/celebrity-news/400130/Emma-Stone-goes-au-naturel-for-charity-event|accessdate=March 20, 2016|work=[[Daily Express]]|date=May 16, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612162851/https://www.express.co.uk/celebrity-news/400130/Emma-Stone-goes-au-naturel-for-charity-event|archive-date=June 12, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> From 2012 to 2014, she hosted the [[Entertainment Industry Foundation]]'s Revlon Run/Walk, which helps fight women's cancer.<ref>{{cite web|title=Join the Fight Against Cancer: Entertainment Industry Foundation's Revlon Run/Walk For Women Announces 2014 Hosts for Annual Event|url=http://www.eifoundation.org/press-room/join-fight-against-cancer-entertainment-industry-foundations-revlon-runwalk-women-announc/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160329093709/http://www.eifoundation.org/press-room/join-fight-against-cancer-entertainment-industry-foundations-revlon-runwalk-women-announc/|archivedate=March 29, 2016|publisher=[[Entertainment Industry Foundation]]|accessdate=April 24, 2016|date=March 26, 2014}}</ref>\n\nStone, alongside three other celebrities, was present at the 2012 [[Nickelodeon HALO Awards]], a television special that profiled five teenagers who are \"Helping And Leading Others\" (HALO).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/tyra-banks-justin-bieber-josh-duhamel-and-emma-stone-honor-four-teens-for-their-commitment-to-service-in-fourth-annual-teennick-halo-awards-176414821.html |title=Tyra Banks, Justin Bieber, Josh Duhamel and Emma Stone Honor Four Teens for Their Commitment to Service in Fourth Annual TeenNick HALO Awards |date=October 30, 2012 |accessdate=March 20, 2016 |publisher=[[PR Newswire]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160403003834/http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/tyra-banks-justin-bieber-josh-duhamel-and-emma-stone-honor-four-teens-for-their-commitment-to-service-in-fourth-annual-teennick-halo-awards-176414821.html |archivedate=April 3, 2016 |df= }}</ref> She attended the 2014 [[Earth Hour]], a worldwide movement for the planet organized by the [[World Wide Fund for Nature]].<ref>{{cite web|title=2014 Celebrates the Biggest Earth Hour in History |url=https://www.earthhour.org/2014-celebrates-the-biggest-earth-hour-history |publisher=[[Earth Hour]] |accessdate=March 20, 2016 |date=March 30, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401002858/https://www.earthhour.org/2014-celebrates-the-biggest-earth-hour-history |archivedate=April 1, 2016 |df= }}</ref> In 2015, she was part of a fundraising event in support of the [[Motion Picture & Television Fund]], which helps people in the television and film industry with limited or no resources.<ref>{{cite news|title=2015 MPTF 'Night Before' Host Committee Members George Clooney, Eddie Redmayne, Reese Witherspoon, And More Attend 13th Annual Fundraiser in Support of MPTF |url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/2015-mptf-night-before-host-committee-members-george-clooney-eddie-redmayne-reese-witherspoon-and-more-attend-13th-annual-fundraiser-in-support-of-mptf-300039424.html |accessdate=March 20, 2016 |publisher=PR Newswire |date=February 22, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160402165300/http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/2015-mptf-night-before-host-committee-members-george-clooney-eddie-redmayne-reese-witherspoon-and-more-attend-13th-annual-fundraiser-in-support-of-mptf-300039424.html |archivedate=April 2, 2016 |df= }}</ref> In 2018, she collaborated with 300 women in Hollywood to set up the [[Time's Up (movement)|Time's Up]] initiative to protect women from harassment and discrimination.<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=McCarthy|first1=Lauren|title=Selena Gomez, Reese Witherspoon, And Emma Stone Among 300 Women In Hollywood to Sign Anti-Harassment Action Plan|url=https://www.wmagazine.com/story/times-up-open-letter-sexual-harassment-selena-gomez-reese-witherspoon|accessdate=January 4, 2018|magazine=W|date=January 1, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180103211443/https://www.wmagazine.com/story/times-up-open-letter-sexual-harassment-selena-gomez-reese-witherspoon|archivedate=January 3, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Media image==\n[[File:Emma Stone 2011 2.jpg|thumb|upright=0.9|left|Stone at the 2011 [[San Diego Comic-Con International]]. Her hair, eyes, and husky voice have been described as her trademarks by the media.<ref name=\"trade1\"/><ref name=\"trade\"/>]]\nSeveral media publications consider Stone one of her generation's most talented actresses.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/02/kristen-stewart-kelly-reichardt-project-1201383230/ |title=Kristen Stewart Joins Untitled Kelly Reichardt Project |last=Busch |first=Anita |date=February 28, 2015 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |language= |access-date=May 5, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160803172808/http://deadline.com/2015/02/kristen-stewart-kelly-reichardt-project-1201383230/ |archivedate=August 3, 2016 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/emma-stone-to-star-in-cameron-crowes-next-film-reworked-version-of-ben-stiller-reese-witherspoon-project-deep-tiki-20120730 |title=Emma Stone To Star In Cameron Crowe's Next Film, A Reworked Version Of 'Deep Tiki' |last=Lyttelton |first=Oliver |date=July 30, 2012 |website= |publisher=Indiewire |access-date=May 5, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140727073213/http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/emma-stone-to-star-in-cameron-crowes-next-film-reworked-version-of-ben-stiller-reese-witherspoon-project-deep-tiki-20120730 |archivedate=July 27, 2014 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Fitzpatrick |first1=Hayley |title=Emma Stone Is Unrecognizable in a Pixie Wig on the Cover of 'Vogue' |url=https://www.yahoo.com/style/emma-stone-wears-pixie-wig-and-discusses-the-wage-gap-in-hollywood-in-november-vogue-174401654.html |publisher=Yahoo! |accessdate=February 1, 2017 |date=October 14, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170109211904/https://www.yahoo.com/style/emma-stone-wears-pixie-wig-and-discusses-the-wage-gap-in-hollywood-in-november-vogue-174401654.html |archivedate=January 9, 2017 |df= }}</ref> Commenting on her performance in ''The Help'', Kirk Honeycutt of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' called her \"one of our very best young actresses\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/helps-emma-stone-what-critics-221417 |title='The Help's' Emma Stone: What Critics Say of Her Performance |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=August 10, 2011 |accessdate=March 29, 2016 |author=Powers, Lindsay |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160413150941/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/helps-emma-stone-what-critics-221417 |archivedate=April 13, 2016 |df= }}</ref> She is known for starring both in high-profile, mainstream productions and in low-budget independent films. ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''{{'s}} Daniel D'Addario describes the latter as \"substantive risk\" and adds that taking on a role in them provides her an opportunity to \"try something new and to get credibility\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=D'Addario |first1=Daniel |title=Here's Why Emma Stone's Artistic Alliance With Woody Allen Is So Complicated |url=http://time.com/3960218/emma-stone-woody-allen-joaquin-phoenix-irrational-man/ |accessdate=April 7, 2016 |work=Time |date=July 17, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160405174444/http://time.com/3960218/emma-stone-woody-allen-joaquin-phoenix-irrational-man/ |archivedate=April 5, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Analyzing her on-screen persona, Jessica Kiang of [[Indiewire]] noted that Stone \"usually [plays] the approachable, down-to-earth, girl-next-door type, [and] in person she demonstrates many of those qualities too, along with an absolute refusal to take herself too seriously.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kiang |first1=Jessica |title=Interview: Emma Stone Talks Comedy, 'The Croods' And Cameron Crowe; Scores Off The Charts On Likability |url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/berlin-interview-emma-stone-talks-comedy-the-croods-and-cameron-crowe-scores-off-the-charts-on-likability-20130224 |publisher=[[Indiewire]] |accessdate=April 7, 2015 |date=February 24, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130518110414/http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/berlin-interview-emma-stone-talks-comedy-the-croods-and-cameron-crowe-scores-off-the-charts-on-likability-20130224 |archivedate=May 18, 2013 |df= }}</ref>\n\nAs her career in Hollywood films has developed, Stone has become a successful and popular actress.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2012/01/05/emma-stone-little-white-corvette |title=Emma Stone 'acts' like a dude \u2013 and it's making her Hollywood's hottest young actress |date=January 5, 2012 |accessdate=April 6, 2016 |work=Entertainment Weekly |author=Labrecque, Jeff |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151108151844/http://www.ew.com/article/2012/01/05/emma-stone-little-white-corvette |archivedate=November 8, 2015 |df= }}</ref> In 2008, she topped ''[[Saturday Night Magazine (U.S.)|Saturday Night Magazine]]''{{'s}} Top 20 Rising Stars Under 30 and was included in a similar list compiled by [[Moviefone]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Top 20 Rising Stars Under 30|url=http://www.snmag.com/MAGAZINE/Features/Top-20-Rising-Stars-Under-30.html|accessdate=April 8, 2016|work=[[Saturday Night Magazine (U.S.)|Saturday Night Magazine]]|date=July 29, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080924181516/http://www.snmag.com/MAGAZINE/Features/Top-20-Rising-Stars-Under-30.html|archivedate=September 24, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=MovieFone's 25 Hottest Young Stars Under 25 |url=http://www.accesshollywood.com/galleries/moviefones-25-hottest-young-stars-under-25-1561/#14 |work=Access Hollywood |accessdate=April 8, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160412072235/http://www.accesshollywood.com/galleries/moviefones-25-hottest-young-stars-under-25-1561/ |archivedate=April 12, 2016 |df= }}</ref> [[LoveFilm]] placed her on their list of 2010 Top 20 Actresses Under 30, and her performance in ''Easy A'' was included in ''Time''{{'s}} Top 10 Everything of 2010.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Corliss |first1=Richard |title=The Top 10 Everything of 2010 |url=http://content.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,2035319_2035307_2032774,00.html |accessdate=March 27, 2016 |work=Time |date=December 9, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160311134912/http://content.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0%2C28804%2C2035319_2035307_2032774%2C00.html |archivedate=March 11, 2016 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=2010 Top 20 Actresses Under 30|url=http://www.lovefilm.com/features/detail.html?section_name=newsletter&editorial_id=24704|publisher=[[LoveFilm]]|accessdate=April 8, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110702120342/http://www.lovefilm.com/features/detail.html?section_name=newsletter&editorial_id=24704|archivedate=July 2, 2011}}</ref> She appeared in the 2013 [[Celebrity 100]], a compilation of the 100 most powerful people in the world, as selected annually by ''[[Forbes (magazine)|Forbes]]''. The magazine reported that she had earned $16 million from June 2012 to June 2013.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pomerantz |first1=Dorothy |title=Celebrity 100 Sneak Peek: Emma Stone Makes Our List For The First Time |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/dorothypomerantz/2013/06/25/celebrity-100-sneak-peek-emma-stone-makes-our-list-for-the-first-time/#13daeb4b2681 |accessdate=April 7, 2016 |work=[[Forbes (magazine)|Forbes]] |date=June 25, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422015311/http://www.forbes.com/sites/dorothypomerantz/2013/06/25/celebrity-100-sneak-peek-emma-stone-makes-our-list-for-the-first-time/ |archivedate=April 22, 2016 |df= }}</ref> That same year, she was ranked first in the magazine's Top 10 Best Value Stars.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Child |first1=Ben |title=Emma Stone tops Forbes list of 'best value' Hollywood stars |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2013/dec/24/emma-stone-best-value-film-star-investment-return |accessdate=April 8, 2016 |work=The Guardian |date=December 24, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160417141613/http://www.theguardian.com/film/2013/dec/24/emma-stone-best-value-film-star-investment-return |archivedate=April 17, 2016 |df= }}</ref> In 2015, ''Forbes'' published that she had become one of the highest-paid actresses with earnings of $6.5 million.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Robehmed |first1=Natalie |title=The World's Highest-Paid Actresses 2015: Jennifer Lawrence Leads With 52 Million |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/natalierobehmed/2015/08/20/the-worlds-highest-paid-actresses-2015-jennifer-lawrence-leads-with-52-million/#5e9aa1c23820 |accessdate=April 7, 2016 |work=Forbes |date=August 21, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160405063521/http://www.forbes.com/sites/natalierobehmed/2015/08/20/the-worlds-highest-paid-actresses-2015-jennifer-lawrence-leads-with-52-million/ |archivedate=April 5, 2016 |df= }}</ref> The magazine would rank her as the world's highest-paid actress two years later with yearly earnings of $26 million.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Robehmed|first1=Natalie|title=The World's Highest-Paid Actresses 2017: Emma Stone Leads With $26 Million|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/natalierobehmed/2017/08/16/the-worlds-highest-paid-actresses-2017-emma-stone-leads-with-26-million/#641f066911e6|accessdate=August 17, 2017|work=Forbes|date=August 16, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170817044520/https://www.forbes.com/sites/natalierobehmed/2017/08/16/the-worlds-highest-paid-actresses-2017-emma-stone-leads-with-26-million/#641f066911e6|archivedate=August 17, 2017}}</ref> In 2017, she was featured by ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' as one of the [[Time 100|100 most influential people in the world]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Larson |first1=Brie |title=Time 100: Emma Stone |url=http://time.com/collection/2017-time-100/4736213/emma-stone/ |accessdate=April 21, 2017 |work=Time |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170420220918/http://time.com/collection/2017-time-100/4736213/emma-stone/ |archivedate=April 20, 2017 |df= }}</ref>\n\nStone has been described as a style icon{{nsmdns}}the media cites her hair, eyes, and husky voice as her trademarks.<ref name=\"trade1\">{{cite web|last1=Watson |first1=Sheridan |title=31 Photos That Prove Emma Stone Is The Most Stylish Person on Earth |url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/sheridanwatson/photos-that-prove-emma-stone-is-the-most-stylish-person |publisher=[[BuzzFeed]] |accessdate=April 7, 2016 |date=October 17, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150829080504/http://www.buzzfeed.com/sheridanwatson/photos-that-prove-emma-stone-is-the-most-stylish-person |archivedate=August 29, 2015 |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"trade\">{{cite news|last1=Stern |first1=Marlow |title=Emma Stone On 'The Amazing Spider-Man,' Andrew Garfield, & More |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2012/06/26/emma-stone-on-the-amazing-spider-man-andrew-garfield-more.html |accessdate=April 7, 2016 |work=[[The Daily Beast]] |date=June 26, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160407170215/http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2012/06/26/emma-stone-on-the-amazing-spider-man-andrew-garfield-more.html |archivedate=April 7, 2016 |df= }}</ref> ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' credits the actress for her \"sophisticated, perfectly put-together looks\", writing that \"her charisma, both on-screen and off-, has charmed many.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Emma Stone's Best Red\u2013Carpet Moments |url=http://www.vogue.com/868846/emma-stone-best-red-carpet-moments/ |accessdate=April 7, 2016 |work=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]] |date=April 15, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160418055522/http://www.vogue.com/868846/emma-stone-best-red-carpet-moments/ |archivedate=April 18, 2016 |df= }}</ref> In 2009, she featured in [[AskMen|AskMen's]] Top 99 Women, ''[[FHM]]''{{'s}} [[FHM's 100 Sexiest Women (UK)|100 Sexiest Women in the World]], and ''[[Maxim (magazine)|Maxim]]'' magazine's Hot 100;<ref name=\"Ask quote\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=The 100 Sexiest Women in the World |url=http://www.fhmonline.com/Site/customPage/DefaultPlain.aspx?ID=40563 |accessdate=April 8, 2016 |work=[[FHM]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090707094703/http://www.fhmonline.com/Site/customPage/DefaultPlain.aspx?ID=40563 |archivedate=July 7, 2009 }}<br />{{cite news|title=2009 Hot 100 List |url=http://www.maxim.com/women/2009-hot-100-post |accessdate=April 8, 2016 |work=[[Maxim (magazine)|Maxim]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160413060220/http://www.maxim.com/women/2009-hot-100-post |archivedate=April 13, 2016 |df= }}</ref> the latter also placed her on the list on three other occasions{{nsmdns}}2010, 2011, and 2014.<ref>{{cite news|title=2010 Hot 100 List |url=http://www.maxim.com/women/2010-hot-100-post |accessdate=April 8, 2016 |work=Maxim |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401121236/http://www.maxim.com/women/2010-hot-100-post |archivedate=April 1, 2016 |df= }}<br />{{cite news|title=2011 Hot 100 List |url=http://www.maxim.com/women/2011-hot-100-post |accessdate=April 8, 2016 |work=Maxim |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160406052023/http://www.maxim.com/women/2011-hot-100-post |archivedate=April 6, 2016 |df= }}<br />{{cite news|title=2014 Hot 100 List |url=http://www.maxim.com/women/2014-hot-100-post |accessdate=April 8, 2016 |work=Maxim |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160412180232/http://www.maxim.com/women/2014-hot-100-post |archivedate=April 12, 2016 |df= }}</ref> She continued to be featured in AskMen's annual beauty lists from 2010 to 2015, ranking among the top forty each year.<ref>{{cite web |title=Top 99 Women |url=http://www.askmen.com/specials/2011_top_99/32-emma-stone.html |publisher=AskMen |accessdate=April 8, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110803220157/http://www.askmen.com/specials/2011_top_99/32-emma-stone.html |archivedate=August 3, 2011 }}<br />{{cite web |title=Top 99 Women of 2012 |url=http://www.askmen.com/specials/2012_top_99/6-emma-stone.html |publisher=AskMen |accessdate=April 8, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120203044117/http://www.askmen.com/specials/2012_top_99/6-emma-stone.html |archivedate=February 3, 2012 }}<br />{{cite web |title=Emma Stone AskMen Top 99 2013 Video |url=http://www.askmen.com/video/entertainment-and-celebrities/emma-stone-askmen-top-99-2013-video.html |publisher=AskMen |accessdate=April 9, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422155849/http://www.askmen.com/video/entertainment-and-celebrities/emma-stone-askmen-top-99-2013-video.html |archivedate=April 22, 2016 |df= }}<br />{{cite web |title=Top 99 Women of 2014 |url=http://www.askmen.com/specials/2014_top_99/28-emma-stone.html |publisher=AskMen |accessdate=April 8, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408054957/http://www.askmen.com/specials/2014_top_99/28-emma-stone.html |archivedate=April 8, 2016 |df= }}<br />{{cite web |title=Top 99 Women of 2015 |url=http://www.askmen.com/specials/2015_top_99/27-emma-stone.html |publisher=AskMen |accessdate=April 8, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160419223419/http://www.askmen.com/specials/2015_top_99/27-emma-stone.html |archivedate=April 19, 2016 |df= }}</ref> In 2011, she appeared in [[Victoria's Secret|Victoria's Secret's]] list of What is Sexy? as the Sexiest Actress.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Derschowitz |first1=Jessica |title=Emma Stone, Rihanna top Victoria's Secret's \"What is Sexy?\" list |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/emma-stone-rihanna-top-victorias-secrets-what-is-sexy-list/ |publisher=[[CBS News]] |accessdate=April 7, 2016 |date=May 12, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160420184251/http://www.cbsnews.com/news/emma-stone-rihanna-top-victorias-secrets-what-is-sexy-list/ |archivedate=April 20, 2016 |df= }}</ref> She was mentioned in several other media outlet lists that year, including ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' magazine's 100 Most Beautiful Women, each of ''FHM''{{'s}} and ''[[FHM Australia]]''{{'s}} 100 Sexiest Women in the World, and ''[[Men's Health]]'' magazine's 100 Hottest Women.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.people.com/people/package/gallery/0,,20360857_20481337_20936743,00.html |title=World's Most Beautiful 2011 |work=People |accessdate=April 8, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160508073049/http://www.people.com/people/package/gallery/0%2C%2C20360857_20481337_20936743%2C00.html |archivedate=May 8, 2016 |df= }}<br />{{cite news|url=http://www.fhm.com/girls/100-sexiest-women |title=FHM's 100 Sexiest Women in the World 2011 |work=FHM |date=May 5, 2011 |accessdate=April 8, 2016 |author=Moody, Jon |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111230002746/http://www.fhm.com/girls/100-sexiest-women |archivedate=December 30, 2011 }}<br />{{cite news|url=http://www.fhm.com.au/view_image.htm?index=62&gid=17384 |title=FHM's 100 Sexiest Women in the World |work=[[FHM Australia]] |accessdate=April 8, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321200202/http://www.fhm.com.au/view_image.htm?index=62&gid=17384 |archivedate=March 21, 2012 }}<br />{{cite news|url=http://www.menshealth.com/sex-women/hottest-women-2011 |title=The Hottest Women of 2011 |work=[[Men's Health]] |accessdate=April 8, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111228191141/http://www.menshealth.com/sex-women/hottest-women-2011 |archivedate=December 28, 2011 }}</ref> She ranked sixth on ''Empire''{{'s}} list of the 100 Sexiest Movie Stars in 2013.<ref>{{cite news|title=The 100 Sexiest Movie Stars: The Top 20 |url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/100-sexiest/ |accessdate=August 29, 2016 |work=Empire |date=October 7, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160828220419/http://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/100-sexiest/ |archivedate=August 28, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Stone was named the best dressed woman of 2012 by ''Vogue'' magazine and was featured in similar listings by ''[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]]'' in 2013 and 2015, and ''People'' in 2014.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.vogue.com/slideshow/778652/best-dressed-of-2012-photos/#1 |title=Photos: The Best Dressed of 2012 |work=Vogue |accessdate=April 8, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160418142952/http://www.vogue.com/slideshow/778652/best-dressed-of-2012-photos/#1 |archivedate=April 18, 2016 |df= }}<br />{{cite news |title=50 Best Dressed Women 2013 |url=http://www.glamourmagazine.co.uk/fashion/celebrity-fashion/2013/glamour-best-dressed-women-2013/viewgallery/954094 |accessdate=April 8, 2016 |work=Glamour |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160419063927/http://www.glamourmagazine.co.uk/fashion/celebrity-fashion/2013/glamour-best-dressed-women-2013/viewgallery/954094 |archivedate=April 19, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}<br />{{cite news |title=30 Best Dressed Women of 2015 |url=http://www.glamourmagazine.co.uk/fashion/celebrity-fashion/2015/09/best-dressed-women-2015/viewgallery/1456202 |accessdate=April 8, 2016 |work=Glamour |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160415031549/http://www.glamourmagazine.co.uk/fashion/celebrity-fashion/2015/09/best-dressed-women-2015/viewgallery/1456202 |archivedate=April 15, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://stylenews.peoplestylewatch.com/2014/09/17/best-dressed-taylor-swift-jennifer-lopez-style/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160220110441/http://stylenews.peoplestylewatch.com/2014/09/17/best-dressed-taylor-swift-jennifer-lopez-style/|archivedate=February 20, 2016 |title=People's Best Dressed, Taylor Swift Best Dressed 2014 |website=People |date=September 17, 2014 |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> In 2017, [[Buzznet]] named her one of the world's most beautiful women.<ref>{{cit news|title=Top 30 World's Most Beautiful Women of 2017 |url=http://www.buzznet.com/2017/03/top-30-worlds-most-beautiful-women-of-2017/ |publisher=[[Buzznet]] |date=March 10, 2017 |accessdate=April 23, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170420235117/http://www.buzznet.com/2017/03/top-30-worlds-most-beautiful-women-of-2017/ |archivedate=April 20, 2017 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==Works and accolades==\n{{Main|List of Emma Stone performances|List of awards and nominations received by Emma Stone|l2=awards and nominations}}\nAccording to the review aggregator site [[Rotten Tomatoes]] and the box-office site [[Box Office Mojo]], Stone's most critically acclaimed and commercially successful films are ''Superbad'' (2007), ''Zombieland'' (2009), ''Easy A'' (2010), ''Crazy, Stupid, Love'' (2011), ''The Help'' (2011), ''The Amazing Spider-Man'' (2012), ''The Amazing Spider-Man 2'' (2014), ''Birdman'' (2014), ''La La Land'' (2016), ''Battle of the Sexes'' (2017), and ''The Favourite'' (2018).<ref name=\"rotten\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Emma Stone|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/people/chart/?view=Actor&id=emmastone|publisher=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=July 30, 2016}}</ref>\n\nStone has been nominated for three [[Academy Awards]]: Best Supporting Actress for ''Birdman'' and ''The Favourite'', and Best Actress for ''La La Land''; and four [[British Academy Film Awards]]: BAFTA Rising Star Award, Best Supporting Actress for ''Birdman'' and ''The Favourite'', and Best Actress in a Leading Role for ''La La Land''. She won the Best Actress award at both ceremonies for ''La La Land''.<ref name=\"EasyA\"/><ref name=\"awards\"/><ref name=\"la la\"/> Stone also won Best Actress in a Comedy or Musical at the [[74th Golden Globe Awards]], Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Leading Role at the [[23rd Screen Actors Guild Awards]] and [[Volpi Cup for Best Actress]] at [[73rd Venice International Film Festival|Venice Film Festival]] for her role in ''La La Land''.<ref name=\"la la\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/awards/2017/01/29/sag-awards-2017-winners-see-the-full-list/ |title=SAG Awards 2017 winners: See the full list |website=The Hollywood Reporter |date=January 30, 2016 |accessdate=February 1, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170131123633/http://ew.com/awards/2017/01/29/sag-awards-2017-winners-see-the-full-list/ |archivedate=January 31, 2017 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.labiennale.org/en/cinema/73rd-festival/awards |title=Official Awards of the 73rd Venice Film Festival |work=labiennale.org |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161008224708/http://www.labiennale.org/en/cinema/73rd-festival/awards |archivedate=8 October 2016 |access-date=20 April 2018  }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of actors with two or more Academy Award nominations in acting categories]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|25em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[https://networthcloud.com/emma-stone-wikis/ Emma Stone] on Networthcloud\n*{{IMDb name|1297015|name=Emma Stone}}\n* {{IBDB name|497842|name=Emma Stone}}\n* {{Tcmdb name|1455286|name=Emma Stone}}\n* {{AllMovie name|491706|name=Emma Stone}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes person|emma-stone|name=Emma Stone}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = [[List of awards and nominations received by Emma Stone|Awards for Emma Stone]]\n|list  = \n{{Academy Award Best Actress}}\n{{AACTA International Award for Best Actress}}\n{{BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Leading Role}}\n{{Boston Society of Film Critics Award for Best Supporting Actress}}\n{{Golden Globe Award Best Actress Motion Picture Musical or Comedy}}\n{{MTV Movie Award for Best Comedic Performance}}\n{{People's Choice Award for Favorite Movie Actress}}\n{{ScreenActorsGuildAward FemaleLeadMotionPicture}}\n{{Volpi Cup for Best Actress}}\n}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Art|Biography|Film|New York City|Television|United States|Video games}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{featured article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stone, Emma}}\n[[Category:Emma Stone| ]]\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from New York City]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Scottsdale, Arizona]]\n[[Category:American child actresses]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American voice actresses]]\n[[Category:Best Actress Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Actress BAFTA Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Musical or Comedy Actress Golden Globe (film) winners]]\n[[Category:Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture Screen Actors Guild Award winners]]\n[[Category:Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Leading Role Screen Actors Guild Award winners]]\n[[Category:Volpi Cup for Best Actress winners]]\n[[Category:Participants in American reality television series]]\n[[Category:People from Greenwich Village]]\n[[Category:American people of Swedish descent]]\n[[Category:Best Actress AACTA International Award winners]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Scottish descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American actress}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{Use American English|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n | name        = Emma Stone\n | image       = Emma Stone at the 39th Mill Valley Film Festival (cropped).jpg\n | alt         = A picture of Emma Stone as she looks at the camera.\n | caption     = Stone at the 2016 [[Mill Valley Film Festival]]\n | birthname   = Emily Jean Stone\n | birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1988|11|6}}\n | birth_place = [[Scottsdale, Arizona]], U.S.<!--As per WP:LINKDIRECT and Template:infobox person, birth/death place indicates city, state, then country. No need to spell out \"United States; 'U.S.' is fine.-->\n | occupation  = Actress\n | yearsactive = 2004\u2013present\n | partner     = [[Dave McCary]] (2017\u2013present; engaged)\n | works       = [[List of Emma Stone performances|Performances]]\n | awards      = [[List of awards and nominations received by Emma Stone|Full list]]\n | signature   = Emma Stone Signature.svg\n }}\n'''Emily Jean''' \"'''Emma'''\" '''Stone''' (born November 6, 1988) is an American actress. The recipient of [[List of awards and nominations received by Emma Stone|numerous accolades]], including an [[Academy Award]] and a [[Golden Globe Award]], she was the world's highest-paid actress in 2017. Stone has appeared in [[Celebrity 100|''Forbes'' Celebrity 100]] in 2013 and in 2017, she was featured by ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' as one of the [[Time 100|100 most influential people in the world]].\n\nBorn and raised in [[Scottsdale, Arizona]], Stone began acting as a child, in a theater production of ''[[The Wind in the Willows]]'' in 2000. As a teenager, she relocated to Los Angeles with her mother and made her television debut in ''[[The New Partridge Family|In Search of the New Partridge Family]]'' (2004), a reality show that produced only an unsold pilot. After small television roles, she made her film debut in ''[[Superbad (film)|Superbad]]'' (2007), and received positive media attention for her role in ''[[Zombieland]]'' (2009). The 2010 teen comedy ''[[Easy A]]'' was Stone's first starring role, earning her nominations for the [[BAFTA Rising Star Award]] and a [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Comedy or Musical|Golden Globe Award for Best Actress]]. This breakthrough was followed with further success in the romantic comedy ''[[Crazy, Stupid, Love]]'' (2011) and the drama ''[[The Help (film)|The Help]]'' (2011).\n\nStone gained wider recognition as [[Gwen Stacy]] in the 2012 superhero film ''[[The Amazing Spider-Man (2012 film)|The Amazing Spider-Man]]'', and [[The Amazing Spider-Man 2|its 2014 sequel]]. She was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress]] for playing a recovering drug addict in the black comedy ''[[Birdman (film)|Birdman]]'' (2014), and her [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] debut came in a revival of the musical ''[[Cabaret (musical)|Cabaret]]'' (2014\u20132015). She won the [[Academy Award for Best Actress]] for playing an aspiring actress in the romantic musical ''[[La La Land (film)|La La Land]]'' (2016). Stone portrayed [[Billie Jean King]] in the biographical sports film ''[[Battle of the Sexes (2017 film)|Battle of the Sexes]]'' (2017) and [[Abigail Masham]] in the historical comedy-drama ''[[The Favourite (film)|The Favourite]]'' (2018), receiving a third Academy Award nomination for the latter. She has since starred in the [[Netflix]] dark comedy miniseries ''[[Maniac (miniseries)|Maniac]]'' (2018) and the comedy sequel ''[[Zombieland: Double Tap]]'' (2019).\n\n==Early life==\nEmily Jean Stone was born on November 6, 1988, in [[Scottsdale, Arizona]], to Krista Jean Stone ([[Given name#Name at birth|n\u00e9e]] Yeager), a homemaker, and Jeffrey Charles Stone, the founder and CEO of a general-contracting company.<ref name=\"F.Y.I.\">{{cite web|title=Emma Stone Biography|url=http://www.biography.com/people/emma-stone-20874773|publisher=[[FYI (U.S. TV channel)|FYI]]|accessdate=March 17, 2016|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160423201239/http://www.biography.com/people/emma-stone-20874773|archivedate=April 23, 2016| url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"vanityfair1\">{{cite news|last1=Diehl |first1=Jessica |last2=Wolfe |first2=Alexandra |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2011/08/emma-stone-201108 |title=Hollywood Is Her Oyster |accessdate=March 17, 2016 |work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160312131935/http://www.vanityfair.com/news/2011/08/emma-stone-201108 |archivedate=March 12, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Stone lived on the grounds of the [[Camelback Inn]] resort from the age of 12 to 15.<ref>{{cite web|last=Barker |first=Lynn |url=http://www.teenhollywood.com/2008/08/19/rockin-with-emma-stone |title=\"Rockin'\" with Emma Stone |publisher=TeenHollywood.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140417044401/http://www.teenhollywood.com/2008/08/19/rockin-with-emma-stone|archivedate=April 17, 2014 |date=August 19, 2008 |accessdate=September 8, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"people\">{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/emma_stone/biography/0,,20517671,00.html |title=Emma Stone Biography |website=[[People (magazine)|People]] |date= |accessdate=September 8, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160419122505/http://www.people.com/people/emma_stone/biography/0%2C%2C20517671%2C00.html |archivedate=April 19, 2016 |df= }}</ref> She has a younger brother, Spencer.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Thomas |first1=Leah |title=Emma Stone Brings Brother Spencer to the Golden Globes, Adding to the Trend of the Night |url=http://www.bustle.com/articles/57994-emma-stone-brings-brother-spencer-to-the-golden-globes-adding-to-the-trend-of-the-night |accessdate=March 17, 2016 |work=[[Bustle (magazine)|Bustle]] |date=January 12, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160325033423/http://www.bustle.com/articles/57994-emma-stone-brings-brother-spencer-to-the-golden-globes-adding-to-the-trend-of-the-night |archivedate=March 25, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Her paternal grandfather, Conrad Ostberg Sten, was from a Swedish family that [[Anglicisation|anglicized]] their surname to \"Stone\" when they immigrated to the United States through [[Ellis Island]]. She also has German, English, Scottish, and Irish ancestry.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=David |first1=Elliot |year=2010 |title=Emma Stone |journal=Wonderland |issue=23 |pages=177\u2013181}}</ref>\n\n[[File:ValleyYouthTheatre.jpg|thumb|right|Stone appeared in sixteen productions at [[Valley Youth Theatre]].]]\nAs an infant, Stone had [[baby colic]] and cried frequently; she consequently developed [[Vocal fold nodule|nodules]] and calluses on her vocal cords while she was a child.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wilner|first=Norman|date=July 27, 2011|title=Q&A: Emma Stone|url=http://www.nowtoronto.com/daily/movies/story.cfm?content=181989|work=[[Now (newspaper)|Now]]|accessdate=November 13, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120620013944/http://www.nowtoronto.com/daily/movies/story.cfm?content=181989|archivedate=June 20, 2012}}</ref> Stone has described herself as having been \"loud\" and \"bossy\" while growing up.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.wmagazine.com/people/celebrities/2011/01/emma_stone_easy_a_actress/ |title=Emma Stone |last=Hirschberg |first=Lynn |date=January 2011 |work=[[W (magazine)|W]] |access-date=April 12, 2016 |via= |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425004045/http://www.wmagazine.com/people/celebrities/2011/01/emma_stone_easy_a_actress/ |archivedate=April 25, 2016 |df= }}</ref> She was educated at Sequoya Elementary School and attended [[Scottsdale Unified School District|Cocopah Middle School]] for the sixth grade. Although she did not like school, she has stated that her controlling nature meant that \"I made sure I got all [[Grading (education)|As]]\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Schuman |first=Michael A. |title=Emma!: Amazing Actress Emma Stone |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mrWUAgAAQBAJ |year=2013 |publisher=Enslow Publishers |isbn=978-0-7660-4113-4 |pages=11\u201312 |accessdate=May 16, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170131104515/https://books.google.com/books?id=mrWUAgAAQBAJ |archivedate=January 31, 2017 |df= }}</ref> Stone suffered [[panic attack]]s as a child,<ref name=\"WSJ-IrrationalMan-2015\">{{cite news|last1=Eells |first1=Josh |title=Emma Stone Talks 'Irrational Man,' the Sony Hack and Keeping Her Personal Life Private |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/emma-stone-talks-irrational-man-the-sony-hack-and-keeping-her-personal-life-private-1434547660 |accessdate=March 16, 2016 |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=June 17, 2015 |url-access=subscription  |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160316045141/http://www.wsj.com/articles/emma-stone-talks-irrational-man-the-sony-hack-and-keeping-her-personal-life-private-1434547660 |archivedate=March 16, 2016 |df= }}</ref> which she says caused a decline in her social skills.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fisher |first1=Luchina |title=Emma Stone Has History of Panic Attacks |url=https://abcnews.go.com/blogs/entertainment/2012/06/emma-stone-has-history-of-panic-attacks/ |accessdate=March 23, 2016 |publisher=[[ABC News]] |date=June 21, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160326092353/http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/entertainment/2012/06/emma-stone-has-history-of-panic-attacks/ |archivedate=March 26, 2016 |df= }}</ref> She underwent therapy but states that it was her participation in local theater plays that helped cure the attacks.<ref name=\"WSJ-IrrationalMan-2015\" />\n\n{{quote|The first time I had a panic attack I was sitting in my friend's house, and I thought the house was burning down. I called my mom and she brought me home, and for the next three years it just would not stop. I would go to the nurse at lunch most days and just wring my hands. I would ask my mom to tell me exactly how the day was going to be, then ask again 30 seconds later. I just needed to know that no one was going to die and nothing was going to change. | Stone | ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', June 2015<ref name=\"WSJ-IrrationalMan-2015\" />}}\n\nStone started acting at age four;<ref name=\"people\" /> she wanted a career in [[sketch comedy]] initially, but shifted her focus toward musical theater, and took voice lessons for several years.<ref name=\"Blackbook2009\" /> Her acting debut, at the age of 11, came in a stage production of ''[[The Wind in the Willows]]'', playing the part of Otter.<ref>{{cite news|title=Emma Stone: Before She Was Famous |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/11/04/emma-stone-before-she-was-famous-theater-productions_n_1076798.html |accessdate=March 15, 2016 |work=[[The Huffington Post]] |date=January 4, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160322100722/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/11/04/emma-stone-before-she-was-famous-theater-productions_n_1076798.html |archivedate=March 22, 2016 |df= }}</ref> The actress was [[Homeschooling|homeschooled]] for two years, during which time she appeared in sixteen productions at Phoenix's [[Valley Youth Theatre]]\u2014including ''[[The Princess and the Pea]]'', ''[[Alice's Adventures in Wonderland]]'', and ''[[Joseph and the Amazing Technicolor Dreamcoat]]''<ref name=\"F.Y.I.\" />\u2014and performed with the theater's [[improvisational theatre|improvisational comedy]] troupe.<ref name=\"EastValleyTribune\">{{cite news|last=Outhier|first= Craig |date=August 16, 2008|url=http://www.eastvalleytribune.com/article_9aeedb12-8c94-54f1-b507-9ff97ffb0cc3.html|title=Emma Stone explores comedy with latest roles|work=[[East Valley Tribune]]|accessdate=October 2, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120919164526/http://www.eastvalleytribune.com/article_9aeedb12-8c94-54f1-b507-9ff97ffb0cc3.html|archivedate=September 19, 2012}}</ref> Around this time, she traveled to Los Angeles and auditioned unsuccessfully for a role in [[Nickelodeon]]'s ''[[All That]]''.<ref name=\"breakout\">{{cite book|last=Owings |first=Lisa |title=Emma Stone: Breakout Movie Star |url=https://archive.org/details/emmastonebreakou0000owin |url-access=registration |year=2014 |publisher=ABDO Publishing Company |isbn=978-1-62968-026-2 |page=22; 33 |accessdate=May 16, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Her parents later sent her for private acting lessons with a local acting coach, who had worked at the [[William Morris Agency]] in the 1970s.<ref name=\"vanityfair1\" />\n\nStone attended [[Xavier College Preparatory (Arizona)|Xavier College Preparatory]]{{nsmdns}}an all-girl [[Catholic school|Catholic high school]]{{nsmdns}}as a freshman, but [[High school dropouts|dropped out]] after one semester to become an actress.<ref name=\"F.Y.I.\" /> She prepared a [[Microsoft PowerPoint|PowerPoint]] presentation for her parents titled \"Project Hollywood\" (featuring [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]'s 2003 song \"[[Hollywood (Madonna song)|Hollywood]]\") to convince them to let her move to California to pursue an acting career.<ref name=\"Blackbook2009\" /> In January 2004, she moved with her mother to an apartment in Los Angeles. She recalls: \"I went up for every single show on the [[Disney Channel]] and auditioned to play the daughter on every single sitcom\", adding, \"I ended up getting none.\"<ref name=\"people\" /> Between auditions for roles, she enrolled in online high-school classes, and worked part-time at a dog-treat bakery.<ref name=\"vanityfair1\" /><ref name=\"WSJ-IrrationalMan-2015\" />\n\n==Career==\n===Early career (2004\u20132008)===\nWhen Stone registered for the [[Screen Actors Guild]], the name \"Emily Stone\" was already taken. She initially chose to go by \"Riley Stone\", but after guest-starring in the [[NBC]] drama ''[[Medium (TV series)|Medium]]'' and the [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] sitcom ''[[Malcolm in the Middle]]'', she decided that she was more comfortable with \"Emma\".<ref name=\"breakout\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Printing \u2013 Emma Stone \u2013 Interview Magazine |url=http://www.interviewmagazine.com/film/emma-stone/print/ |accessdate=August 21, 2016 |work=[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816012839/http://www.interviewmagazine.com/film/emma-stone/print |archivedate=August 16, 2016 |df= }}</ref> She chose to use \"Emma\" in honor of [[Emma Bunton]] of [[the Spice Girls]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/emma-stone-reveals-hilariously-bad-reason-stopped-using-real-name-094537813.html|title=Emma Stone reveals the hilariously bad reason she stopped using her real name|access-date=2018-11-17|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190606155337/https://finance.yahoo.com/news/emma-stone-reveals-hilariously-bad-reason-stopped-using-real-name-094537813.html|archive-date=June 6, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> She made her television debut as Laurie Partridge on the [[VH1]] talent competition reality show ''In Search of the New Partridge Family'' (2004). The resulting show, retitled ''[[The New Partridge Family]]'' (2004), remained an unsold pilot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/427693/emma-stone-flashback-see-star-sing-on-partridge-family-reality-competition-in-pre-fame-days |title=Emma Stone Flashback: See Star Sing on Partridge Family Reality Competition in Pre-Fame Days |publisher=[[E!]] |date=June 7, 2013 |accessdate=March 24, 2016 |author=Grossberg, Josh |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160508123457/http://www.eonline.com/news/427693/emma-stone-flashback-see-star-sing-on-partridge-family-reality-competition-in-pre-fame-days |archivedate=May 8, 2016 |df= }}</ref> She followed this with a guest appearance in [[Louis C.K.]]'s [[HBO]] series ''[[Lucky Louie]]''.<ref name=\"WSJ-IrrationalMan-2015\" /> She auditioned to star as [[Claire Bennet]] in the NBC science fiction drama [[Heroes (U.S. TV series)|''Heroes'']] (2007) but was unsuccessful and later called this her \"rock bottom\" experience.<ref name=\"vanityfair1\" /> In April 2007, she played [[List of Drive characters#Violet Trimble|Violet Trimble]] in the Fox action drama ''[[Drive (2007 TV series)|Drive]]'', but the show was canceled after seven episodes.<ref name=\"F.Y.I.\" />\n\nStone made her feature film debut in [[Greg Mottola]]'s comedy ''[[Superbad (film)|Superbad]]'' (2007), co-starring [[Michael Cera]] and [[Jonah Hill]]. The film tells the story of two high school students who go through a series of comic misadventures after they plan to buy alcohol for a party. To play the role of Hill's romantic interest, she dyed her hair red.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.teenvogue.com/gallery/emma-stone-hair-styles |title=Emma Stone's Best Hair Moments |work=[[Teen Vogue]] |accessdate=March 23, 2016 |author=Duan, Noel |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160411050337/http://www.teenvogue.com/gallery/emma-stone-hair-styles |archivedate=April 11, 2016 |df= }}</ref> A reviewer for ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' found her \"appealing\", but felt that her role was poorly written.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/superbad-158043 |title=Superbad |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=March 23, 2016 |author=Farber, Stephen |date=August 6, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408205811/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/superbad-158043 |archivedate=April 8, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Stone has described the experience of acting in her first film as \"amazing&nbsp;... [but] very different than other experiences I've had since then\".<ref name=\"AccessHollywood6-4-2008\">{{cite news|url=http://www.accesshollywood.com/article/9785/rising-star-emma-stone/|title=Rising Star: Emma Stone|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080609021459/http://www.accesshollywood.com/article/9785/rising-star-emma-stone/|archivedate=June 9, 2008|work=[[Access Hollywood]]|date=June 4, 2008|accessdate=June 5, 2008}}</ref> The film was a commercial success, and earned her the [[Young Hollywood Award]] for Exciting New Face.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=superbad.htm |title=Superbad |publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=March 23, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408184959/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=superbad.htm |archivedate=April 8, 2016 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.lexpress.fr/culture/cinema/emma-stone-une-muse-qui-ne-craint-pas-les-defis_1723443.html | title=Emma Stone, une muse qui ne craint pas les d\u00e9fis | work=[[L'Express]] | date=October 14, 2015 | accessdate=March 23, 2016 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151019031823/http://www.lexpress.fr/culture/cinema/emma-stone-une-muse-qui-ne-craint-pas-les-defis_1723443.html | archivedate=October 19, 2015 | language=French}}</ref>\n\nThe following year, Stone starred in the comedy ''[[The Rocker (film)|The Rocker]]'' (2008) playing Amelia Stone, the \"straight face\" [[bass guitar]]ist in a band; she learned to play the bass for the role.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/new/Interview-Emma-Stone-And-Teddy-Geiger-of-The-Rocker-9109.html |title=Interview: Emma Stone And Teddy Geiger Of The Rocker |publisher=Cinemablend.com |accessdate=March 24, 2016 |author=McConnell, Mariana |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160402011602/http://www.cinemablend.com/new/Interview-Emma-Stone-And-Teddy-Geiger-of-The-Rocker-9109.html |archivedate=April 2, 2016 |df= |date=June 9, 2008 }}</ref> The actress, who describes herself as \"a big smiler and laugher\", has admitted that she found it difficult portraying a character whose personality traits were so different from her own. The film, and her performance, received negative reviews from critics and was a commercial failure.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Rocker |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/10009055-rocker/ |publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=March 24, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160312080953/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/10009055-rocker/ |archivedate=March 12, 2016 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Hendrix |first1=Graddy |title=Rainn Wilson on His New Spiritual Book and How The Rocker's Epic Flop Changed His Life for the Better |url=https://www.vulture.com/2010/10/the_vulture_transcript_rainn_w.html |accessdate=March 23, 2016 |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |date=October 29, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160406052037/http://www.vulture.com/2010/10/the_vulture_transcript_rainn_w.html |archivedate=April 6, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Her next release, the romantic comedy ''[[The House Bunny]]'', performed better at the box-office, becoming a moderate commercial success.<ref>{{cite news|title=French auds flock to 'Barcelona' |url=https://variety.com/2008/film/news/french-auds-flock-to-barcelona-1117993958/ |accessdate=March 23, 2016 |work=Variety |date=October 14, 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160404124644/http://variety.com/2008/film/news/french-auds-flock-to-barcelona-1117993958/ |archivedate=April 4, 2016 |df= }}</ref> The film sees her play the president of a sorority, and perform a [[cover version]] of [[the Waitresses]]' 1982 song \"[[I Know What Boys Like (song)|I Know What Boys Like]]\".<ref name=\"Sullivan2008\">{{cite news |last1=Sullivan |first1=Kevin |date=June 2, 2008 |url=http://www.northbynorthwestern.com/story/the-house-bunny/ |title=An interview with Emma Stone of The House Bunny |work=[[North by Northwestern]] |accessdate=June 4, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120312165049/http://www.northbynorthwestern.com/story/the-house-bunny/ |archivedate=March 12, 2012 |df= }}</ref> Reviews for the film were generally negative,<ref>{{cite web|title=The House Bunny |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/house_bunny |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=March 24, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160313030016/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/house_bunny/ |archivedate=March 13, 2016 |df= }}</ref> though she was praised for her supporting role,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/richard-brody/the-talent-in-the-house |title=The Talent in the House |work=[[The New Yorker]] |date=March 29, 2012 |accessdate=May 18, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160924132227/http://www.newyorker.com/culture/richard-brody/the-talent-in-the-house |archivedate=September 24, 2016 |df= }}</ref> and ''[[TV Guide]]''{{'s}} Ken Fox wrote of Stone that: \"She's positively incandescent, lighting up a movie that would be pretty dim without her.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fox |first1=Ken |title=The House Bunny |url=https://www.tvguide.com/movies/house-bunny/review/293511/ |accessdate=March 24, 2016 |work=[[TV Guide]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160407025625/http://www.tvguide.com/movies/house-bunny/review/293511/ |archivedate=April 7, 2016 |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Breakthrough (2009\u20132011)===\n[[File:EmmaStoneSept09.jpg|thumb|Stone at the ''[[Zombieland]]'' world premiere in 2009]]\n\nStone appeared in three films released in 2009. The first of these was opposite [[Matthew McConaughey]], [[Jennifer Garner]] and [[Michael Douglas]] in [[Mark Waters (director)|Mark Waters]]' ''[[Ghosts of Girlfriends Past]]''. Loosely based on [[Charles Dickens]]' 1843 [[novella]] ''[[A Christmas Carol]]'', the romantic comedy has her playing a ghost who haunts her former boyfriend. Critical reaction to the film was negative, though it was a modest commercial success.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=ghostsofgirlfriendspast.htm |title=Ghosts of Girlfriends Past (2009) |publisher=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=March 25, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160407014245/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=ghostsofgirlfriendspast.htm |archivedate=April 7, 2016 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Ghosts of Girlfriends Past (2009) |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=March 25, 2016 |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1193906-ghosts_of_girlfriends_past |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408110619/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1193906-ghosts_of_girlfriends_past/ |archivedate=April 8, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Her most financially profitable venture that year was [[Ruben Fleischer]]'s $102.3 million-grossing horror comedy film ''[[Zombieland]]'',<ref>{{cite web|title=2009 Yearly Box Office Results |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?yr=2009 |publisher=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=March 26, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160406233637/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?yr=2009 |archivedate=April 6, 2016 |df= }}</ref> in which she features alongside [[Jesse Eisenberg]], [[Woody Harrelson]] and [[Abigail Breslin]]. In the film, she appeared as a con artist and survivor of a [[zombie apocalypse]], in a role which ''[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]''{{'s}} Chris Hewitt found to be \"somewhat underwritten\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hewitt |first1=Chris |title=Zombieland Review |url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/zombieland/review/ |accessdate=March 26, 2016 |work=[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]] |date=October 9, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160625030310/http://www.empireonline.com/movies/zombieland/review/ |archivedate=June 25, 2016 |df= }}</ref> In a more positive review, the critic for ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' wrote: \"[T]he hugely promising Stone{{nbsp}}... [is] a tough cookie who projects the aura of being wiser than her years.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Robey |first1=Tim |title=Zombieland, review |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/6273649/Zombieland-review.html |accessdate=April 11, 2016 |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=October 8, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160424003803/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/6273649/Zombieland-review.html |archivedate=April 24, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Stone's third release in 2009 was [[Kieran Mulroney|Kieran and Michelle Mulroney's]] ''[[Paper Man (2009 film)|Paper Man]]'', a comedy-drama which disappointed critics.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lawrence|first1=Will|title=The heart of Stone|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/movies/the-heart-of-stone-30192722.html|accessdate=May 16, 2016|work=[[Irish Independent]]|date=April 18, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160610191804/http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/movies/the-heart-of-stone-30192722.html|archive-date=June 10, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nStone provided the voice of an [[Australian Shepherd]] in ''[[Marmaduke (film)|Marmaduke]]'' (2010), a comedy from director [[Tom Dey]], which is based on [[Brad Anderson (cartoonist)|Brad Anderson]]'s [[Marmaduke|long-running comic strip of the same name]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kit |first1=Borys |date=November 3, 2009 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-wilson-idUSTRE5A20K120091103 |title=Owen Wilson signs on for 'Marmaduke' |publisher=Reuters |accessdate=November 7, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305213159/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-wilson-idUSTRE5A20K120091103 |archivedate=March 5, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Her breakthrough came the same year with a starring role in ''[[Easy A]]'', a teen comedy directed by [[Will Gluck]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wilner|first1=Norman|url=https://nowtoronto.com/movies/cover-story/emma-stone/ |title=Emma Stone|work=Now|date=September 9, 2010|accessdate=September 16, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160114112247/https://nowtoronto.com/movies/cover-story/emma-stone/|archivedate=January 14, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Emma Stone On 'Obsessing' Over Her Breakout Role In 'Easy A' |url=http://www.accesshollywood.com/videos/emma-stone-on-obsessing-over-her-breakout-role-in-easy-a-23090/ |accessdate=March 27, 2016 |work=Access Hollywood |date=August 31, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160409071552/http://www.accesshollywood.com/videos/emma-stone-on-obsessing-over-her-breakout-role-in-easy-a-23090/ |archivedate=April 9, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Partially based on [[Nathaniel Hawthorne]]'s 1850 historical romance novel ''[[The Scarlet Letter]]'', the film tells the story of Olive Penderghast (Stone), a high school student who becomes embroiled in a comic sex scandal after a false rumor circulates that she is sexually [[promiscuous]]. Stone read the script before the project was optioned for production, and pursued it with her manager while production details were being finalized. She found the script \"so different and unique from anything I'd read before\", saying that it was \"funny and sweet\". When Stone discovered that the film had begun production, she met with Gluck, expressing her enthusiasm for the project. A few months later, the audition process started and she met again with Gluck, becoming one of the first actresses to audition.<ref name=\"collider\">{{cite web|last1=Roberts|first1=Sheila|date=September 11, 2010|url=https://collider.com/emma-stone-interview-easy-a/48258/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304084823/http://collider.com/emma-stone-interview-easy-a/|archivedate=March 4, 2016|title=Emma Stone Interview Easy A|publisher=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|accessdate=July 1, 2011}}</ref> The film received positive critical reviews, and Stone's performance was considered its prime asset.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Thorpe |first1=Vanessa |title=Lies, paranoia and jealousy on the internet's social networks inspire Hollywood |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2010/oct/24/easya-social-network-chatroom-catfish |accessdate=August 21, 2016 |work=The Guardian |date=October 23, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920225141/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2010/oct/24/easya-social-network-chatroom-catfish |archivedate=September 20, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Anna Smith of ''[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]'' commented: \"Stone gives a terrific performance, her knowing drawl implying intellect and indifference with underlying warmth.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Smith |first1=Anna |title=Easy A |url=https://www.timeout.com/london/film/easy-a |accessdate=March 27, 2016 |work=[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]] |date=October 19, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160413204448/http://www.timeout.com/london/film/easy-a |archivedate=April 13, 2016 |df= }}</ref> With a total box office of $75 million, the film was a commercial success.<ref>{{cite web|title=Easy A (2010) |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=easya.htm |publisher=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=March 27, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304203436/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=easya.htm |archivedate=March 4, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Stone was nominated for a [[BAFTA Rising Star Award]] and a [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy|Golden Globe Award for Best Actress in a Musical or Comedy]], and won the [[MTV Movie Award for Best Comedic Performance]].<ref name=\"EasyA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bafta.org/awards/film/2011-film-awards,1572,BA.html#jump23 |title=Nominees Are Announced Orange Wednesdays Rising Star Award |publisher=[[British Academy of Film and Television Arts]] |date=January 6, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110110061729/http://www.bafta.org/awards/film/2011-film-awards%2C1572%2CBA.html |archivedate=January 10, 2011 |accessdate=March 24, 2016 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}<br />{{cite news|first=Amy |last=Kaufmann |title=Golden Globes 2011 nominations: Newcomers Emma Stone, Jennifer Lawrence and Mila Kunis react |date=December 15, 2010 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |url=http://theenvelope.latimes.com/awards/globes/la-et-globes-newcomers-20101215,0,5904052.story |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101218181041/http://theenvelope.latimes.com/awards/globes/la-et-globes-newcomers-20101215%2C0%2C5904052.story |archivedate=December 18, 2010 |accessdate=December 19, 2010 |url-status=dead |df= }}<br />{{cite web|title=2011 MTV Movie Awards |url=http://www.mtv.com/ontv/movieawards/2011/ |publisher=MTV |accessdate=March 24, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160323083848/http://www.mtv.com/ontv/movieawards/2011/ |archivedate=March 23, 2016 |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn October 2010, Stone hosted an episode of NBC's late-night sketch comedy ''[[Saturday Night Live]]''; her appearances included a sketch playing off her resemblance to [[Lindsay Lohan]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Setoodeh |first=Ramin |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2011/09/01/emma-stone-s-lindsay-lohan-problem.html |title=Emma Stone's Lohan Problem |work=[[The Daily Beast]] |date=September 1, 2011 |accessdate=October 4, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161005131215/http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2011/09/01/emma-stone-s-lindsay-lohan-problem.html |archivedate=October 5, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Stone described it as \"the greatest week of my life\".<ref name=\"people\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=SNL Season 36 Episode 04 \u2013 Emma Stone, Kings of Leon. |url=http://www.nbc.com/saturday-night-live/season-36/episode/4-emma-stone-with-kings-of-leon-60496 |accessdate=August 1, 2016 |publisher=[[NBC]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822050025/http://www.nbc.com/saturday-night-live/season-36/episode/4-emma-stone-with-kings-of-leon-60496 |archivedate=August 22, 2016 |df= }}</ref> She hosted it again in 2011, appeared in an episode in 2014, and in [[Saturday Night Live 40th Anniversary Special|its 40th anniversary special]] in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|last1=McGee |first1=Ryan |title=Recap: 'Saturday Night Live' \u2013 Emma Stone and Coldplay |url=http://www.hitfix.com/blogs/monkeys-as-critics/posts/recap-saturday-night-live-emma-stone-and-coldplay |publisher=[[HitFix]] |date=November 13, 2011 |accessdate=March 25, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160325092321/http://www.hitfix.com/blogs/monkeys-as-critics/posts/recap-saturday-night-live-emma-stone-and-coldplay |archivedate=March 25, 2016 |df= }}<br />{{cite news|last1=Monde |first1=Chinderah |title=Andrew Garfield, Emma Stone spoof 'Amazing Spider-Man 2' with awkward make-out sessions on 'Saturday Night Live' |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv/andrew-garfield-emma-stone-awkwardly-kiss-snl-article-1.1779073 |accessdate=March 25, 2016 |work=[[New York Daily News]] |date=May 4, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160405193939/http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv/andrew-garfield-emma-stone-awkwardly-kiss-snl-article-1.1779073 |archivedate=April 5, 2016 |df= }}<br />{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/jon-hamm-emma-stone-star-wars-snl-1201646236/ |title=Watch: Jon Hamm, Emma Stone Audition for 'Star Wars: The Force Awakens' on 'SNL' |date=November 22, 2015 |accessdate=March 25, 2016 |author=Stedman, Alex |work=Variety |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160225104850/http://variety.com/2015/tv/news/jon-hamm-emma-stone-star-wars-snl-1201646236/ |archivedate=February 25, 2016 |df= }}</ref> A brief appearance in the sex comedy ''[[Friends with Benefits (film)|Friends with Benefits]]'' (2011) reunited her with Gluck.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Siegel |first1=Tatiana |date=July 13, 2010 |url=https://variety.com/2010/film/news/a-rod-goes-from-big-leagues-to-bigscreen-1118021649/ |title=A-Rod goes from big leagues to bigscreen |work=Variety |accessdate=August 1, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004214849/http://variety.com/2010/film/news/a-rod-goes-from-big-leagues-to-bigscreen-1118021649/ |archivedate=October 4, 2013 |df= }}</ref> She followed this with a supporting role in [[Glenn Ficarra]] and [[John Requa]]'s romantic comedy ''[[Crazy, Stupid, Love]]'' (2011) alongside [[Steve Carell]], [[Ryan Gosling]] and [[Julianne Moore]]. The film features her as a law school graduate, and the love interest of Gosling's character. Despite finding \"some inevitable collapses into convention\" in the film, Drew McWeeny of [[HitFix]] wrote that Stone \"ties the whole film together\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=McWeeny |first1=Drew |title=Review: Ryan Gosling, Emma Stone, and Steve Carell excel in smart, adult 'Crazy, Stupid, Love' |url=http://www.hitfix.com/blogs/motion-captured/posts/review-gosling-stone-and-carell-excel-in-smart-adult-crazy-stupid-love |publisher=HitFix |accessdate=March 27, 2016 |date=July 21, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160406053141/http://www.hitfix.com/blogs/motion-captured/posts/review-gosling-stone-and-carell-excel-in-smart-adult-crazy-stupid-love |archivedate=April 6, 2016 |df= }}</ref> At the [[2012 Teen Choice Awards]], she won the [[Teen Choice Award for Choice Movie Actress \u2013 Comedy|Choice Movie Actress \u2013 Comedy]] award for her performance in the film.<ref>{{cite news|first=Philiana |last=Ng |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/teen-choice-awards-breaking-dawn-snow-white-huntsman-337825 |title=Teen Choice Awards 2012: ''Breaking Dawn'', ''Snow White'' Lead Second Wave of Nominees |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=March 27, 2016 |accessdate=June 14, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120615201747/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/teen-choice-awards-breaking-dawn-snow-white-huntsman-337825 |archivedate=June 15, 2012 |url-status=live |df=mdy}}</ref> ''Crazy, Stupid, Love'' was a box office success, grossing $142.9 million worldwide with a production budget of $50 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=crazystupidlove.htm |title=Crazy, Stupid, Love. (2011) |publisher=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=March 29, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160417102459/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=crazystupidlove.htm |archivedate=April 17, 2016 |df= }}</ref>\n\nDisillusioned at being [[typecasting (acting)|typecast]] as the \"sarcastic interest of the guy\", Stone co-starred with [[Viola Davis]] in [[Tate Taylor]]'s period drama ''[[The Help (film)|The Help]]'' (2011), a film she found to be challenging.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/entertainment/film-tv/news/stone-typecasting-is-frustrating-28675472.html | title=Stone: Typecasting is frustrating | work=[[Belfast Telegraph]] | date=October 28, 2011 | accessdate=April 10, 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190601211625/https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/entertainment/film-tv/news/stone-typecasting-is-frustrating-28675472.html | archive-date=June 1, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The film is based on [[Kathryn Stockett]]'s [[The Help|2009 novel of the same name]] and is set in 1960s [[Jackson, Mississippi]]. She met with Taylor to express a desire to work in the film. Taylor has said: \"Emma was completely awkward and dorky, with her raspy voice, and she sat down and we got a little intoxicated and had a blast, and I just thought, 'God! God! This is Skeeter.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ew.com/gallery/summer-movies-we-cant-wait-see/477434_help-august-12 |title=Summer Movies We Can't Wait To See |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=June 2, 2011 |accessdate=March 29, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161114144359/http://www.ew.com/gallery/summer-movies-we-cant-wait-see/477434_help-august-12 |archivedate=November 14, 2016 |df= }}</ref> She was cast as Eugenia \"Skeeter\" Phelan, an aspiring writer learning about the lives of the African-American maids. In preparation for the part, she trained to speak in a [[Southern American English|Southern dialect]]; she also educated herself on the [[Civil Rights Movement]] through literature and film.<ref name=\"speakeasy\">{{cite news|title='Paper Man' Co-Star Emma Stone on Playing Skeeter Phelan in 'The Help' |last=Kung |first=Michelle |date=April 12, 2010 |newspaper=The Wall Street Journal |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2010/04/12/paper-man-co-star-emma-stone-on-playing-skeeter-phelan-in-the-help/ |accessdate=April 18, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100418211049/https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2010/04/12/paper-man-co-star-emma-stone-on-playing-skeeter-phelan-in-the-help/ |archivedate=April 18, 2010 |df= }}</ref> With a worldwide gross of $216 million against a budget of $25 million, ''The Help'' became Stone's most commercially successful film to that point.<ref>{{cite web|title=Emma Stone |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/people/chart/?id=emmastone.htm |publisher=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=March 29, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160409101708/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/people/chart/?id=emmastone.htm |archivedate=April 9, 2016 |df= }}</ref> The film, and her performance, received positive reviews from critics.<ref name=\"mojo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.watchmojo.com/video/id/13852/ |title=Top 10 Emma Stone Performances |date=June 3, 2015 |publisher=[[WatchMojo.com]] |accessdate=March 27, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160409091659/http://www.watchmojo.com/video/id/13852/ |archivedate=April 9, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Writing for ''Empire'', Anna Smith thought that Stone was \"well-meaning and hugely likable\" despite finding flaws in the character.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Smith |first1=Anna |title=The Help Review |url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/help-2/review/ |accessdate=April 11, 2016 |work=Empire |date=October 26, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160918025349/http://www.empireonline.com/movies/help-2/review/ |archivedate=September 18, 2016 |df= }}</ref> The film was nominated for an [[Academy Award for Best Picture]],<ref name=\"OAcademyAwards\">{{cite news|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130226215926/http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/legacy/ceremony/84th-winners.html|archivedate=February 26, 2013|url=http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/legacy/ceremony/84th-winners.html |title=The 84th Academy Awards (2012) Nominees and Winners |accessdate=March 29, 2016|publisher=[[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]]}}</ref> and won Best Ensemble Cast from the [[Women Film Critics Circle]] and the [[Broadcast Film Critics Association]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Adams |first1=Ryan |title=The Women Film Critics Circle Awards |url=http://www.awardsdaily.com/2011/12/19/the-women-film-critics-circle-awards/ |publisher=[[Awards Daily]] |accessdate=March 29, 2016 |date=December 19, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160411133735/http://www.awardsdaily.com/2011/12/19/the-women-film-critics-circle-awards/ |archivedate=April 11, 2016 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=17th Annual Critics' Choice Movie Awards (2012) |url=http://www.criticschoice.com/movie-awards/17th-annual-critics-choice-movie-awards-2012/ |publisher=[[Broadcast Film Critics Association]] |accessdate=March 29, 2016 |date=December 13, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121107224146/http://www.criticschoice.com/movie-awards/17th-annual-critics-choice-movie-awards-2012/ |archivedate=November 7, 2012 |df= }}</ref>\n\n===''The Amazing Spider-Man'', ''Birdman'', and Broadway (2012\u20132015)===\nStone declined a role in the action comedy film ''[[21 Jump Street (film)|21 Jump Street]]'' after signing on to [[Marc Webb]]'s 2012 film ''[[The Amazing Spider-Man (2012 film)|The Amazing Spider-Man]]'', a [[Reboot (fiction)|reboot]] of [[Sam Raimi]]'s [[Spider-Man in film#Sam Raimi films|''Spider-Man'' series]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2437995/emma-stone-21-jump-street-reboot/ |title=Exclusive: Emma Stone Not Starring in '21 Jump Street' Reboot |publisher=MTV |date=November 24, 2010 |accessdate=April 6, 2016 |author=Ditzian, Eric |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160415145956/http://www.mtv.com/news/2437995/emma-stone-21-jump-street-reboot/ |archivedate=April 15, 2016 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Kroll |first1=Justin |last2=Stewart |first2=Andrew |date=September 23, 2010 |url=https://variety.com/2010/biz/news/emma-stone-tangled-in-sony-s-web-1118024559/ |title=Emma Stone tangled in Sony's web |work=Variety |accessdate=March 23, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305074025/http://variety.com/2010/biz/news/emma-stone-tangled-in-sony-s-web-1118024559/ |archivedate=March 5, 2016 |df= }}</ref> She portrayed [[Gwen Stacy]], the love interest of the [[Spider-Man|title character]] (played by [[Andrew Garfield]]).<ref>{{cite news |first=Chris |last=Garcia |date=July 28, 2011 |title=Emma Stone has grown up since 'Easy A,' starring opposite Ryan Gosling in 'Crazy, Stupid, Love' Lya|work=New York Daily News |url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2011-07-28/entertainment/29840506_1_emma-stone-andrew-garfield-gwen-stacy |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121028171524/http://articles.nydailynews.com/2011-07-28/entertainment/29840506_1_emma-stone-andrew-garfield-gwen-stacy|archivedate=October 28, 2012|accessdate=March 23, 2016}}</ref> Stone returned to a blond hair color for the role, having dyed it red previously.<ref name=\"blonde\">{{cite web|url=http://news.instyle.com/2010/12/06/emma-stone-goes-blonde-for-spiderman/ |title=Emma Stone goes blonde for Spiderman |website=[[InStyle]] |date=December 6, 2010 |accessdate=March 23, 2016 |first=Kendall |last=Herbst |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120513051933/http://news.instyle.com/2010/12/06/emma-stone-goes-blonde-for-spiderman/ |archivedate=May 13, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy}}</ref><ref name=\"MTV Emma\">{{cite news|url=http://splashpage.mtv.com/2010/11/24/spider-man-emma-stone-gwen-stacy/ |title='Spider-Man' Star Emma Stone on Going Blonde, Science Class, And Becoming Gwen Stacy |publisher=MTV |date=November 24, 2010 |accessdate=November 30, 2011 |first=Erik |last=Ditzian |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120612155349/http://splashpage.mtv.com/2010/11/24/spider-man-emma-stone-gwen-stacy/ |archivedate=June 12, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy}}</ref> She told ''[[The Vancouver Sun]]'' that she felt responsible to educate herself about Spider-Man and admitted that she had not read the comics: \"My experience was with the Sam Raimi movies&nbsp;... I always assumed that [[Mary Jane Watson|Mary Jane]] was his first love\",<ref name=\"other woman\">{{cite news |last1=Lacker |first1=Chris |url=https://vancouversun.com/touch/interview+emma+stone+plays+spider+first+love/5152459/story.html?rel=5155561 |title=Interview: Emma Stone Plays Spider-Man's First Love |date=July 24, 2011 |accessdate=April 9, 2016 |work=[[The Vancouver Sun]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160805180300/http://www.vancouversun.com/touch/interview%2Bemma%2Bstone%2Bplays%2Bspider%2Bfirst%2Blove/5152459/story.html?rel=5155561 |archivedate=August 5, 2016 |df= }}</ref> adding that she was only familiar with Stacy's character from [[Bryce Dallas Howard]]'s portrayal in ''[[Spider-Man 3]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nbcchicago.com/blogs/popcornbiz/Amazing-Spider-Emma-Stone-Marc-Webb-144255585.html |title=\"Spider-Man\" Director and Star Talk Up \"Amazing\" New Film |publisher=[[WMAQ-TV|NBC Chicago]] |date=April 2, 2012 |accessdate=April 24, 2012 |last=Huver |first=Scott |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120331215138/http://www.nbcchicago.com/blogs/popcornbiz/Amazing-Spider-Emma-Stone-Marc-Webb-144255585.html |archivedate=March 31, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy }}</ref><ref name=\"Empire\">{{cite news|url=https://www.empireonline.com/news/story.asp?NID=31646 |title=Emma Stone on the Amazing Spider-Man |work=Empire |accessdate=November 26, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111228061738/http://www.empireonline.com/news/story.asp?nid=31646 |archivedate=December 28, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=mdy}}</ref> ''The Amazing Spider-Man'' was a commercial success and was [[2012 in film|the seventh highest-grossing film of 2012]] with global revenues of $757.9 million.<ref>{{cite web|title=2012 Worldwide Grosses |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?view2=worldwide&yr=2012&p=.htm |publisher=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=March 25, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160402034443/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?view2=worldwide&yr=2012&p=.htm |archivedate=April 2, 2016 |df= }}</ref> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''{{'s}} [[Lisa Schwarzbaum]] found Stone \"irresistible\",<ref>{{cite news|last1=Schwarzbaum |first1=Lisa |title=The Amazing Spider-Man |url=https://www.ew.com/article/2012/07/04/amazing-spider-man |accessdate=April 9, 2016 |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=July 4, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160405081326/http://www.ew.com/article/2012/07/04/amazing-spider-man |archivedate=April 5, 2016 |df= }}</ref> and [[Ian Freer]] of ''Empire'' magazine was particularly impressed with Stone's and Garfield's performances.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Freer |first1=Ian |title=The Amazing Spider-Man Review |url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/amazing-spider-man/review/ |accessdate=March 25, 2016 |work=Empire |date=July 3, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160406223101/http://www.empireonline.com/movies/amazing-spider-man/review/ |archivedate=April 6, 2016 |df= }}</ref> At the annual [[People's Choice Awards]] ceremony, she was nominated for three awards, including Favorite Movie Actress.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peopleschoice.com/pca/awards/nominees/index.jsp?year=2013|title=People's Choice Awards 2013 Nominees & Winners|publisher=[[People's Choice Awards]]|accessdate=March 24, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160128023759/http://www.peopleschoice.com/pca/awards/nominees/index.jsp?year=2013|archivedate=January 28, 2016}}</ref> Later that year, Stone voiced a role in the crime-based video game, ''[[Sleeping Dogs (video game)|Sleeping Dogs]]'', which earned her a [[Spike Video Game Award]] for Best Performance by a Human Female.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Horgan |first1=Richard |title=Xbox Users Set to Play with a Unique Awards Show Component \u2013 'Samuel L. Jackson Mode' |url=http://www.adweek.com/fishbowlny/2012-video-game-awards-spike-samuell-jackson-mark-burnett/186503 |accessdate=January 25, 2017 |work=[[Adweek]] |date=December 7, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170128135139/http://www.adweek.com/fishbowlny/2012-video-game-awards-spike-samuell-jackson-mark-burnett/186503 |archivedate=January 28, 2017 |df= }}</ref>\n\nStone began 2013 with a voice role in [[DreamWorks Animation|DreamWorks]]' ''[[The Croods]]'', an animated feature nominated for an [[Academy Award for Best Animated Feature]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://oscar.go.com/nominees?cid=AMPAS_oscarnominees |title=2014 Oscar Nominees |publisher=[[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]] |accessdate=March 30, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160506020834/http://oscar.go.com/nominees?cid=AMPAS_oscarnominees |archivedate=May 6, 2016 |df= }}</ref> This followed with an appearance in ''[[Movie 43]]'', an [[anthology film]] which consists of sixteen short stories\u2014she played the title role in the segment entitled \"Veronica\".<ref>{{cite news|first=M. Scot |last=Skinner |title=After 'Hours', a Q & A with star |date=November 4, 2010 |newspaper=[[Arizona Daily Star]] |url=http://tucson.com/entertainment/movies/article_4ab2465e-9a9f-58c7-9b54-c18b2d60d8e1.html |accessdate=November 7, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307081337/http://tucson.com/entertainment/movies/article_4ab2465e-9a9f-58c7-9b54-c18b2d60d8e1.html|archivedate=March 7, 2016}}</ref> The actress collaborated with Ryan Gosling and [[Sean Penn]] in Ruben Fleischer's ''[[Gangster Squad (film)|Gangster Squad]]'' (2013), a crime thriller set in Los Angeles during the 1940s.<ref>{{cite news|first1=Jeff |last1=Sneider |first2=Justin |last2=Kroll |title=Emma Stone rounds up 'Gangster Squad' |date=July 26, 2011 |magazine=Variety |url=https://variety.com/2011/film/news/emma-stone-rounds-up-gangster-squad-1118040460/ |accessdate=August 15, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130731201616/http://variety.com/2011/film/news/emma-stone-rounds-up-gangster-squad-1118040460/ |archivedate=July 31, 2013 |df= }}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]''{{'}} [[A. O. Scott]] dismissed the film as \"a hectic jumble of fedoras and zoot suits\", but praised her pairing with Gosling.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/01/11/movies/gangster-squad-with-sean-penn-ryan-gosling-and-emma-stone.html |title=These Law Enforcers Will Stop at Nothing |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=January 10, 2013 |accessdate=April 5, 2016 |author=Scott, A. O. |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170516073551/http://www.nytimes.com/2013/01/11/movies/gangster-squad-with-sean-penn-ryan-gosling-and-emma-stone.html |archivedate=May 16, 2017 |df= }}</ref> Stone expressed a desire to work with Gosling on more projects.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Radish|first1=Christina|url=https://collider.com/ryan-gosling-emma-stone-gangster-squad-interview/220638/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150622002414/http://collider.com/ryan-gosling-emma-stone-gangster-squad-interview/220638/|archivedate=June 22, 2015|title=Josh Brolin, Ryan Gosling, Emma Stone, and Director Ruben Fleischer Talk Gangster Squad|publisher=Collider.com|date=January 8, 2013|accessdate=April 5, 2016}}</ref>\n[[File:Emma Stone by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|left|180px|Stone at [[WonderCon]] in 2012]]\nIn 2014, Stone reprised the role of Gwen Stacy in ''[[The Amazing Spider-Man 2]]''. In an interview with ''[[Total Film]]'', the actress explained that her character was not dependent on the film's protagonist. \"She saves him more than he saves her. She's incredibly helpful to Spider-Man&nbsp;... He's the muscle, she's the brains.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Emma Stone talks saving Spidey in The Amazing Spider-Man 2|url=http://www.totalfilm.com/news/emma-stone-talks-saving-spidey-in-the-amazing-spider-man-2|accessdate=April 6, 2016|work=[[Total Film]]|date=January 4, 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140701013428/http://www.totalfilm.com/news/emma-stone-talks-saving-spidey-in-the-amazing-spider-man-2|archivedate=July 1, 2014}}</ref> Her performance was well received by critics;<ref>{{cite news|last=Silman |first=Anna |title=Review Roundup: The Amazing Spider-Man 2 Belongs to Emma Stone |url=https://www.vulture.com/2014/05/review-roundup-amazing-spider-man-2-emma-stone.html |accessdate=May 4, 2014 |work=[[New York (magazine)|Vulture.com]] |date=May 3, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140504140535/http://www.vulture.com/2014/05/review-roundup-amazing-spider-man-2-emma-stone.html |archivedate=May 4, 2014 |df= }}</ref> an ''Empire'' reviewer praised her for standing out in the film: \"Stone is the [[Heath Ledger]] of this series, doing something unexpected with an easily dismissed supporting character.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Newman |first1=Kim |title=The Amazing Spider-Man 2 Review |url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/amazing-spider-man-2/review/ |accessdate=May 14, 2016 |work=Empire |date=April 16, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160524190307/http://www.empireonline.com/movies/amazing-spider-man-2/review/ |archivedate=May 24, 2016 |df= }}</ref> The role earned her the Favorite Movie Actress award at the [[2015 Kids' Choice Awards]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/kids-choice-awards-complete-winners-783761 |title=Kids' Choice Awards 2015: The Complete Winners List |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=March 28, 2015 |accessdate=April 1, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160209001551/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/kids-choice-awards-complete-winners-783761 |archivedate=February 9, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Later that year, Stone took on a role in [[Woody Allen]]'s romantic comedy ''[[Magic in the Moonlight]]'', a modest commercial success.<ref name=\"Woody\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/aug/21/arthouse-blues-indie-films-terrible-summer |title=Arthouse blues: why did indie films have such a terrible summer? |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=August 21, 2015 |accessdate=April 7, 2016 |author=Smith, Nigel M |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160416183345/http://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/aug/21/arthouse-blues-indie-films-terrible-summer |archivedate=April 16, 2016 |df= }}</ref> A. O. Scott criticized her role, and pairing with [[Colin Firth]], describing it as \"the kind of pedantic nonsense that is meant to signify superior intellect\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Scott |first1=A. O. |title=Metaphysical Sleight of Heart |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/25/movies/magic-in-the-moonlight-another-woody-allen-odd-couple.html |accessdate=May 14, 2016 |work=The New York Times |date=July 24, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160715090504/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/25/movies/magic-in-the-moonlight-another-woody-allen-odd-couple.html |archivedate=July 15, 2016 |df= }}</ref>\n\nThe [[black comedy]]-drama ''[[Birdman (film)|Birdman]]'', from director [[Alejandro Gonz\u00e1lez I\u00f1\u00e1rritu]], was Stone's final film release in 2014. Co-starring [[Michael Keaton]] and [[Edward Norton]], the film features her in the role of Sam Thomson, the recovering-addict daughter of actor Riggan Thomson (Keaton), who becomes his assistant. I\u00f1\u00e1rritu created the character based on his experience with his daughter.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mitchell |first1=Elvis |title=Alejandro Gonz\u00e1lez I\u00f1\u00e1rritu |url=http://www.interviewmagazine.com/film/alejandro-gonzalez-inarritu/ |accessdate=April 8, 2016 |work=Interview |date=September 10, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160414004601/http://www.interviewmagazine.com/film/alejandro-gonzalez-inarritu/ |archivedate=April 14, 2016 |df= }}</ref> ''Birdman'' was critically acclaimed,<ref>{{cite news|last1=McMillan |first1=Graeme |title=The Secret Life of the Other Birdman |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/secret-life-birdman-775822 |accessdate=May 14, 2016 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=February 23, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160822124933/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/secret-life-birdman-775822 |archivedate=August 22, 2016 |df= }}</ref> and was the most successful film at the [[87th Academy Awards]]; it was nominated for nine awards, winning four, including Best Picture.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/2015 |title=The 87th Academy Awards (2015) Nominees and Winners |accessdate=February 23, 2015 |publisher=Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences (AMPAS) |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150223171100/http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/2015 |archivedate=February 23, 2015 |df= }}</ref> [[The Movie Network]] considered it one of Stone's best performances to date and [[Robbie Collin]] of ''The Daily Telegraph'' was impressed with a monologue she delivers, which he thought was \"like a knitting needle to the gut\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Brian |first1=Greg |title=Was 2014 the Most Significant Breakthrough Year for Emma Stone? Oscar Chances for 'Birdman' |url=http://www.themovienetwork.com/article/was-2014-most-significant-breakthrough-year-emma-stone-oscar-chances-birdman |publisher=[[The Movie Network]] |accessdate=April 9, 2016 |date=November 13, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160407213529/http://www.themovienetwork.com/article/was-2014-most-significant-breakthrough-year-emma-stone-oscar-chances-birdman |archivedate=April 7, 2016 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/2016/04/14/birdman-spectacular/ |title=Birdman: 'spectacular' |date=February 23, 2015 |work=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=April 30, 2016 |author=Collin, Robbie |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160502150729/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/2016/04/14/birdman-spectacular/ |archivedate=May 2, 2016 |df= }}</ref> She received numerous accolades for her portrayal, including nominations for an [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Academy]], a [[BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Supporting Role|BAFTA]], a [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actress \u2013 Motion Picture|Golden Globe]], a [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Supporting Role|Screen Actors Guild]], and a [[Critics' Choice Movie Award|Critics' Choice Movie]] award for Best Supporting Actress.<ref name=\"awards\">{{cite web|url=https://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/2015 |title=The 87th Academy Awards (2015) Nominees and Winners |publisher=Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences |accessdate=March 24, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151201224651/http://oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/2015 |archivedate=December 1, 2015 |df= }}<br />{{cite web|url=http://www.bafta.org/film/awards/supporting-actress-nominees-in-2015 |title=Supporting Actress Nominees in 2015 |publisher=British Academy of Film and Television Arts |accessdate=April 1, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160409132541/http://www.bafta.org/film/awards/supporting-actress-nominees-in-2015 |archivedate=April 9, 2016 |df= }}<br />{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/birdman-grand-budapest-pace-noms-for-critics-choice-awards-1201379383/ |title='Birdman,' 'Grand Budapest' Top Critics Choice Awards Nominations |work=Variety |date=December 15, 2014 |first=Tim |last=Gray |accessdate=March 31, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141216035611/http://variety.com/2014/film/news/birdman-grand-budapest-pace-noms-for-critics-choice-awards-1201379383/ |archivedate=December 16, 2014 |df= }}<br />{{cite web|title=72nd Annual Golden Globes Nominations |url=http://www.goldenglobes.com/articles/72nd-annual-golden-globes-nominations |publisher=[[Golden Globe Awards]] |accessdate=March 24, 2016 |date=December 11, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160407092619/http://www.goldenglobes.com/articles/72nd-annual-golden-globes-nominations |archivedate=April 7, 2016 |df= }}<br />{{cite web|title=The 21st Annual Screen Actors Guild Awards |url=http://www.sagawards.org/awards/nominees-and-recipients/21st-annual-screen-actors-guild-awards |publisher=[[Screen Actors Guild Awards]] |accessdate=March 31, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160316113714/http://sagawards.org/awards/nominees-and-recipients/21st-annual-screen-actors-guild-awards |archivedate=March 16, 2016 |df= }}</ref>\n\nFrom November 2014 to February 2015, Stone starred in a revival of the [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] musical ''[[Cabaret (musical)|Cabaret]]'' as [[Sally Bowles]], taking over the role from [[Michelle Williams (actress)|Michelle Williams]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2014/legit/reviews/broadway-review-emma-stone-in-cabaret-1201372234/ |title=Broadway Review: Emma Stone in 'Cabaret' |author=Stasio, Marilyn |date=December 5, 2014 |accessdate=April 8, 2016 |work=Variety |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305014529/http://variety.com/2014/legit/reviews/broadway-review-emma-stone-in-cabaret-1201372234/ |archivedate=March 5, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Considering it to be \"the most nerve-racking thing ever\", Stone told the ''Entertainment Weekly'' magazine that she listened to a French radio station to mentally prepare herself for the role.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2014/10/emma-stone-cabaret-taylor-swift |title=Emma Stone Is Mentally Preparing for the Moment Taylor Swift Sees Her Sing in Broadway's Cabaret |work=Vanity Fair |date=October 14, 2014 |accessdate=April 21, 2016 |author=Miller, Julie |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160413050737/http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2014/10/emma-stone-cabaret-taylor-swift |archivedate=April 13, 2016 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2015/01/emma-stone-cabaret-sally-bowles-pre-show-rituals |title=Here's What Emma Stone Does Before Each Cabaret Performance on Broadway |date=January 9, 2015 |accessdate=April 21, 2016 |author=Miller, Julie |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160412224855/http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2015/01/emma-stone-cabaret-sally-bowles-pre-show-rituals |archivedate=April 12, 2016 |df= }}</ref> ''Variety''{{'}}s Marilyn Stasio was critical of her singing and found her performance \"a bit narrow as an emotional platform, but a smart choice for her acting skills, the perfect fit for her sharp intelligence and kinetic energy.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Stasio |first1=Marilyn |title=Broadway Review: Emma Stone in 'Cabaret' |url=https://variety.com/2014/legit/reviews/broadway-review-emma-stone-in-cabaret-1201372234/ |accessdate=April 21, 2016 |work=Variety |date=December 5, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305014529/http://variety.com/2014/legit/reviews/broadway-review-emma-stone-in-cabaret-1201372234/ |archivedate=March 5, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Both of Stone's 2015 films{{nsmdns}}the romantic comedy-drama ''[[Aloha (2015 film)|Aloha]]'', and the mystery drama ''[[Irrational Man (film)|Irrational Man]]''{{nsmdns}}were critical and commercial failures, and her roles were panned by critics.<ref name=\"Woody\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=crowe2014.htm |title=Aloha |publisher=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=April 7, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160406031957/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=crowe2014.htm |archivedate=April 6, 2016 |df= }}<br />{{cite web|title=Irrational Man |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/irrational_man/ |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=May 16, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160510220256/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/irrational_man |archivedate=May 10, 2016 |df= }}<br />\n{{cite web|title=Aloha |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/aloha_2015 |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=May 16, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160517040533/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/aloha_2015 |archivedate=May 17, 2016 |df= }}</ref> In [[Cameron Crowe]]'s ''Aloha'', she took on the role of an air force pilot alongside [[Bradley Cooper]], and in the Woody Allen-directed ''Irrational Man'', she portrayed the romantic interest of [[Joaquin Phoenix]]'s character, a philosophy professor. The former was controversial for [[racebending|whitewashing]] the cast, as Stone's character was meant to be of Asian, Hawaiian, and Swedish descent; Stone later regretted the project, acknowledging whitewashing as a widespread problem in Hollywood.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rosen |first1=Christopher |title=Emma Stone says she understands Hollywood whitewashing after Aloha controversy |url=https://www.ew.com/article/2015/07/16/emma-stone-aloha-whitewashing |accessdate=April 7, 2016 |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=July 16, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160405112215/http://www.ew.com/article/2015/07/16/emma-stone-aloha-whitewashing |archivedate=April 5, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Despite the criticism, she was nominated for Choice Movie Actress \u2013 Comedy at the [[2015 Teen Choice Awards]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Teen Choice Awards 2015 Winners: Full List |url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/teen-choice-awards-winners-2015-full-list-1201571268/ |accessdate=April 7, 2016 |work=Variety |date=August 16, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160110215656/http://variety.com/2015/tv/news/teen-choice-awards-winners-2015-full-list-1201571268/ |archivedate=January 10, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Stone also appeared in the music video for [[Win Butler|Win Butler's]] single \"Anna\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Geslani |first1=Michael |title=Emma Stone is absolutely magnetic in Will Butler's \"Anna\" video \u2014 watch |url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2015/10/emma-stone-is-absolutely-magnetic-in-will-butlers-anna-video-watch/ |website=Consequence of Sound |accessdate=11 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161227161413/http://consequenceofsound.net/2015/10/emma-stone-is-absolutely-magnetic-in-will-butlers-anna-video-watch/ |archive-date=December 27, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===''La La Land'' and beyond (2016\u2013present)===\nDuring her ''Cabaret'' show, Stone met director [[Damien Chazelle]], who, impressed with her performance, cast her in his musical comedy-drama ''[[La La Land (film)|La La Land]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://deadline.com/2016/11/emma-stone-mel-gibson-la-la-land-hacksaw-ridge-lionsgate-contenders-1201847486/ |title= Emma Stone Reveals Unorthodox 'La La Land' Audition; Mel Gibson on 'Hacksaw Ridge' Inspiration&nbsp;\u2013 The Contenders |first= Matthew |last= Grobar |website= Deadline Hollywood |date= November 5, 2016 |accessdate= February 24, 2018 |archive-url= https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http://deadline.com/2016/11/emma-stone-mel-gibson-la-la-land-hacksaw-ridge-lionsgate-contenders-1201847486/&date=2018-06-22 |archive-date= June 22, 2018 |url-status= live }}</ref> The project, which marked her third collaboration with Gosling, featured Stone as Mia Dolan, an aspiring actress living in Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2016/03/07/ryan-gosling-emma-stone-la-la-land-release-date/ |title=Ryan Gosling, Emma Stone musical La La Land pushed to December |first=Devan |last=Coggan |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=March 7, 2016 |accessdate=April 7, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160407094609/http://www.ew.com/article/2016/03/07/ryan-gosling-emma-stone-la-la-land-release-date |archivedate=April 7, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Stone borrowed several real-life experiences for her character, and in preparation, watched ''[[The Umbrellas of Cherbourg]]'' and films of [[Fred Astaire and Ginger Rogers]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=McGovern |first1=Joe |title='La La Director' Director On the 'Timeless Glamour' of Ryan Gosling & Emma Stone |url=https://www.ew.com/article/2016/08/30/ryan-gosling-emma-stone-la-la-land |accessdate=November 7, 2016 |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=August 30, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161119070241/http://www.ew.com/article/2016/08/30/ryan-gosling-emma-stone-la-la-land |archivedate=November 19, 2016 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Alter, Ethan |title=Emma Stone on Reteaming With Ryan Gosling in 'La La Land' and Her New Appreciation of Los Angeles |url=https://www.yahoo.com/movies/emma-stone-on-reteaming-with-ryan-gosling-in-la-la-land-and-her-new-appreciation-of-los-angeles-120240431.html |publisher=[[Yahoo! Movies]] |date=September 16, 2016 |accessdate=November 7, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161110023416/https://www.yahoo.com/movies/emma-stone-on-reteaming-with-ryan-gosling-in-la-la-land-and-her-new-appreciation-of-los-angeles-120240431.html |archivedate=November 10, 2016 |df= }}</ref> For the [[La La Land (soundtrack)|musical's soundtrack]], she recorded six songs.{{efn|\"[[Another Day of Sun]]\", \"[[City of Stars]]\", \"Someone in the Crowd\", \"A Lovely Night\", \"[[Audition (The Fools Who Dream)]]\" and \"City of Stars (Humming)\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Desta |first1=Yohana |title=Emma Stone Shows Off Her Delicate Singing Voice in Soaring La La Land Trailer |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2016/08/emma-stone-singing-la-la-land |accessdate=January 12, 2017 |work=Vanity Fair |date=August 23, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161028083421/http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2016/08/emma-stone-singing-la-la-land |archivedate=October 28, 2016 |df= }}</ref>}} ''La La Land'' served as the opening film at the 2016 Venice Film Festival, and received highly positive reviews.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Vivarelli |first1=Nick |title=Damien Chazelle's 'La La Land' to Open Venice Film Festival in Competition |url=https://variety.com/2016/film/festivals/damien-chazelles-la-la-land-to-open-venice-film-festival-in-competition-1201797771/ |accessdate=September 3, 2016 |date=June 17, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160908012048/http://variety.com/2016/film/festivals/damien-chazelles-la-la-land-to-open-venice-film-festival-in-competition-1201797771/ |archivedate=September 8, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Besides being Stone's highest-rated film on the review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]],<ref name=\"rotten\">{{cite web|title=Emma Stone |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/celebrity/770683296 |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=July 30, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160910050042/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/celebrity/770683296 |archivedate=September 10, 2016 |df= }}</ref> the film was successful at the box office, earning over $440 million against its $30 million budget.<ref>{{cite web|title=La La Land (2016) |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=lalaland.htm |publisher=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=March 28, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170128222455/http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=lalaland.htm |archivedate=January 28, 2017 |df= }}</ref> Writing for ''[[The Guardian]]'', [[Peter Bradshaw]] reviewed, \"Stone has never been better: superbly smart, witty, vulnerable, her huge doe eyes radiating intelligence even, or especially, when they are filling with tears.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bradshaw |first1=Peter |title=La La Land review \u2013 Gosling and Stone sparkle in a gorgeous musical romance |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/jan/12/la-la-land-review-ryan-gosling-emma-stone-musical-romance-movie |accessdate=January 12, 2017 |work=The Guardian |date=January 12, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170112204822/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/jan/12/la-la-land-review-ryan-gosling-emma-stone-musical-romance-movie |archivedate=January 12, 2017 |df= }}</ref> Stone received an [[Academy Award for Best Actress|Academy]], [[BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Leading Role|BAFTA]], [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Motion Picture Comedy or Musical|Golden Globe]] and a [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Leading Role|SAG]] Award for Best Actress.<ref name=\"la la\">{{citation|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/awards/7647883/golden-globes-2017-winners-list |work=Billboard |date=January 8, 2017 |accessdate=January 8, 2017 |title=Here Is the 2017 Golden Globes Winners List |first=Taylor |last=Weatherby |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170109184352/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/awards/7647883/golden-globes-2017-winners-list |archivedate=January 9, 2017 |df= }}<br>{{cite news|title=Baftas 2017: full list of winners |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/feb/12/baftas-2017-film-full-list-of-winners |accessdate=February 12, 2017 |work=The Guardian |date=February 12, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170212225353/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/feb/12/baftas-2017-film-full-list-of-winners |archivedate=February 12, 2017 |df= }}<br>{{cite news|title=Oscar winners 2017: the full list updated live |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/feb/27/oscar-winners-2017-the-full-list-academy-awards |work=The Guardian |date=February 26, 2017 |accessdate=February 27, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170227032811/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/feb/27/oscar-winners-2017-the-full-list-academy-awards |archivedate=February 27, 2017 |df= }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Emma Stone (30498079137) (cropped).jpg|thumb|Stone at an event for ''[[Maniac (miniseries)|Maniac]]'' in 2018]]\n\nStone's sole film release of 2017 was the sports drama ''[[Battle of the Sexes (2017 film)|Battle of the Sexes]]'', based on the 1973 [[Battle of the Sexes (tennis)|eponymous match]] between tennis players [[Billie Jean King]] (Stone) and [[Bobby Riggs]] (Steve Carell). In preparation, Stone met with King, watched old footage and interviews of her, trained with a dialect coach to speak in King's accent, and drank high-calorie protein shakes to gain {{convert|15|lb}}.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Coggan|first1=Devan|title=Emma Stone on Preparing to Play Billie Jean King: 'I Was a Real Creep'|url=https://ew.com/movies/2017/08/15/emma-stone-battle-of-the-sexes-interview/|accessdate=September 20, 2017|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=August 15, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170921000701/http://ew.com/movies/2017/08/15/emma-stone-battle-of-the-sexes-interview/|archivedate=September 21, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Randone|first1=Amanda|title=How Emma Stone Gained 15 Pounds for Battle of the Sexes|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/881311/how-emma-stone-gained-15-pounds-for-battle-of-the-sexes|publisher=E!|accessdate=September 20, 2017|date=September 19, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170919205622/http://www.eonline.com/news/881311/how-emma-stone-gained-15-pounds-for-battle-of-the-sexes|archivedate=September 19, 2017}}</ref> The film premiered to positive reviews at the [[2017 Toronto International Film Festival]], and certain critics considered Stone's performance to be the best of her career.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Giles|first1=Jeff|title=American Made Is Certified Fresh|url=https://editorial.rottentomatoes.com/article/american-made-is-certified-fresh/|publisher=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=December 20, 2017|date=September 28, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171126190012/https://editorial.rottentomatoes.com/article/american-made-is-certified-fresh/|archivedate=November 26, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Benjamin Lee of ''The Guardian'' praised her for playing against type, and credited her for being \"strong\" and \"convincing\" in the part.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lee|first1=Benjamin|title=Battle of the Sexes review \u2013 Emma Stone serves up rousing, timely tennis drama|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/sep/11/battle-of-the-sexes-review-toronto-film-festival-tiff|accessdate=September 20, 2017|work=The Guardian|date=September 11, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170919185458/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/sep/11/battle-of-the-sexes-review-toronto-film-festival-tiff|archivedate=September 19, 2017}}</ref> Even so, the film earned less than its $25 million budget.<ref>{{cite news|author=Ende, Maura|title='Battle of the Sexes' has important messages about prejudice, sexuality|url=https://buffalonews.com/2017/10/11/battle-sexes-important-messages-prejudice-sexuality/|work=[[The Buffalo News]]|date=October 11, 2017|accessdate=September 20, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920084021/https://buffalonews.com/2017/10/11/battle-sexes-important-messages-prejudice-sexuality/|archive-date=September 20, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Stone received her fourth Golden Globe nomination for it, and attended the ceremony with King.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Pett |first1=Stephanie |title=Emma Stone Brings Billie Jean King, Who she Played in Battle of the Sexes, as Globes Date |url=https://people.com/movies/golden-globes-2018-emma-stone-brings-billie-jean-king/ |accessdate=September 8, 2018 |magazine=People |date=January 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180908164839/https://people.com/movies/golden-globes-2018-emma-stone-brings-billie-jean-king/ |archive-date=September 8, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Stone and [[Rachel Weisz]] starred as [[Abigail Masham]] and [[Sarah Churchill, Duchess of Marlborough|Sarah Churchill]], two cousins fighting for the affection of [[Anne, Queen of Great Britain|Queen Anne]] ([[Olivia Colman]]), in [[Yorgos Lanthimos]]'s historical comedy-drama ''[[The Favourite (film)|The Favourite]]''. Stone found it challenging being an American among a British cast, and had difficulty in mastering the accent.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Galloway |first1=Stephen |title=Telluride: Emma Stone Reveals Her Acting Breaking Points |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/emma-stones-reveals-acting-breaking-points-1139241 |accessdate=September 6, 2018 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=September 2, 2018 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904190438/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/emma-stones-reveals-acting-breaking-points-1139241 |archive-date=September 4, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The film premiered at the [[75th Venice International Film Festival]] in August.<ref>{{cite magazine |first=Ariston |last=Anderson |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/venice-film-festival-unveils-full-lineup-1129426 |title=Venice to Kick Off Awards Season With New Films From Coen Brothers, Luca Guadagnino and Alfonso Cuaron |magazine=The Hollywood Reporter |date=July 25, 2018 |accessdate=September 7, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180725121213/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/venice-film-festival-unveils-full-lineup-1129426 |archive-date=July 25, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Michael Nordine of [[IndieWire]] praised Stone for taking on a bold role after ''La La Land'', and termed the three leading ladies \"a majestic triumvirate in a period piece that's as tragic as it is hilarious.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Nordine |first1=Michael |title='The Favourite' Review: Yorgos Lanthimos' Royal Drama Is His Crowning Achievement \u2014 Venice |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2018/08/the-favourite-review-yorgos-lanthimos-emma-stone-venice-1201998762/ |publisher=IndieWire |accessdate=September 7, 2018 |date=August 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180907221353/https://www.indiewire.com/2018/08/the-favourite-review-yorgos-lanthimos-emma-stone-venice-1201998762/ |archive-date=September 7, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> For ''The Favourite'', Stone received her fifth Golden Globe nomination and third Oscar nomination.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/golden-globe-nominations-2019-1203082075/|title=Golden Globe Nominations: Complete List|date=December 6, 2018|work=Variety|access-date=December 6, 2018|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/74T7WuEQQ?url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/golden-globe-nominations-2019-1203082075/|archive-date=December 6, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/oscar-nominations-2019-complete-list-nominees-1172407|title=Oscars: Nominations List|date=January 22, 2019|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=January 22, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190122160706/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/oscar-nominations-2019-complete-list-nominees-1172407|archive-date=January 22, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> That September, she featured in and served as an executive producer for the [[Netflix]] dark comedy miniseries ''[[Maniac (miniseries)|Maniac]]'', co-starring Jonah Hill and directed by [[Cary Fukunaga]]. Stone and Hill played two strangers, Annie Landsberg and Owen Milgrim, whose lives are transformed due to a mysterious pharmaceutical trial. An admirer of Fukunaga's work, Stone agreed to the project without reading the script.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Jeffery |first1=Morgan |title=Emma Stone opens up about Maniac rewrites |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/ustv/news/a866529/emma-stone-maniac-netflix-interview/ |website=Digital Spy |accessdate=September 21, 2018 |language=en |date=September 21, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180921191143/http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/ustv/news/a866529/emma-stone-maniac-netflix-interview/ |archive-date=September 21, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Lucy Mangan]] of ''The Guardian'' praised Stone and Hill for playing against type and for delivering career-best performances;<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mangan |first1=Lucy |title=Maniac review \u2013 Jonah Hill and Emma Stone hit career highs in NYC dystopia |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2018/sep/21/maniac-review-jonah-hill-emma-stone-netflix-cary-fukunaga |accessdate=September 21, 2018 |work=The Guardian |date=September 21, 2018 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180921075620/https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2018/sep/21/maniac-review-jonah-hill-emma-stone-netflix-cary-fukunaga |archive-date=September 21, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Judy Berman of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' was similarly impressed with their growth as actors since ''Superbad'' and took note of the complexity in their performances.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Berman |first1=Judy |title=Maniac Is the Most Exciting Netflix Drama Since Stranger Things |url=http://time.com/5400995/maniac-netflix-review-emma-stone-jonah-hill/ |accessdate=September 21, 2018 |magazine=Time |date=September 20, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180921123618/http://time.com/5400995/maniac-netflix-review-emma-stone-jonah-hill/ |archive-date=September 21, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the same year, Stone appeared alongside [[Paul McCartney]] in a music video for his song \"[[Who Cares (Paul McCartney song)|Who Cares]]\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Grow |first1=Kory |title=See Paul McCartney, Emma Stone Shrug Off Bullies in 'Who Cares' Video |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/see-paul-mccartney-emma-stone-shrug-off-bullies-in-who-cares-video-771060/ |work=Rolling Stone |date=December 19, 2018 |accessdate=March 11, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190605062109/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/see-paul-mccartney-emma-stone-shrug-off-bullies-in-who-cares-video-771060/ |archive-date=June 5, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nStone reprised her role of Wichita in ''[[Zombieland: Double Tap]]'' (2019), which received mixed reviews and grossed $122 million worldwide.<ref>{{cite web |title= Zombieland: Double Tap (2019) |website= Rotten Tomatoes |url= https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/zombieland_double_tap/ |accessdate= November 14, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url= https://www.boxofficemojo.com/title/tt1560220/ |title= Zombieland: Double Tap (2019) |website= Box Office Mojo |access-date=January 17, 2020}}</ref> She will next star in ''[[Cruella (film)|Cruella]]'', a live-action spin-off of ''[[One Hundred and One Dalmatians]]'', in which she will portray [[Cruella de Vil]] (originally played by [[Glenn Close]] in the [[101 Dalmatians (1996 film)|1996 adaptation]]).<ref>{{cite web|last1=D'Alessandro |first1=Anthony |title=Disney Puts A Slew Of Dates On Hold For 'Jungle Book 2', 'Maleficent 2', 'Dumbo', 'Cruella' & More |url=https://deadline.com/2016/04/disney-fairy-tale-live-action-films-release-dates-jungle-book-2-cruella-dumbo-1201743988/ |accessdate=May 14, 2016 |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=April 25, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160513151039/http://deadline.com/2016/04/disney-fairy-tale-live-action-films-release-dates-jungle-book-2-cruella-dumbo-1201743988/ |archivedate=May 13, 2016 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Fleming Jr.|first1=Mike|title=Craig Gillespie In Talks To Direct Emma Stone In 'Cruella'|url=https://deadline.com/2018/12/emma-stone-craig-gillespie-cruella-director-live-action-1202514016/|accessdate=December 5, 2018|website=Deadline.com|date=December 4, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190606173711/https://deadline.com/2018/12/emma-stone-craig-gillespie-cruella-director-live-action-1202514016/|archive-date=June 6, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> She is also set to return as the voice of Eep in the sequel to ''The Croods'' and to star in the drama ''Love May Fail'', based on [[Matthew Quick]]'s 2015 novel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/11/emma-stone-love-may-fail-tristar-matthew-quick-silver-linings-playbook-1201627457/ |title=Emma Stone Boarding 'Love May Fail' As Hannah Minghella Brings Matthew Quick Book To TriStar |first=Mike, Jr. |last=Flemming |date=November 17, 2015 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=November 19, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151119045022/http://deadline.com/2015/11/emma-stone-love-may-fail-tristar-matthew-quick-silver-linings-playbook-1201627457/ |archivedate=November 19, 2015 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Kroll |first1=Kroll |title='Croods 2,' Revived as Animated Sequel, and Jason Blum's 'Spooky Jack' Get Release Dates |url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/croods-2-spooky-jack-release-dates-1202563635/ |accessdate=January 16, 2019 |website=Variety.com |date=September 19, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190604034547/https://variety.com/2017/film/news/croods-2-spooky-jack-release-dates-1202563635/ |archive-date=June 4, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|title='Sing 2' To Croon Summer 2021; 'The Croods 2' Moves To Holiday Season 2020|url=https://deadline.com/2019/04/sing-2-croods-2-release-date-changes-1202594951/|accessdate=July 5, 2019|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=April 12, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190828024514/https://deadline.com/2019/04/sing-2-croods-2-release-date-changes-1202594951/|archive-date=August 28, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nStone moved from Los Angeles to [[Greenwich Village]], New York City, in 2009.<ref name=\"Blackbook2009\">{{cite news|last=Barna|first=Ben|date=October 2, 2009|url=http://www.blackbookmag.com/article/zombielands-emma-stone-dreams-of-snl-and-mexican-food/11382|title='Zombieland's' Emma Stone Dreams of SNL and Mexican Food|work=[[BlackBook]] magazine|accessdate=October 2, 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111022221855/http://www.blackbookmag.com/article/zombielands-emma-stone-dreams-of-snl-and-mexican-food/11382|archivedate=October 22, 2011}}</ref> In 2016, she moved back to Los Angeles.<ref name=\"WSJ-IrrationalMan-2015\" /> Despite frequent media coverage, the actress has refused to speak about her private life. Concerned with living a \"normal\" life, she has said that she finds little value in media attention.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Malik |first1=Sonam |title=SAG Awards: 'The Amazing Spider-Man' Actress Emma Stone Spotted without Beau Andrew Garfield |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/sag-awards-amazing-spider-man-actress-emma-stone-spotted-without-beau-andrew-garfield-621647 |accessdate=March 16, 2016 |work=[[International Business Times]] |date=January 27, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160323003909/http://www.ibtimes.co.in/sag-awards-amazing-spider-man-actress-emma-stone-spotted-without-beau-andrew-garfield-621647 |archivedate=March 23, 2016 |df= }}</ref> She has expressed her fondness for her profession,<ref name=\"WSJ-IrrationalMan-2015\" /> and has cited actress [[Diane Keaton]] as an influence, who is (in Stone's words) \"one of the most covered-up actresses of all time\". She has also named actress and singer-songwriter [[Marion Cotillard]] as one of her inspirations.<ref name=\"vanityfair1\" />\n\n[[File:Emma Stone, Andrew Garfield 2014 (cropped).jpg|thumb|Stone with [[Andrew Garfield]] at ''[[The Amazing Spider-Man 2]]'' premiere in Sydney, 2014]]\n\nStone has a close relationship with her family.<ref name=\"vanityfair1\" /> She says: \"I am blessed with a great family and great people around me that would be able to kick me in the shins if I ever for one minute got lost up in the clouds. I've been really lucky in that sense.\"<ref name=\"Ask quote\">{{cite web|title=Emma Stone|url=http://www.askmen.com/celebs/women/celeb_profiles_actress_100/111_emma_stone.html|publisher=[[AskMen]]|accessdate=April 8, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090602071935/http://www.askmen.com/celebs/women/celeb_profiles_actress_100/111_emma_stone.html|archivedate=June 2, 2009}}</ref> During the production of ''The Amazing Spider-Man'' in 2010, Stone dated co-star [[Andrew Garfield]].<ref name=\"Emma Stone\">{{cite press release| url= http://www.sonypictures.com/corp/press_releases/2010/10_10/10052010_estone.html|title=Spider-Man Gets His Girl: Emma Stone To Play Female Lead|publisher=[[Sony Pictures]]|date=October 5, 2010|accessdate=March 19, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101009111726/http://www.sonypictures.com/corp/press_releases/2010/10_10/10052010_estone.html|archivedate=October 9, 2010}}</ref> Their relationship was reported in the media, with various speculations. The couple refused to talk about it publicly, though they made several appearances together. In 2014, on an occasion in New York, Stone and Garfield encouraged [[paparazzi]] to visit websites that spread awareness of causes such as [[autism]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Boy with Autism Thanks Emma Stone for Spreading Awareness |url=https://www.autismspeaks.org/news/news-item/boy-autism-thanks-emma-stone-spreading-awareness |publisher=[[Autism Speaks]] |accessdate=March 20, 2016 |date=June 20, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160329231255/https://www.autismspeaks.org/news/news-item/boy-autism-thanks-emma-stone-spreading-awareness |archivedate=March 29, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In 2015, they were reported to have broken up.<ref>{{cite news|title=Emma Stone and Andrew Garfield Have Reportedly Split For Good |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2015/10/emma-stone-andrew-garfield-break-up |accessdate=February 20, 2016 |work=Vanity Fair |date=October 27, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160302044751/http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2015/10/emma-stone-andrew-garfield-break-up |archivedate=March 2, 2016 |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"LA Times\">{{cite news|last1=Saad |first1=Nardine |title=Emma Stone, Andrew Garfield split 'a couple of months ago,' reports say |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/gossip/la-et-mg-emma-stone-andrew-garfield-split-20151027-story.html |date=October 28, 2015 |accessdate=February 20, 2016 |work=Los Angeles Times |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160220103816/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/gossip/la-et-mg-emma-stone-andrew-garfield-split-20151027-story.html |archivedate=February 20, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Since 2017, Stone has been in a romantic relationship with ''Saturday Night Live'' segment director [[Dave McCary]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Juneau |first1=Jen |title=He's Her Favourite! Emma Stone and Boyfriend Dave McCary Make Rare Appearance at SAG Awards |url=https://people.com/movies/sag-awards-2019-emma-stone-dave-mccary-rare-appearance/ |website=People |accessdate=17 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417115133/https://people.com/movies/sag-awards-2019-emma-stone-dave-mccary-rare-appearance/ |archive-date=April 17, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> They became engaged in December 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/movies/emma-stone-engaged-dave-mccary/|title=Emma Stone Engaged to SNL Writer Dave McCary After 2 Years of Dating|work=People|author=Ashley Boucher|date=December 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Stone, she suffers from [[asthma]], which she discovered after having difficulty breathing while filming ''Easy A''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Warner |first1=Kara |title=Emma Stone Recalls Asthma Attack During 'Easy A' Fake-Sex Scenes |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1647971/emma-stone-recalls-asthma-attack-during-easy-a-fake-sex-scenes/ |accessdate=March 16, 2016 |publisher=MTV News |date=September 15, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408212317/http://www.mtv.com/news/1647971/emma-stone-recalls-asthma-attack-during-easy-a-fake-sex-scenes/ |archivedate=April 8, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Her mother was diagnosed with [[triple-negative breast cancer]] and was cured in 2008.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Masica |first1=Kristen |title=Emma Stone: My Mom's Cancer Diagnosis 'Was Terrifying' |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20702530,00.html |accessdate=April 9, 2016 |work=People |date=May 22, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160513222906/http://www.people.com/people/article/0%2C%2C20702530%2C00.html |archivedate=May 13, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Stone and her mother celebrated by getting tattoos of birds' feet, designed by [[Paul McCartney]], a reference to [[the Beatles]]' \"[[Blackbird (Beatles song)|Blackbird]]\", which is a song she and her mother love.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Abrams |first1=Natalie |title=Emma Stone Has Paul McCartney Design Mother-Daughter Tattoo |url=https://www.tvguide.com/news/emma-stone-tattoo-1024493/ |accessdate=March 20, 2016 |work=TV Guide |date=October 18, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401225622/http://www.tvguide.com/news/emma-stone-tattoo-1024493/ |archivedate=April 1, 2016 |df= }}</ref> She appeared in a [[Revlon]] campaign that promoted breast cancer awareness.<ref name=\"eonline\">{{cite web|last1=Serfe |first1=Gina |title=Emma Stone Poses With Breast Cancer Survivor Mom in New Awareness Campaign |url=http://www.eonline.com/news/345364/emma-stone-poses-with-breast-cancer-survivor-mom-in-new-awareness-campaign |publisher=E! |accessdate=March 20, 2016 |date=September 12, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160508104714/http://www.eonline.com/news/345364/emma-stone-poses-with-breast-cancer-survivor-mom-in-new-awareness-campaign |archivedate=May 8, 2016 |df= }}</ref> In 2011, the actress featured in a collaborative video between ''[[Star Wars (film series)|Star Wars]]'' and [[Stand Up to Cancer]], which aimed to raise funds for cancer research.<ref>{{cite news|title='Star Wars' stands up to cancer, with the help of Andy Samberg, Emma Stone, Seth Rogen, and more! \u2013 Exclusive Video |url=https://www.ew.com/article/2011/09/15/star-wars-stand-up-to-cancer-exclusive-video |accessdate=March 20, 2016 |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=September 15, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160309090928/http://www.ew.com/article/2011/09/15/star-wars-stand-up-to-cancer-exclusive-video |archivedate=March 9, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Two years later, she attended an event by [[Gilda's Club]], an organization working for a similar purpose.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mcnally|first1=Kelby|title=Emma Stone goes au-naturel for charity event|url=http://www.express.co.uk/celebrity-news/400130/Emma-Stone-goes-au-naturel-for-charity-event|accessdate=March 20, 2016|work=[[Daily Express]]|date=May 16, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612162851/https://www.express.co.uk/celebrity-news/400130/Emma-Stone-goes-au-naturel-for-charity-event|archive-date=June 12, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> From 2012 to 2014, she hosted the [[Entertainment Industry Foundation]]'s Revlon Run/Walk, which helps fight women's cancer.<ref>{{cite web|title=Join the Fight Against Cancer: Entertainment Industry Foundation's Revlon Run/Walk For Women Announces 2014 Hosts for Annual Event|url=http://www.eifoundation.org/press-room/join-fight-against-cancer-entertainment-industry-foundations-revlon-runwalk-women-announc/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160329093709/http://www.eifoundation.org/press-room/join-fight-against-cancer-entertainment-industry-foundations-revlon-runwalk-women-announc/|archivedate=March 29, 2016|publisher=[[Entertainment Industry Foundation]]|accessdate=April 24, 2016|date=March 26, 2014}}</ref>\n\nStone, alongside three other celebrities, was present at the 2012 [[Nickelodeon HALO Awards]], a television special that profiled five teenagers who are \"Helping And Leading Others\" (HALO).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/tyra-banks-justin-bieber-josh-duhamel-and-emma-stone-honor-four-teens-for-their-commitment-to-service-in-fourth-annual-teennick-halo-awards-176414821.html |title=Tyra Banks, Justin Bieber, Josh Duhamel and Emma Stone Honor Four Teens for Their Commitment to Service in Fourth Annual TeenNick HALO Awards |date=October 30, 2012 |accessdate=March 20, 2016 |publisher=[[PR Newswire]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160403003834/http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/tyra-banks-justin-bieber-josh-duhamel-and-emma-stone-honor-four-teens-for-their-commitment-to-service-in-fourth-annual-teennick-halo-awards-176414821.html |archivedate=April 3, 2016 |df= }}</ref> She attended the 2014 [[Earth Hour]], a worldwide movement for the planet organized by the [[World Wide Fund for Nature]].<ref>{{cite web|title=2014 Celebrates the Biggest Earth Hour in History |url=https://www.earthhour.org/2014-celebrates-the-biggest-earth-hour-history |publisher=[[Earth Hour]] |accessdate=March 20, 2016 |date=March 30, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401002858/https://www.earthhour.org/2014-celebrates-the-biggest-earth-hour-history |archivedate=April 1, 2016 |df= }}</ref> In 2015, she was part of a fundraising event in support of the [[Motion Picture & Television Fund]], which helps people in the television and film industry with limited or no resources.<ref>{{cite news|title=2015 MPTF 'Night Before' Host Committee Members George Clooney, Eddie Redmayne, Reese Witherspoon, And More Attend 13th Annual Fundraiser in Support of MPTF |url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/2015-mptf-night-before-host-committee-members-george-clooney-eddie-redmayne-reese-witherspoon-and-more-attend-13th-annual-fundraiser-in-support-of-mptf-300039424.html |accessdate=March 20, 2016 |publisher=PR Newswire |date=February 22, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160402165300/http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/2015-mptf-night-before-host-committee-members-george-clooney-eddie-redmayne-reese-witherspoon-and-more-attend-13th-annual-fundraiser-in-support-of-mptf-300039424.html |archivedate=April 2, 2016 |df= }}</ref> In 2018, she collaborated with 300 women in Hollywood to set up the [[Time's Up (movement)|Time's Up]] initiative to protect women from harassment and discrimination.<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=McCarthy|first1=Lauren|title=Selena Gomez, Reese Witherspoon, And Emma Stone Among 300 Women In Hollywood to Sign Anti-Harassment Action Plan|url=https://www.wmagazine.com/story/times-up-open-letter-sexual-harassment-selena-gomez-reese-witherspoon|accessdate=January 4, 2018|magazine=W|date=January 1, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180103211443/https://www.wmagazine.com/story/times-up-open-letter-sexual-harassment-selena-gomez-reese-witherspoon|archivedate=January 3, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Media image==\n[[File:Emma Stone 2011 2.jpg|thumb|upright=0.9|left|Stone at the 2011 [[San Diego Comic-Con International]]. Her hair, eyes, and husky voice have been described as her trademarks by the media.<ref name=\"trade1\"/><ref name=\"trade\"/>]]\nSeveral media publications consider Stone one of her generation's most talented actresses.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/02/kristen-stewart-kelly-reichardt-project-1201383230/ |title=Kristen Stewart Joins Untitled Kelly Reichardt Project |last=Busch |first=Anita |date=February 28, 2015 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |language= |access-date=May 5, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160803172808/http://deadline.com/2015/02/kristen-stewart-kelly-reichardt-project-1201383230/ |archivedate=August 3, 2016 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/emma-stone-to-star-in-cameron-crowes-next-film-reworked-version-of-ben-stiller-reese-witherspoon-project-deep-tiki-20120730 |title=Emma Stone To Star In Cameron Crowe's Next Film, A Reworked Version Of 'Deep Tiki' |last=Lyttelton |first=Oliver |date=July 30, 2012 |website= |publisher=Indiewire |access-date=May 5, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140727073213/http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/emma-stone-to-star-in-cameron-crowes-next-film-reworked-version-of-ben-stiller-reese-witherspoon-project-deep-tiki-20120730 |archivedate=July 27, 2014 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Fitzpatrick |first1=Hayley |title=Emma Stone Is Unrecognizable in a Pixie Wig on the Cover of 'Vogue' |url=https://www.yahoo.com/style/emma-stone-wears-pixie-wig-and-discusses-the-wage-gap-in-hollywood-in-november-vogue-174401654.html |publisher=Yahoo! |accessdate=February 1, 2017 |date=October 14, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170109211904/https://www.yahoo.com/style/emma-stone-wears-pixie-wig-and-discusses-the-wage-gap-in-hollywood-in-november-vogue-174401654.html |archivedate=January 9, 2017 |df= }}</ref> Commenting on her performance in ''The Help'', Kirk Honeycutt of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' called her \"one of our very best young actresses\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/helps-emma-stone-what-critics-221417 |title='The Help's' Emma Stone: What Critics Say of Her Performance |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=August 10, 2011 |accessdate=March 29, 2016 |author=Powers, Lindsay |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160413150941/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/helps-emma-stone-what-critics-221417 |archivedate=April 13, 2016 |df= }}</ref> She is known for starring both in high-profile, mainstream productions and in low-budget independent films. ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''{{'s}} Daniel D'Addario describes the latter as \"substantive risk\" and adds that taking on a role in them provides her an opportunity to \"try something new and to get credibility\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=D'Addario |first1=Daniel |title=Here's Why Emma Stone's Artistic Alliance With Woody Allen Is So Complicated |url=http://time.com/3960218/emma-stone-woody-allen-joaquin-phoenix-irrational-man/ |accessdate=April 7, 2016 |work=Time |date=July 17, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160405174444/http://time.com/3960218/emma-stone-woody-allen-joaquin-phoenix-irrational-man/ |archivedate=April 5, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Analyzing her on-screen persona, Jessica Kiang of [[Indiewire]] noted that Stone \"usually [plays] the approachable, down-to-earth, girl-next-door type, [and] in person she demonstrates many of those qualities too, along with an absolute refusal to take herself too seriously.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kiang |first1=Jessica |title=Interview: Emma Stone Talks Comedy, 'The Croods' And Cameron Crowe; Scores Off The Charts On Likability |url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/berlin-interview-emma-stone-talks-comedy-the-croods-and-cameron-crowe-scores-off-the-charts-on-likability-20130224 |publisher=[[Indiewire]] |accessdate=April 7, 2015 |date=February 24, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130518110414/http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/berlin-interview-emma-stone-talks-comedy-the-croods-and-cameron-crowe-scores-off-the-charts-on-likability-20130224 |archivedate=May 18, 2013 |df= }}</ref>\n\nAs her career in Hollywood films has developed, Stone has become a successful and popular actress.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2012/01/05/emma-stone-little-white-corvette |title=Emma Stone 'acts' like a dude \u2013 and it's making her Hollywood's hottest young actress |date=January 5, 2012 |accessdate=April 6, 2016 |work=Entertainment Weekly |author=Labrecque, Jeff |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151108151844/http://www.ew.com/article/2012/01/05/emma-stone-little-white-corvette |archivedate=November 8, 2015 |df= }}</ref> In 2008, she topped ''[[Saturday Night Magazine (U.S.)|Saturday Night Magazine]]''{{'s}} Top 20 Rising Stars Under 30 and was included in a similar list compiled by [[Moviefone]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Top 20 Rising Stars Under 30|url=http://www.snmag.com/MAGAZINE/Features/Top-20-Rising-Stars-Under-30.html|accessdate=April 8, 2016|work=[[Saturday Night Magazine (U.S.)|Saturday Night Magazine]]|date=July 29, 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080924181516/http://www.snmag.com/MAGAZINE/Features/Top-20-Rising-Stars-Under-30.html|archivedate=September 24, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=MovieFone's 25 Hottest Young Stars Under 25 |url=http://www.accesshollywood.com/galleries/moviefones-25-hottest-young-stars-under-25-1561/#14 |work=Access Hollywood |accessdate=April 8, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160412072235/http://www.accesshollywood.com/galleries/moviefones-25-hottest-young-stars-under-25-1561/ |archivedate=April 12, 2016 |df= }}</ref> [[LoveFilm]] placed her on their list of 2010 Top 20 Actresses Under 30, and her performance in ''Easy A'' was included in ''Time''{{'s}} Top 10 Everything of 2010.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Corliss |first1=Richard |title=The Top 10 Everything of 2010 |url=http://content.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,2035319_2035307_2032774,00.html |accessdate=March 27, 2016 |work=Time |date=December 9, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160311134912/http://content.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0%2C28804%2C2035319_2035307_2032774%2C00.html |archivedate=March 11, 2016 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=2010 Top 20 Actresses Under 30|url=http://www.lovefilm.com/features/detail.html?section_name=newsletter&editorial_id=24704|publisher=[[LoveFilm]]|accessdate=April 8, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110702120342/http://www.lovefilm.com/features/detail.html?section_name=newsletter&editorial_id=24704|archivedate=July 2, 2011}}</ref> She appeared in the 2013 [[Celebrity 100]], a compilation of the 100 most powerful people in the world, as selected annually by ''[[Forbes (magazine)|Forbes]]''. The magazine reported that she had earned $16 million from June 2012 to June 2013.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pomerantz |first1=Dorothy |title=Celebrity 100 Sneak Peek: Emma Stone Makes Our List For The First Time |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/dorothypomerantz/2013/06/25/celebrity-100-sneak-peek-emma-stone-makes-our-list-for-the-first-time/#13daeb4b2681 |accessdate=April 7, 2016 |work=[[Forbes (magazine)|Forbes]] |date=June 25, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422015311/http://www.forbes.com/sites/dorothypomerantz/2013/06/25/celebrity-100-sneak-peek-emma-stone-makes-our-list-for-the-first-time/ |archivedate=April 22, 2016 |df= }}</ref> That same year, she was ranked first in the magazine's Top 10 Best Value Stars.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Child |first1=Ben |title=Emma Stone tops Forbes list of 'best value' Hollywood stars |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2013/dec/24/emma-stone-best-value-film-star-investment-return |accessdate=April 8, 2016 |work=The Guardian |date=December 24, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160417141613/http://www.theguardian.com/film/2013/dec/24/emma-stone-best-value-film-star-investment-return |archivedate=April 17, 2016 |df= }}</ref> In 2015, ''Forbes'' published that she had become one of the highest-paid actresses with earnings of $6.5 million.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Robehmed |first1=Natalie |title=The World's Highest-Paid Actresses 2015: Jennifer Lawrence Leads With 52 Million |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/natalierobehmed/2015/08/20/the-worlds-highest-paid-actresses-2015-jennifer-lawrence-leads-with-52-million/#5e9aa1c23820 |accessdate=April 7, 2016 |work=Forbes |date=August 21, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160405063521/http://www.forbes.com/sites/natalierobehmed/2015/08/20/the-worlds-highest-paid-actresses-2015-jennifer-lawrence-leads-with-52-million/ |archivedate=April 5, 2016 |df= }}</ref> The magazine would rank her as the world's highest-paid actress two years later with yearly earnings of $26 million.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Robehmed|first1=Natalie|title=The World's Highest-Paid Actresses 2017: Emma Stone Leads With $26 Million|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/natalierobehmed/2017/08/16/the-worlds-highest-paid-actresses-2017-emma-stone-leads-with-26-million/#641f066911e6|accessdate=August 17, 2017|work=Forbes|date=August 16, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170817044520/https://www.forbes.com/sites/natalierobehmed/2017/08/16/the-worlds-highest-paid-actresses-2017-emma-stone-leads-with-26-million/#641f066911e6|archivedate=August 17, 2017}}</ref> In 2017, she was featured by ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' as one of the [[Time 100|100 most influential people in the world]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Larson |first1=Brie |title=Time 100: Emma Stone |url=http://time.com/collection/2017-time-100/4736213/emma-stone/ |accessdate=April 21, 2017 |work=Time |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170420220918/http://time.com/collection/2017-time-100/4736213/emma-stone/ |archivedate=April 20, 2017 |df= }}</ref>\n\nStone has been described as a style icon{{nsmdns}}the media cites her hair, eyes, and husky voice as her trademarks.<ref name=\"trade1\">{{cite web|last1=Watson |first1=Sheridan |title=31 Photos That Prove Emma Stone Is The Most Stylish Person on Earth |url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/sheridanwatson/photos-that-prove-emma-stone-is-the-most-stylish-person |publisher=[[BuzzFeed]] |accessdate=April 7, 2016 |date=October 17, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150829080504/http://www.buzzfeed.com/sheridanwatson/photos-that-prove-emma-stone-is-the-most-stylish-person |archivedate=August 29, 2015 |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"trade\">{{cite news|last1=Stern |first1=Marlow |title=Emma Stone On 'The Amazing Spider-Man,' Andrew Garfield, & More |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2012/06/26/emma-stone-on-the-amazing-spider-man-andrew-garfield-more.html |accessdate=April 7, 2016 |work=[[The Daily Beast]] |date=June 26, 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160407170215/http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2012/06/26/emma-stone-on-the-amazing-spider-man-andrew-garfield-more.html |archivedate=April 7, 2016 |df= }}</ref> ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' credits the actress for her \"sophisticated, perfectly put-together looks\", writing that \"her charisma, both on-screen and off-, has charmed many.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Emma Stone's Best Red\u2013Carpet Moments |url=http://www.vogue.com/868846/emma-stone-best-red-carpet-moments/ |accessdate=April 7, 2016 |work=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]] |date=April 15, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160418055522/http://www.vogue.com/868846/emma-stone-best-red-carpet-moments/ |archivedate=April 18, 2016 |df= }}</ref> In 2009, she featured in [[AskMen|AskMen's]] Top 99 Women, ''[[FHM]]''{{'s}} [[FHM's 100 Sexiest Women (UK)|100 Sexiest Women in the World]], and ''[[Maxim (magazine)|Maxim]]'' magazine's Hot 100;<ref name=\"Ask quote\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=The 100 Sexiest Women in the World |url=http://www.fhmonline.com/Site/customPage/DefaultPlain.aspx?ID=40563 |accessdate=April 8, 2016 |work=[[FHM]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090707094703/http://www.fhmonline.com/Site/customPage/DefaultPlain.aspx?ID=40563 |archivedate=July 7, 2009 }}<br />{{cite news|title=2009 Hot 100 List |url=http://www.maxim.com/women/2009-hot-100-post |accessdate=April 8, 2016 |work=[[Maxim (magazine)|Maxim]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160413060220/http://www.maxim.com/women/2009-hot-100-post |archivedate=April 13, 2016 |df= }}</ref> the latter also placed her on the list on three other occasions{{nsmdns}}2010, 2011, and 2014.<ref>{{cite news|title=2010 Hot 100 List |url=http://www.maxim.com/women/2010-hot-100-post |accessdate=April 8, 2016 |work=Maxim |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160401121236/http://www.maxim.com/women/2010-hot-100-post |archivedate=April 1, 2016 |df= }}<br />{{cite news|title=2011 Hot 100 List |url=http://www.maxim.com/women/2011-hot-100-post |accessdate=April 8, 2016 |work=Maxim |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160406052023/http://www.maxim.com/women/2011-hot-100-post |archivedate=April 6, 2016 |df= }}<br />{{cite news|title=2014 Hot 100 List |url=http://www.maxim.com/women/2014-hot-100-post |accessdate=April 8, 2016 |work=Maxim |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160412180232/http://www.maxim.com/women/2014-hot-100-post |archivedate=April 12, 2016 |df= }}</ref> She continued to be featured in AskMen's annual beauty lists from 2010 to 2015, ranking among the top forty each year.<ref>{{cite web |title=Top 99 Women |url=http://www.askmen.com/specials/2011_top_99/32-emma-stone.html |publisher=AskMen |accessdate=April 8, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110803220157/http://www.askmen.com/specials/2011_top_99/32-emma-stone.html |archivedate=August 3, 2011 }}<br />{{cite web |title=Top 99 Women of 2012 |url=http://www.askmen.com/specials/2012_top_99/6-emma-stone.html |publisher=AskMen |accessdate=April 8, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120203044117/http://www.askmen.com/specials/2012_top_99/6-emma-stone.html |archivedate=February 3, 2012 }}<br />{{cite web |title=Emma Stone AskMen Top 99 2013 Video |url=http://www.askmen.com/video/entertainment-and-celebrities/emma-stone-askmen-top-99-2013-video.html |publisher=AskMen |accessdate=April 9, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422155849/http://www.askmen.com/video/entertainment-and-celebrities/emma-stone-askmen-top-99-2013-video.html |archivedate=April 22, 2016 |df= }}<br />{{cite web |title=Top 99 Women of 2014 |url=http://www.askmen.com/specials/2014_top_99/28-emma-stone.html |publisher=AskMen |accessdate=April 8, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408054957/http://www.askmen.com/specials/2014_top_99/28-emma-stone.html |archivedate=April 8, 2016 |df= }}<br />{{cite web |title=Top 99 Women of 2015 |url=http://www.askmen.com/specials/2015_top_99/27-emma-stone.html |publisher=AskMen |accessdate=April 8, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160419223419/http://www.askmen.com/specials/2015_top_99/27-emma-stone.html |archivedate=April 19, 2016 |df= }}</ref> In 2011, she appeared in [[Victoria's Secret|Victoria's Secret's]] list of What is Sexy? as the Sexiest Actress.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Derschowitz |first1=Jessica |title=Emma Stone, Rihanna top Victoria's Secret's \"What is Sexy?\" list |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/emma-stone-rihanna-top-victorias-secrets-what-is-sexy-list/ |publisher=[[CBS News]] |accessdate=April 7, 2016 |date=May 12, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160420184251/http://www.cbsnews.com/news/emma-stone-rihanna-top-victorias-secrets-what-is-sexy-list/ |archivedate=April 20, 2016 |df= }}</ref> She was mentioned in several other media outlet lists that year, including ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' magazine's 100 Most Beautiful Women, each of ''FHM''{{'s}} and ''[[FHM Australia]]''{{'s}} 100 Sexiest Women in the World, and ''[[Men's Health]]'' magazine's 100 Hottest Women.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.people.com/people/package/gallery/0,,20360857_20481337_20936743,00.html |title=World's Most Beautiful 2011 |work=People |accessdate=April 8, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160508073049/http://www.people.com/people/package/gallery/0%2C%2C20360857_20481337_20936743%2C00.html |archivedate=May 8, 2016 |df= }}<br />{{cite news|url=http://www.fhm.com/girls/100-sexiest-women |title=FHM's 100 Sexiest Women in the World 2011 |work=FHM |date=May 5, 2011 |accessdate=April 8, 2016 |author=Moody, Jon |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111230002746/http://www.fhm.com/girls/100-sexiest-women |archivedate=December 30, 2011 }}<br />{{cite news|url=http://www.fhm.com.au/view_image.htm?index=62&gid=17384 |title=FHM's 100 Sexiest Women in the World |work=[[FHM Australia]] |accessdate=April 8, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321200202/http://www.fhm.com.au/view_image.htm?index=62&gid=17384 |archivedate=March 21, 2012 }}<br />{{cite news|url=http://www.menshealth.com/sex-women/hottest-women-2011 |title=The Hottest Women of 2011 |work=[[Men's Health]] |accessdate=April 8, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111228191141/http://www.menshealth.com/sex-women/hottest-women-2011 |archivedate=December 28, 2011 }}</ref> She ranked sixth on ''Empire''{{'s}} list of the 100 Sexiest Movie Stars in 2013.<ref>{{cite news|title=The 100 Sexiest Movie Stars: The Top 20 |url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/100-sexiest/ |accessdate=August 29, 2016 |work=Empire |date=October 7, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160828220419/http://www.empireonline.com/movies/features/100-sexiest/ |archivedate=August 28, 2016 |df= }}</ref> Stone was named the best dressed woman of 2012 by ''Vogue'' magazine and was featured in similar listings by ''[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]]'' in 2013 and 2015, and ''People'' in 2014.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.vogue.com/slideshow/778652/best-dressed-of-2012-photos/#1 |title=Photos: The Best Dressed of 2012 |work=Vogue |accessdate=April 8, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160418142952/http://www.vogue.com/slideshow/778652/best-dressed-of-2012-photos/#1 |archivedate=April 18, 2016 |df= }}<br />{{cite news |title=50 Best Dressed Women 2013 |url=http://www.glamourmagazine.co.uk/fashion/celebrity-fashion/2013/glamour-best-dressed-women-2013/viewgallery/954094 |accessdate=April 8, 2016 |work=Glamour |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160419063927/http://www.glamourmagazine.co.uk/fashion/celebrity-fashion/2013/glamour-best-dressed-women-2013/viewgallery/954094 |archivedate=April 19, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}<br />{{cite news |title=30 Best Dressed Women of 2015 |url=http://www.glamourmagazine.co.uk/fashion/celebrity-fashion/2015/09/best-dressed-women-2015/viewgallery/1456202 |accessdate=April 8, 2016 |work=Glamour |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160415031549/http://www.glamourmagazine.co.uk/fashion/celebrity-fashion/2015/09/best-dressed-women-2015/viewgallery/1456202 |archivedate=April 15, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://stylenews.peoplestylewatch.com/2014/09/17/best-dressed-taylor-swift-jennifer-lopez-style/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160220110441/http://stylenews.peoplestylewatch.com/2014/09/17/best-dressed-taylor-swift-jennifer-lopez-style/|archivedate=February 20, 2016 |title=People's Best Dressed, Taylor Swift Best Dressed 2014 |website=People |date=September 17, 2014 |accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> In 2017, [[Buzznet]] named her one of the world's most beautiful women.<ref>{{cit news|title=Top 30 World's Most Beautiful Women of 2017 |url=http://www.buzznet.com/2017/03/top-30-worlds-most-beautiful-women-of-2017/ |publisher=[[Buzznet]] |date=March 10, 2017 |accessdate=April 23, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170420235117/http://www.buzznet.com/2017/03/top-30-worlds-most-beautiful-women-of-2017/ |archivedate=April 20, 2017 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==Works and accolades==\n{{Main|List of Emma Stone performances|List of awards and nominations received by Emma Stone|l2=awards and nominations}}\nAccording to the review aggregator site [[Rotten Tomatoes]] and the box-office site [[Box Office Mojo]], Stone's most critically acclaimed and commercially successful films are ''Superbad'' (2007), ''Zombieland'' (2009), ''Easy A'' (2010), ''Crazy, Stupid, Love'' (2011), ''The Help'' (2011), ''The Amazing Spider-Man'' (2012), ''The Amazing Spider-Man 2'' (2014), ''Birdman'' (2014), ''La La Land'' (2016), ''Battle of the Sexes'' (2017), and ''The Favourite'' (2018).<ref name=\"rotten\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Emma Stone|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/people/chart/?view=Actor&id=emmastone|publisher=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=July 30, 2016}}</ref>\n\nStone has been nominated for three [[Academy Awards]]: Best Supporting Actress for ''Birdman'' and ''The Favourite'', and Best Actress for ''La La Land''; and four [[British Academy Film Awards]]: BAFTA Rising Star Award, Best Supporting Actress for ''Birdman'' and ''The Favourite'', and Best Actress in a Leading Role for ''La La Land''. She won the Best Actress award at both ceremonies for ''La La Land''.<ref name=\"EasyA\"/><ref name=\"awards\"/><ref name=\"la la\"/> Stone also won Best Actress in a Comedy or Musical at the [[74th Golden Globe Awards]], Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Leading Role at the [[23rd Screen Actors Guild Awards]] and [[Volpi Cup for Best Actress]] at [[73rd Venice International Film Festival|Venice Film Festival]] for her role in ''La La Land''.<ref name=\"la la\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/awards/2017/01/29/sag-awards-2017-winners-see-the-full-list/ |title=SAG Awards 2017 winners: See the full list |website=The Hollywood Reporter |date=January 30, 2016 |accessdate=February 1, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170131123633/http://ew.com/awards/2017/01/29/sag-awards-2017-winners-see-the-full-list/ |archivedate=January 31, 2017 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.labiennale.org/en/cinema/73rd-festival/awards |title=Official Awards of the 73rd Venice Film Festival |work=labiennale.org |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161008224708/http://www.labiennale.org/en/cinema/73rd-festival/awards |archivedate=8 October 2016 |access-date=20 April 2018  }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of actors with two or more Academy Award nominations in acting categories]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|25em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name|1297015|name=Emma Stone}}\n* {{IBDB name|497842|name=Emma Stone}}\n* {{Tcmdb name|1455286|name=Emma Stone}}\n* {{AllMovie name|491706|name=Emma Stone}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes person|emma-stone|name=Emma Stone}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title = [[List of awards and nominations received by Emma Stone|Awards for Emma Stone]]\n|list  = \n{{Academy Award Best Actress}}\n{{AACTA International Award for Best Actress}}\n{{BAFTA Award for Best Actress in a Leading Role}}\n{{Boston Society of Film Critics Award for Best Supporting Actress}}\n{{Golden Globe Award Best Actress Motion Picture Musical or Comedy}}\n{{MTV Movie Award for Best 