{"title_page": "2006 in Singapore", "text_new": "{{Dynamic list}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{Year in Singapore|2006}}\n\nThe following lists events that happened during '''[[2006]] in [[Singapore]]'''.\n\n==Incumbents==\n*[[President of Singapore|President]]: [[S.R. Nathan]]\n*[[Prime Minister of Singapore|Prime Minister]]: [[Lee Hsien Loong]]\n\n==Events==\n===January===\n[[File:Buangkok MRT Station 3, Aug 06.JPG|thumb|right|300px|Buangkok MRT station]]\n* 3 January - The National Research Foundation is established to set the direction of [[research and development]] initiatives.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nrf.gov.sg/about-nrf/national-research-foundation-singapore/nrf-milestones|title=NRF Milestones|date=2019|accessdate=30 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190421081100/https://www.nrf.gov.sg/about-nrf/national-research-foundation-singapore/nrf-milestones|archive-date=21 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 7 January - The new [[Supreme Court of Singapore|Supreme Court]] building is officially opened.<ref>{{cite web |title=Official Opening of the new Supreme Court Building |url=https://www.istana.gov.sg/Newsroom/Speeches/2006/01/07/S-R-Nathan-at-the-Official-Opening-of-the-new-Supreme-Court-Building |publisher=Istana |accessdate=11 August 2019 |date=7 January 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190811112005/https://www.istana.gov.sg/Newsroom/Speeches/2006/01/07/S-R-Nathan-at-the-Official-Opening-of-the-new-Supreme-Court-Building |archive-date=11 August 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* 9 January - The [[Ministry of Education (Singapore)|Ministry of Education]] announced that a single intake for junior college and centralised institute admissions will be implemented from January 2009. This is made possible as the [[Singapore Examinations and Assessment Board]] moves to take greater control of the [[Singapore-Cambridge GCE Ordinary Level|O Level]] examinations from this year.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wong |first1=Siew Ying |title=Single intake for junior colleges, centralised institutes from 2009 |url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/187347/1/.html |publisher=Channel NewsAsia |accessdate=11 August 2019 |date=9 January 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060111082136/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/187347/1/.html |archive-date=11 January 2006 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* 12 January - The first $2 polymer notes are released.<ref>{{cite web|title=MAS Issues $2 Polymer Notes|url=https://www.mas.gov.sg/news/media-releases/2005/mas-issues-2dollars-polymer-notes|website=MAS|accessdate=15 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715180154/https://www.mas.gov.sg/news/media-releases/2005/mas-issues-2dollars-polymer-notes|archive-date=15 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 13 January - 27 students from [[Raffles Girls' School (Secondary)|Raffles Girls' School]] sold [[Buangkok MRT station#Second white elephant incident|white elephant shirts]] for a carnival at [[Buangkok MRT station]] to raise funds for a youth organisation, sparling a [[Singapore Police Force|police]] reaction.<ref>{{cite news |title=Teens' white elephant T-shirt venture gets police attention |publisher=Today (Singapore newspaper) |date=14 January 2006 |url=http://www.todayonline.com/articles/95206.asp |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060116035840/http://www.todayonline.com/articles/95206.asp |archivedate=16 January 2006 }}</ref> On 21 January however, then Deputy Prime Minister [[Wong Kan Seng]] apologised for the overreaction by the police.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ng |first1=Julia |title=Police overreacted to white elephant T-shirt incident: DPM Wong |publisher=Channel NewsAsia |date=21 January 2006 |url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/189327/1/.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930235446/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/189327/1/.html |archivedate=30 September 2007 }}</ref>\n* 15 January - [[Buangkok MRT station]] opens on the [[North East MRT line]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Buangkok NEL Station Commences Revenue Service Amid Great Fanfare|url=https://www.sbstransit.com.sg/press/2006jan_15-1.aspx|website=SBS Transit|accessdate=29 August 2019|date=15 January 2006}}</ref>\n* 16 January - A statement on [[National service in Singapore|NS defaulters]] is delivered in [[Parliament of Singapore|Parliament]] after the case of [[Melvyn Tan]] in 2005. It sparked a controversy due to the fine imposed.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ministerial statement on National Service defaulters |url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/speeches/view-html?filename=20060116991.htm |publisher=NAS |accessdate=23 July 2019 |date=16 January 2006}}</ref> \n* 17 January - The [[Workplace Safety and Health Act]] is passed to ensure better workplace safety and health standards, after several high-profile accidents. The law came into effect on 1 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sso.agc.gov.sg/Act/WSHA2006?ProvIds=xv-#xv-|title=Workplace Safety & Health Act|publisher=AGC|accessdate=27 July 2019}}</ref>\n* 19 January - The Somerset Skate Park is officially opened.<ref>{{cite web|title=News release: Bigger, better Somerset skate park opens in Orchard. |url=http://nyc.pa.gov.sg/newss/pdf/1323682440MR---Launch-of-Somerset-Skate-Park.pdf |publisher=National Youth Council |access-date=1 September 2019 |date=19 January 2006 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=National Youth Council |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_419_2005-01-06.html |publisher=NLB |access-date=1 September 2019}}</ref>\n* 20 January - The City Campus of [[Singapore Management University]] officially opened.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smu.edu.sg/news/2006/01/20/singapore-management-university-celebrates-official-opening-city-campus|title=Singapore Management University celebrates Official Opening of City Campus|date=20 January 2006|accessdate=30 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190630115224/https://www.smu.edu.sg/news/2006/01/20/singapore-management-university-celebrates-official-opening-city-campus|archive-date=30 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 23 January - [[Temasek Holdings|Temasek]] buys over [[Sale of Shin Corporation to Temasek Holdings|Shin Corporation]] with [[Siam Commercial Bank]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.temasek.com.sg/en/news-and-views/news-room/news/2006/temasek-scb-led-investor-group-acquires-shinawatra-and-damapong-.html |title=Temasek-SCB led investor group acquires Shinawatra and Damapong Families\u2019 stakes in Shin Corp |website=Temasek Holdings |date=23 January 2006 |accessdate=20 September 2019}}</ref> causing a controversy.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thestar.com.my/business/business-news/2006/01/24/temasek-buys-shin-corp/|title=Temasek buys Shin Corp |website=The Star |accessdate=22 July 2019 |date=24 January 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722015730/https://www.thestar.com.my/business/business-news/2006/01/24/temasek-buys-shin-corp/ |archive-date=22 July 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Nonetheless, the deal is completed on 24 March.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.temasek.com.sg/en/news-and-views/news-room/news/2006/shin-bid-consortium-partners-complete-tender-offer-for-ais.html |title=Shin-bid Consortium Partners Complete Tender Offer for AIS |website=Temasek Holdings |date=24 March 2006 |accessdate=20 September 2019}}</ref>\n* 26 January - \n**[[I Not Stupid Too]] is released in cinemas as a sequel to [[I Not Stupid]].\n**[[Zodiac: The Race Begins]] is released as Singapore's first [[3D animation|3D animated]] film.\n\n===February===\n* 3 February - In response to the [[Jyllands-Posten Muhammad cartoons controversy]], the Islamic Religious Council of Singapore ([[Majlis Ugama Islam Singapura|Majlis Ugama Islam Singapura (MUIS)]]) issued a statement that says \"the inciting of hatred against a faith of a people is very unfortunate.\" Foreign Minister [[George Yeo]] and the [[Minister-in-charge of Muslim Affairs]] [[Yaacob Ibrahim]] have similarly said that the incident shows the need to respect racial and religious sensitivities, to have a \"responsible media\", and to cultivate good inter-religious relations and confidence beyond just legislation.\n* 8 February - The [[Monetary Authority of Singapore]] announced the setting up of Singapore Deposit Insurance Corporation Limited (SDIC) to manage deposit insurance.<ref>{{cite web |title=Establishment of Singapore Deposit Insurance Corporation Limited |url=https://www.mas.gov.sg/news/media-releases/2006/establishment-of-singapore-deposit-insurance |website=MAS |accessdate=20 April 2020 |date=8 February 2006}}</ref> \n* 10 February - The Secretary General of [[Singapore Democratic Party]], [[Chee Soon Juan]], was declared bankrupt by the High Court, after failing to pay [[Singapore dollar|S$]]500,000 in damages awarded to Senior Minister [[Goh Chok Tong]] and Minister Mentor [[Lee Kuan Yew]] in a [[defamation]] lawsuit concerning comments he made during the [[2001 Singaporean general election|2001 election]] and later, the comments relating to last year's [[National Kidney Foundation Singapore scandal]]. Per the bankruptcy order, Chee was barred from participating in the politics (as well as the forthcoming election) for five years.\n* 15 February - \n**Tan Chor Jin shot and killed nightclub owner Lim Hock Soon at his apartment. Nicknamed the \"One Eyed Dragon\", he was sentenced to death and hanged on 9 January 2009.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Teo|first1=Wan Gek|title=Donor 'designated kidney expressly' for Tang|newspaper=The Straits Times|location=Singapore|url=http://news.asiaone.com/News/the+Straits+Times/Story/A1Story20090111-113780.html|accessdate=25 January 2015|date=11 January 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131175029/http://news.asiaone.com/News/the+Straits+Times/Story/A1Story20090111-113780.html|archive-date=31 January 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The suspected murderer who shocked Singapore|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/world/archives/2007/01/22/2003345842|accessdate=25 January 2015|agency=Taipei Times|date=22 January 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140607153720/http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/world/archives/2007/01/22/2003345842|archive-date=2014-06-07|url-status=live}}</ref>\n**The [[Ford Motor Factory]] in Upper Bukit Timah Road, the site of the British surrender to the Japanese during [[World War II]], was gazetted as a [[National Monuments of Singapore|national monument]].\n* 16 February - \n**The [[Ford Motor Factory#Memories at Old Ford Factory|Memories at Old Ford Factory]] is officially opened to showcase the times during [[World War II]].\n**[[MediaCorp]] launches [[MOBTV]], a [[video on demand]] service.<ref>{{cite web|title=MediaCorp Online Broadband TV \u2013 Decide when, where and what you want for your TV entertainment|publisher=MediaCorp|url=http://www.corporate.mediacorp.sg/press_release/pr_1140163968.htm|accessdate=31 July 2019|date=16 February 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060904144212/http://www.corporate.mediacorp.sg/press_release/pr_1140163968.htm|archive-date=4 September 2006}}</ref>\n\n===March===\n* 3 March - The [[Additional CPF Housing Grant]] is announced to help lower-income Singaporeans buy [[Housing and Development Board]] (HDB) flats. The scheme has since been enhanced in 2007 and 2009.\n* 13 March - The updated [[Singapore Green Plan 2012]] is released, with new targets for clean air, emissions, water consumption, among others.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mewr.gov.sg/news/mewr-releases-singapore-green-plan-2012-2006-edition-after-extensive-consultation |title=MEWR releases Singapore Green Plan 2012 (2006 Edition) after extensive consultation |publisher=MEWR |accessdate=18 August 2019 |date=13 March 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190818111750/https://www.mewr.gov.sg/news/mewr-releases-singapore-green-plan-2012-2006-edition-after-extensive-consultation |archive-date=18 August 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* 16 March - [[Monarch of the United Kingdom|British monarch]] [[Elizabeth II]] visits Singapore.\n* 20 March - The [[Police Coast Guard]]'s new headquarters on [[Pulau Brani]], called the [[Brani Regional Base]], starts operation, moving from its previous headquarters in [[Kallang Basin]].\n* 24 March - [[ITE College East]] is officially opened.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/speeches/view-html?filename=20060324980.htm|title=Official opening of ITE College East|publisher=NAS|date=24 March 2006 |accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref>\n* 25 March - The [[West Coast Highway, Singapore|West Coast Highway]] viaduct is officially opened.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mot.gov.sg/news-centre/news/Detail/Speech%20By%20Mr%20Yeo%20Cheow%20Tong%20At%20The%20Opening%20Of%20West%20Coast%20Highway%20Extension%20And%20Upgraded%20Jalan%20Buroh%20on%2025%20March%202006/|title=Opening Of West Coast Highway Extension And Upgraded Jalan Buroh|publisher=MOT|date=25 March 2006 |accessdate=11 July 2019}}</ref>\n* 26 March - \n**The Budget Terminal in [[Changi Airport]] begins operations.<ref>{{cite web |title=Singapore's Budget Terminal Opens For Scheduled Flight Operations |url=https://www.mot.gov.sg/news-centre/news/Detail/Singapore's%20Budget%20Terminal%20Opens%20For%20Scheduled%20Flight%20Operations/ |accessdate=6 September 2019 |website=MOT |date=26 March 2006}}</ref>\n**The [[Ministry of Health (Singapore)|Ministry of Health]] announced a new general hospital in Woodlands, which will be ready 10 years after the [[Khoo Teck Puat Hospital|hospital]] in Yishun is opened.<ref>{{cite news |title=New hospital in Woodlands |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/today20060327-1.2.10.4 |accessdate=11 August 2019 |publisher=Today (retrieved from NLB) |date=27 March 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190811112000/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/today20060327-1.2.10.4 |archive-date=11 August 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* 31 March - The [[Immigration and Checkpoints Authority]] launches the [[Singapore passport#Biometric passport|BioPass]], a biometric passport that promises higher security.<ref>{{cite web |title=Unveiling of \"BioPass\" - The Singapore Biometric Passport |url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/speeches/view-html?filename=20060331996.htm |publisher=NAS |accessdate=11 August 2019 |date=31 March 2006}}</ref> These passports were rolled out on 15 August.<ref>{{cite web |title=Public Introduction of Singapore Biometric Passport |url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/speeches/view-html?filename=20060725983.htm |publisher=NAS |accessdate=11 August 2019 |date=25 July 2006}}</ref>\n\n===April===\n* 1 April - \n**[[National University of Singapore]] and [[Nanyang Technological University]] become [[autonomous university|autonomous universities]], thus ceasing to be statutory boards. At the same time, [[Singapore Management University]] is given more autonomy. The changes are first announced on 12 April 2005.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/speeches/view-html?filename=20050412991.htm |title=NUS, NTU, SMU to become autonomous universities |website=NAS |accessdate=27 June 2019 |date=12 April 2005}}</ref>\n**The Deposit Insurance Scheme is launched to compensate deposits, should a bank or finance company fail.<ref>{{cite web |title=Launch of Deposit Insurance Scheme in Singapore |url=https://www.mas.gov.sg/news/media-releases/2006/launch-of-deposit-insurance-scheme-in-singapore |website=MAS |accessdate=20 April 2020 |date=28 March 2006}}</ref>\n* 13 April - [[OCBC Bank]] proposes to sell its stake in [[Robinsons & Co.]] to Auric Pacific, a [[Lippo Group]] firm.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ocbc.com/download/media_releases/2006/April/Press%20Release%20130406.pdf |title=OCBC Group divests 29.9% stake in Robinsons for S$203 million to Red Oasis Pte. Ltd. |date=13 April 2006 |accessdate=25 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101128161519/http://ocbc.com/download/media_releases/2006/April/Press%20Release%20130406.pdf |archive-date=28 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bnpparibas.com.sg/en/2006/06/27/corporate-finance-lippo-group-consortium-acquires-29-90-of-robinson-and-company-limited-for-eur100m/ |title=Corporate Finance \u2013 Lippo Group consortium acquires 29.90% of Robinson and Company, limited for \u20ac100m |date=27 June 2006 |accessdate=22 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722023034/http://www.bnpparibas.com.sg/en/2006/06/27/corporate-finance-lippo-group-consortium-acquires-29-90-of-robinson-and-company-limited-for-eur100m/ |archive-date=22 July 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 16 April - Former [[National Kidney Foundation Singapore|National Kidney Foundation]]'s CEO [[T.T. Durai]] was arrested for fraud in the wake of the [[National Kidney Foundation Singapore scandal]]. [[Singapore Democratic Party]]'s secretary-general [[Chee Soon Juan]] and his party members went to make public backlash to the ruling [[People's Action Party]], but were sued for defamation by the latter on 22 April, and tasked to pay damages by 26 April.\n* 19 April - The [[Straits Times Index]] sets a high of 2585.84 points,<ref>{{cite web |title=ST Index at all-time high after 26-pt surge |url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes20060420-1.2.2 |website=The Straits Times (retrieved from NLB) |accessdate=28 January 2020 |date=20 April 2006}}</ref> surpassing the former record of 2582.94 points from 2000.<ref>{{cite web |title=STI blazes past 2,500 to new high |url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes20000104-1.2.2 |website=The Straits Times (retrieved from NLB) |accessdate=28 January 2020 |date=4 January 2000}}</ref> These record highs continued until 2007.\n* 22 April - The Heritage Trees Register and the Young Arborist Programme are launched for the public to learn about the histories of Heritage Trees and raise awareness on conservation, and foster appreciation of trees in the younger generation respectively. At the same time, the number of Heritage Trees has increased from 35 to 161.<ref>{{cite web |title=NParks Announces the New Heritage Trees Register |url=https://www.nparks.gov.sg/news/2006/4/nparks-announces-the-new-heritage-trees-register |website=NParks |accessdate=3 November 2019 |date=22 April 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Heritage Tree Scheme |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_2015-09-28_143310.html |website=NLB |accessdate=23 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n===May===\n* 6 May - Polling day for the [[2006 Singaporean general election]]:\n**The ruling [[People's Action Party]] winning 82 out of 84 seats (37 of which were [[walkover|uncontested]]) with a percentage of 66.6% of the total vote. This was the first election since the [[1988 Singaporean general election|1988 election]] more than a majority of seats were contested and the party did not control the government after Nomination Day (held on 27 April).\n**The remaining two seats for [[Hougang SMC]] and [[Potong Pasir SMC]], were retained by the [[Workers' Party (Singapore)|Workers' Party]] and [[Singapore Democratic Alliance]], respectively.\n**Workers' Party's leader [[Low Thia Khiang]] succeeds Singapore Democratic Alliance's leader [[Chiam See Tong]] as the [[Leader of the Opposition (Singapore)|Opposition Leader]] due to a higher party popular vote.\n* 7 May - Workers' Party's candidate [[James Gomez]] is detained in Singapore for further questioning, after trying to leave for [[Sweden]] to return to work. He was released a week later with a formal warning.\n* 15 May - [[Kallang]] body parts murder murderer Leong Siew Chor received a death sentence for murdering a 22-year-old Chinese national Liu Hong Mei.<ref>{{cite news|title=Other gruesome murders that took place in Singapore|url=http://news.asiaone.com/News/AsiaOne+News/Crime/Story/A1Story20120403-337375.html|accessdate=27 December 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150104164706/http://news.asiaone.com/News/AsiaOne+News/Crime/Story/A1Story20120403-337375.html|archivedate=4 January 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* 25 May - The 145 Squadron, which is the [[Republic of Singapore Air Force]]'s third generation of fighter planes and its first advanced pilot jet, was launched for the first time.\n* 26 May - The [[Government of Singapore|government]] selected [[Las Vegas Sands]] as its management for the [[Integrated Resort]] at [[Marina Bay, Singapore|Marina Bay]] among four [[casino]] operators. The project will be finished by 2009.<ref>{{cite web |title=Government Awards Marina Bay IR Project to Las Vegas Sands Corporation |url=https://www.stb.gov.sg/content/stb/en/media-centre/media-releases/government-awards-marina-bay-ir-project-to-las-vegas-sands-corporation.html |publisher=STB |accessdate=7 August 2019 |date=26 May 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190807193215/https://www.stb.gov.sg/content/stb/en/media-centre/media-releases/government-awards-marina-bay-ir-project-to-las-vegas-sands-corporation.html |archive-date=7 August 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Las Vegas Sands wins bid to build Singapore's first integrated resort |url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/210501/1/.html |accessdate=7 August 2019 |publisher=Channel NewsAsia |date=26 May 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060528204532/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/210501/1/.html |archivedate=28 May 2006}}</ref>\n* 29 May - \n**The [[Philippines|Filipino]] maid, Guen Aguilar was sentenced to ten years imprisonment for [[manslaughter]]ing her best friend.\n**Tripartite Alliance for Fair Employment Practices was formed to encourage fair [[employment]] outcomes in Singapore.\n\n===June===\n* 1 June - \n**[[my Paper]] is launched as a free Mandarin newspaper by [[Singapore Press Holdings]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sph.com.sg/media_releases/313|title=Singapore Press Holdings\u00b4 Chinese freesheet - my paper - hits the streets|date=31 May 2006|accessdate=22 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722015728/https://sph.com.sg/media_releases/313|archive-date=22 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n**The Community Court is set up as part of the [[State Courts of Singapore|Subordinate Courts]], dealing mainly with cases requiring community intervention.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.statecourts.gov.sg/cws/CriminalCase/Pages/CommunityCourt.aspx |title=Community Court |accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref>\n* 8 June - [[Emperor of Japan]] [[Akihito]] visits Singapore for three days with [[Empress Michiko of Japan|Empress Michiko]].\n* 14 June - [[Straits Times Online Mobile Print|STOMP]] is launched as a citizen journalism service.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sph.com.sg/media_releases/318|title=The Straits Times extends its reach with bold new platform STOMP|date=14 June 2006|accessdate=22 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722015734/https://sph.com.sg/media_releases/318|archive-date=22 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 26 June - The first [[wheelchair]]-accessible bus service is launched.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sbstransit.com.sg/press/2006jun_26-1.aspx|title=SBS Transit Launches Singapore's First-Ever Wheelchair Accessible Buses, Offers One Month Free Rides|date=26 June 2006|accessdate=27 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160219234355/http://www.sbstransit.com.sg/press/2006jun_26-1.aspx|archive-date=19 February 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===July===\n* 6 July - The local free newspaper ''[[Today (Singapore newspaper)|Today]]'' suspends the column of [[mrbrown]] in a noted case of [[censorship in Singapore]] following a letter from a government official to the letters section of the paper.\n* 24 July - [[A*STAR]] stops its partnership with [[Johns Hopkins Medicine]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes20060725.2.39.5|title=Key dates|publisher=The Straits Times|date=25 July 2006|accessdate=22 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722015728/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes20060725.2.39.5|archive-date=22 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===August===\n* 9 August - Singapore celebrates the last National Day Parade for the last time at the [[Former National Stadium, Singapore|National Stadium]] before it's closed for redevelopment.\n* 10 August - The [[Ministry of Home Affairs (Singapore)|Ministry of Home Affairs]] and [[Ministry of Health (Singapore)|Ministry of Health]] announced tough measures to curb [[Subutex]] abuse, originally allowed in 2000 to help heroin addicts kick the habit.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tougher action against Subutex abuse |url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/data/pdfdoc/20060810990.htm |website=NAS |accessdate=3 March 2020 |date=10 August 2006}}</ref> \n* 15 August - The JetQuay CIP Terminal began operations. \n* 23 August - Singapore announced that their [[A1 Team Singapore|Singapore team]] were to compete in the upcoming [[A1 Grand Prix]] season.\n\n===September===\n* 2 September - The [[Home Team Academy]] is officially opened.<ref>{{cite web |title=Official Opening Ceremony of The Home Team Academy |url=http://www2.mha.gov.sg/mha/detailed.jsp?artid=2074&type=4&root=0&parent=0&cat=0&mode=arc |website=MHA |accessdate=26 September 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070617020333/http://www2.mha.gov.sg/mha/detailed.jsp?artid=2074&type=4&root=0&parent=0&cat=0&mode=arc |archivedate=17 June 2007 |date=2 September 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Cheney |first1=Satish |title=New Home Team Academy to bring all agencies under one roof |url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/225578/1/.html |website=Channel NewsAsia |accessdate=26 September 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070311095411/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/225578/1/.html |archivedate=11 March 2007 |date=18 August 2006}}</ref>\n* 11\u201320 September - The [[Annual Meetings of the International Monetary Fund and the World Bank Group|61st Annual Meetings]] of the Boards of Governors of the [[International Monetary Fund]] and the [[World Bank Group]] took place at the [[Suntec Singapore International Convention and Exhibition Centre]].\n* 24 September - [[St James Power Station]] opens as a nightclub. \n* 28 September - The [[Ministry of Education (Singapore)|Ministry of Education]] announced that EM3 and other streams will be abolished, leading to Subject-Based Banding in primary schools. The change takes effect in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/data/pdfdoc/20060928996.pdf|title=Refining how we deliver ability-driven education|date=28 September 2006|accessdate=7 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190607132248/http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/data/pdfdoc/20060928996.pdf|archive-date=7 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===October===\n* 5 October - The [[Marina Bay Financial Centre]] is launched. It will be a [[mixed-use]] development with office buildings and a commercial district, making it the largest commercial centre in Singapore. The development will also have [[environmentally friendly]] features. Developed by [[Cheung Kong Holdings]], [[Hongkong Land]] and [[Keppel Land]], the development officially opened in 2013.<ref>{{cite web |title=Unveiling of the Marina Bay Financial Centre |url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/data/pdfdoc/20061005990.htm |website=NAS |accessdate=31 January 2020 |date=5 October 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Like S'pore's Canary Wharf (Page 6) |url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Page/today20061006-1.1.6 |website=Today (retrieved from NLB) |accessdate=31 January 2020 |date=6 October 2006}}</ref>\n* 7 October - Singapore experiences the worst [[2006 Southeast Asian haze|haze]] since [[1997 Southeast Asian haze|1997]] with the [[Pollutant Standards Index]] reaching a high of 150.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/234369/1/.html|archive-url=https://archive.is/20061023005348/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/234369/1/.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=23 October 2006|accessdate=8 October 2006|title=Haze worsens in Singapore, PSI hits new high for the year|publisher=[[Channel NewsAsia]]}}</ref>\n* 12 October - [[REACH (Singapore)|REACH]] is formed to connect with citizens.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/today20061013-2.2.5.2|title=Reaching out better (Todayonline)|date=13 October 2006|accessdate=17 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190717040956/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/today20061013-2.2.5.2|archive-date=17 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 30 October - Phase 2 of [[Biopolis]] is opened, adding two buildings to the existing seven.<ref>{{cite news |title=Biopolis booster for local biomed scene |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/today20061031-2.2.9.3 |accessdate=2 August 2019 |publisher=Today (retrieved from NLB) |date=31 October 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190802054552/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/today20061031-2.2.9.3 |archive-date=2 August 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n* 31 October - The Orchard Turn development (now [[ION Orchard]] and [[The Orchard Residences]]) starts construction as a mall-cum-residential development, jointly developed by [[CapitaLand]] and [[Sun Hung Kai Properties]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Orchard Turn Groundbreaking Ceremony |url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/data/pdfdoc/20061031989.pdf |publisher=NAS |accessdate=30 July 2019 |date=31 October 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190730110104/http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/data/pdfdoc/20061031989.pdf |archive-date=30 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===November===\n* 5 November - The first refurbished [[Kawasaki Heavy Industries C151|C151]] train enters service, with the whole project completed by 2008.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rajan |first=T. |title=MRT trains get $145m overhaul |work= The Straits Times |date = 5 November 2006}}</ref>\n* 30 November - [[IKEA]] opens a new store in Tampines Retail Park.<ref>{{cite web |title=Opening Ceremony of IKEA Tampines |url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/speeches/view-html?filename=20061130998.htm |publisher=NAS |accessdate=12 August 2019 |date=30 November 2006}}</ref>\n\n===December===\n* 1 December - \n**[[VivoCity]] is officially open to the public.\n**[[Wireless@SG]] is officially launched at several hotspots, allowing for free [[WiFi]] connections in public spaces.\n* 6 December - Phase 2A of [[Fusionopolis]] starts construction.<ref>{{cite web |title=Groundbreaking Ceremony of Fusionopolis Phase 2A Site |url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/speeches/view-html?filename=20061206996.htm |publisher=NAS |accessdate=2 August 2019 |date=6 December 2006}}</ref>\n* 8 December - \n**The [[National Museum of Singapore]] officially reopened.<ref>{{cite web |title=Opening Of The National Museum |url=https://www.mci.gov.sg/pressroom/news-and-stories/pressroom/2006/12/speech-by-dr-lee-boon-yang-at-the-opening-of-the-national-museum |publisher=MICA (now MCI) |accessdate=1 August 2019 |date=8 December 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190801185700/https://www.mci.gov.sg/pressroom/news-and-stories/pressroom/2006/12/speech-by-dr-lee-boon-yang-at-the-opening-of-the-national-museum |archive-date=1 August 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n**The [[Government of Singapore|government]] selects [[Genting Group]] and [[Star Cruises]] as its management for the [[Integrated Resort]] at [[Sentosa]] among three [[casino]] operators.<ref>{{cite web |title=Remarks by DPM Prof S Jayakumar at Press Conference on Award of Integrated Resort at Sentosa, 8 Dec |url=https://www.mlaw.gov.sg/content/minlaw/en/news/speeches/remarks-by-dpm-prof-s-jayakumar-at-press-conference-on-award-of-integrated-resort-at-sentosa-8-dec.html |publisher=MinLaw |accessdate=7 August 2019 |date=8 December 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190807193220/https://www.mlaw.gov.sg/content/minlaw/en/news/speeches/remarks-by-dpm-prof-s-jayakumar-at-press-conference-on-award-of-integrated-resort-at-sentosa-8-dec.html |archive-date=7 August 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Award of the Integrated Resort on Sentosa |url=https://www.mti.gov.sg/Newsroom/Speeches/2006/12/Transcript-of-Remarks-by-Mr-Lim-Hng-Kiang-Minister-for-Trade-_-Industry-at-the-Press-Conference-on-t |publisher=MTI |accessdate=7 August 2019 |date=8 December 2006}}</ref>\n* 16 December - [[Courts Singapore|Courts]] opens Courts Megastore in Tampines,<ref>{{cite web |title=Opening of Courts Megastore |url=https://m.facebook.com/COURTSSG/photos/a.239618166073522/1057021484333182/?type=3 |publisher=Courts Singapore (Facebook) |accessdate=12 August 2019 |date=28 July 2016}}</ref> followed by [[Giant Hypermarket]] opening in Tampines in 2007.\n\n==Deaths==\n* 22 February - [[Sinnathamby Rajaratnam]] (formally known as S Rajaratnam), former [[Deputy Prime Minister of Singapore|Deputy Prime Minister]] and [[Senior Minister]] (b. 1915).<ref>{{cite web |title=S. Rajaratnam |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_644_2005-01-10.html |publisher=NLB |accessdate=11 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190329103341/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_644_2005-01-10.html |archive-date=29 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* 19 June - [[Arthur Yap]], poet (b. 1943).<ref>{{cite web |title=Arthur Yap |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_641_2005-01-10.html |publisher=NLB |accessdate=11 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190412003713/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_641_2005-01-10.html |archive-date=12 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* 12 July - [[Humphrey Morrison Burkill]], director of [[Singapore Botanic Gardens]] from 1957-1969 (b. 1914).<ref>{{cite web |title=Humphrey Morrison Burkill |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1477_2009-02-26.html |publisher=NLB |accessdate=11 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181205200123/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1477_2009-02-26.html |archive-date=5 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* 20 July - [[Lim Kim San]], former Cabinet Minister (b. 1916).<ref>{{cite web |title=Lim Kim San |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_645_2005-01-11.html |publisher=NLB |accessdate=11 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721193803/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_645_2005-01-11.html |archive-date=21 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* 25 July - [[Chen Jin Lang]], former songwriter (b. 1961).\n* 2 September - [[Anthony Poon]], artist (b. 1945).<ref>{{cite web |title=Anthony Poon |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1356_2008-12-30.html |publisher=NLB |accessdate=11 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190718051108/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1356_2008-12-30.html |archive-date=18 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* 14 September - [[Elizabeth Choy]], educator, war heroine, politician (b. 1910).<ref>{{cite web |title=Elizabeth Choy |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_816_2005-01-25.html |publisher=NLB |accessdate=11 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417081245/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_816_2005-01-25.html |archive-date=17 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* 5 December - [[Lim Chor Pee]], lawyer, playwright (b. 1936).<ref>{{cite web |title=Lim Chor Pee |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1449_2009-02-11.html |website=NLB |accessdate=29 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Years in Singapore}}\n{{Year in Asia|2006}}\n\n[[Category:2006 in Singapore| ]]\n[[Category:Years of the 21st century in Singapore]]\n[[Category:2006 in Southeast Asia|Singapore]]\n[[Category:2006 by country|Singapore]]\n[[Category:2000s in Singapore]]\n", "text_old": "{{Dynamic list}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{Year in Singapore|2006}}\n\nThe following lists events that happened during '''[[2006]] in [[Singapore]]'''.\n\n==Incumbents==\n*[[President of Singapore|President]]: [[S.R. Nathan]]\n*[[Prime Minister of Singapore|Prime Minister]]: [[Lee Hsien Loong]]\n\n==Events==\n===January===\n[[File:Buangkok MRT Station 3, Aug 06.JPG|thumb|right|300px|Buangkok MRT station]]\n* 3 January - The National Research Foundation is established to set the direction of [[research and development]] initiatives.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nrf.gov.sg/about-nrf/national-research-foundation-singapore/nrf-milestones|title=NRF Milestones|date=2019|accessdate=30 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190421081100/https://www.nrf.gov.sg/about-nrf/national-research-foundation-singapore/nrf-milestones|archive-date=21 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 7 January - The new [[Supreme Court of Singapore|Supreme Court]] building is officially opened.<ref>{{cite web |title=Official Opening of the new Supreme Court Building |url=https://www.istana.gov.sg/Newsroom/Speeches/2006/01/07/S-R-Nathan-at-the-Official-Opening-of-the-new-Supreme-Court-Building |publisher=Istana |accessdate=11 August 2019 |date=7 January 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190811112005/https://www.istana.gov.sg/Newsroom/Speeches/2006/01/07/S-R-Nathan-at-the-Official-Opening-of-the-new-Supreme-Court-Building |archive-date=11 August 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* 9 January - The [[Ministry of Education (Singapore)|Ministry of Education]] announced that a single intake for junior college and centralised institute admissions will be implemented from January 2009. This is made possible as the [[Singapore Examinations and Assessment Board]] moves to take greater control of the [[Singapore-Cambridge GCE Ordinary Level|O Level]] examinations from this year.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wong |first1=Siew Ying |title=Single intake for junior colleges, centralised institutes from 2009 |url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/187347/1/.html |publisher=Channel NewsAsia |accessdate=11 August 2019 |date=9 January 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060111082136/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/187347/1/.html |archive-date=11 January 2006 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* 12 January - The first $2 polymer notes are released.<ref>{{cite web|title=MAS Issues $2 Polymer Notes|url=https://www.mas.gov.sg/news/media-releases/2005/mas-issues-2dollars-polymer-notes|website=MAS|accessdate=15 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715180154/https://www.mas.gov.sg/news/media-releases/2005/mas-issues-2dollars-polymer-notes|archive-date=15 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 13 January - 27 students from [[Raffles Girls' School (Secondary)|Raffles Girls' School]] sold [[Buangkok MRT station#Second white elephant incident|white elephant shirts]] for a carnival at [[Buangkok MRT station]] to raise funds for a youth organisation, sparling a [[Singapore Police Force|police]] reaction.<ref>{{cite news |title=Teens' white elephant T-shirt venture gets police attention |publisher=Today (Singapore newspaper) |date=14 January 2006 |url=http://www.todayonline.com/articles/95206.asp |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060116035840/http://www.todayonline.com/articles/95206.asp |archivedate=16 January 2006 }}</ref> On 21 January however, then Deputy Prime Minister [[Wong Kan Seng]] apologised for the overreaction by the police.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ng |first1=Julia |title=Police overreacted to white elephant T-shirt incident: DPM Wong |publisher=Channel NewsAsia |date=21 January 2006 |url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/189327/1/.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930235446/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/189327/1/.html |archivedate=30 September 2007 }}</ref>\n* 15 January - [[Buangkok MRT station]] opens on the [[North East MRT line]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Buangkok NEL Station Commences Revenue Service Amid Great Fanfare|url=https://www.sbstransit.com.sg/press/2006jan_15-1.aspx|website=SBS Transit|accessdate=29 August 2019|date=15 January 2006}}</ref>\n* 16 January - A statement on [[National service in Singapore|NS defaulters]] is delivered in [[Parliament of Singapore|Parliament]] after the case of [[Melvyn Tan]] in 2005. It sparked a controversy due to the fine imposed.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ministerial statement on National Service defaulters |url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/speeches/view-html?filename=20060116991.htm |publisher=NAS |accessdate=23 July 2019 |date=16 January 2006}}</ref> \n* 17 January - The [[Workplace Safety and Health Act]] is passed to ensure better workplace safety and health standards, after several high-profile accidents. The law came into effect on 1 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sso.agc.gov.sg/Act/WSHA2006?ProvIds=xv-#xv-|title=Workplace Safety & Health Act|publisher=AGC|accessdate=27 July 2019}}</ref>\n* 19 January - The Somerset Skate Park is officially opened.<ref>{{cite web|title=News release: Bigger, better Somerset skate park opens in Orchard. |url=http://nyc.pa.gov.sg/newss/pdf/1323682440MR---Launch-of-Somerset-Skate-Park.pdf |publisher=National Youth Council |access-date=1 September 2019 |date=19 January 2006 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=National Youth Council |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_419_2005-01-06.html |publisher=NLB |access-date=1 September 2019}}</ref>\n* 20 January - The City Campus of [[Singapore Management University]] officially opened.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smu.edu.sg/news/2006/01/20/singapore-management-university-celebrates-official-opening-city-campus|title=Singapore Management University celebrates Official Opening of City Campus|date=20 January 2006|accessdate=30 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190630115224/https://www.smu.edu.sg/news/2006/01/20/singapore-management-university-celebrates-official-opening-city-campus|archive-date=30 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 23 January - [[Temasek Holdings|Temasek]] buys over [[Sale of Shin Corporation to Temasek Holdings|Shin Corporation]] with [[Siam Commercial Bank]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.temasek.com.sg/en/news-and-views/news-room/news/2006/temasek-scb-led-investor-group-acquires-shinawatra-and-damapong-.html |title=Temasek-SCB led investor group acquires Shinawatra and Damapong Families\u2019 stakes in Shin Corp |website=Temasek Holdings |date=23 January 2006 |accessdate=20 September 2019}}</ref> causing a controversy.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thestar.com.my/business/business-news/2006/01/24/temasek-buys-shin-corp/|title=Temasek buys Shin Corp |website=The Star |accessdate=22 July 2019 |date=24 January 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722015730/https://www.thestar.com.my/business/business-news/2006/01/24/temasek-buys-shin-corp/ |archive-date=22 July 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> Nonetheless, the deal is completed on 24 March.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.temasek.com.sg/en/news-and-views/news-room/news/2006/shin-bid-consortium-partners-complete-tender-offer-for-ais.html |title=Shin-bid Consortium Partners Complete Tender Offer for AIS |website=Temasek Holdings |date=24 March 2006 |accessdate=20 September 2019}}</ref>\n* 26 January - \n**[[I Not Stupid Too]] is released in cinemas as a sequel to [[I Not Stupid]].\n**[[Zodiac: The Race Begins]] is released as Singapore's first [[3D animation|3D animated]] film.\n\n===February===\n* 3 February - In response to the [[Jyllands-Posten Muhammad cartoons controversy]], the Islamic Religious Council of Singapore ([[Majlis Ugama Islam Singapura|Majlis Ugama Islam Singapura (MUIS)]]) issued a statement that says \"the inciting of hatred against a faith of a people is very unfortunate.\" Foreign Minister [[George Yeo]] and the [[Minister-in-charge of Muslim Affairs]] [[Yaacob Ibrahim]] have similarly said that the incident shows the need to respect racial and religious sensitivities, to have a \"responsible media\", and to cultivate good inter-religious relations and confidence beyond just legislation.\n* 8 February - The [[Monetary Authority of Singapore]] announced the setting up of Singapore Deposit Insurance Corporation Limited (SDIC) to manage deposit insurance.<ref>{{cite web |title=Establishment of Singapore Deposit Insurance Corporation Limited |url=https://www.mas.gov.sg/news/media-releases/2006/establishment-of-singapore-deposit-insurance |website=MAS |accessdate=20 April 2020 |date=8 February 2006}}</ref> \n* 10 February - The Secretary General of [[Singapore Democratic Party]], [[Chee Soon Juan]], was declared bankrupt by the High Court, after failing to pay [[Singapore dollar|S$]]500,000 in damages awarded to Senior Minister [[Goh Chok Tong]] and Minister Mentor [[Lee Kuan Yew]] in a [[defamation]] lawsuit concerning comments he made during the [[2001 Singaporean general election|2001 election]] and later, the comments relating to last year's [[National Kidney Foundation Singapore scandal]]. Per the bankruptcy order, Chee was barred from participating in the politics (as well as the forthcoming election) for five years.\n* 15 February - \n**Tan Chor Jin shot and killed nightclub owner Lim Hock Soon at his apartment. Nicknamed the \"One Eyed Dragon\", he was sentenced to death and hanged on 9 January 2009.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Teo|first1=Wan Gek|title=Donor 'designated kidney expressly' for Tang|newspaper=The Straits Times|location=Singapore|url=http://news.asiaone.com/News/the+Straits+Times/Story/A1Story20090111-113780.html|accessdate=25 January 2015|date=11 January 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131175029/http://news.asiaone.com/News/the+Straits+Times/Story/A1Story20090111-113780.html|archive-date=31 January 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The suspected murderer who shocked Singapore|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/world/archives/2007/01/22/2003345842|accessdate=25 January 2015|agency=Taipei Times|date=22 January 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140607153720/http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/world/archives/2007/01/22/2003345842|archive-date=2014-06-07|url-status=live}}</ref>\n**The [[Ford Motor Factory]] in Upper Bukit Timah Road, the site of the British surrender to the Japanese during [[World War II]], was gazetted as a [[National Monuments of Singapore|national monument]].\n* 16 February - \n**The [[Ford Motor Factory#Memories at Old Ford Factory|Memories at Old Ford Factory]] is officially opened to showcase the times during [[World War II]].\n**[[MediaCorp]] launches [[MOBTV]], a [[video on demand]] service.<ref>{{cite web|title=MediaCorp Online Broadband TV \u2013 Decide when, where and what you want for your TV entertainment|publisher=MediaCorp|url=http://www.corporate.mediacorp.sg/press_release/pr_1140163968.htm|accessdate=31 July 2019|date=16 February 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060904144212/http://www.corporate.mediacorp.sg/press_release/pr_1140163968.htm|archive-date=4 September 2006}}</ref>\n\n===March===\n* 3 March - The [[Additional CPF Housing Grant]] is announced to help lower-income Singaporeans buy [[Housing and Development Board]] (HDB) flats. The scheme has since been enhanced in 2007 and 2009.\n* 13 March - The updated [[Singapore Green Plan 2012]] is released, with new targets for clean air, emissions, water consumption, among others.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mewr.gov.sg/news/mewr-releases-singapore-green-plan-2012-2006-edition-after-extensive-consultation |title=MEWR releases Singapore Green Plan 2012 (2006 Edition) after extensive consultation |publisher=MEWR |accessdate=18 August 2019 |date=13 March 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190818111750/https://www.mewr.gov.sg/news/mewr-releases-singapore-green-plan-2012-2006-edition-after-extensive-consultation |archive-date=18 August 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* 16 March - [[Monarch of the United Kingdom|British monarch]] [[Elizabeth II]] visits Singapore.\n* 20 March - The [[Police Coast Guard]]'s new headquarters on [[Pulau Brani]], called the [[Brani Regional Base]], starts operation, moving from its previous headquarters in [[Kallang Basin]].\n* 24 March - [[ITE College East]] is officially opened.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/speeches/view-html?filename=20060324980.htm|title=Official opening of ITE College East|publisher=NAS|date=24 March 2006 |accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref>\n* 25 March - The [[West Coast Highway, Singapore|West Coast Highway]] viaduct is officially opened.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mot.gov.sg/news-centre/news/Detail/Speech%20By%20Mr%20Yeo%20Cheow%20Tong%20At%20The%20Opening%20Of%20West%20Coast%20Highway%20Extension%20And%20Upgraded%20Jalan%20Buroh%20on%2025%20March%202006/|title=Opening Of West Coast Highway Extension And Upgraded Jalan Buroh|publisher=MOT|date=25 March 2006 |accessdate=11 July 2019}}</ref>\n* 26 March - \n**The Budget Terminal in [[Changi Airport]] begins operations.<ref>{{cite web |title=Singapore's Budget Terminal Opens For Scheduled Flight Operations |url=https://www.mot.gov.sg/news-centre/news/Detail/Singapore's%20Budget%20Terminal%20Opens%20For%20Scheduled%20Flight%20Operations/ |accessdate=6 September 2019 |website=MOT |date=26 March 2006}}</ref>\n**The [[Ministry of Health (Singapore)|Ministry of Health]] announced a new general hospital in Woodlands, which will be ready 10 years after the [[Khoo Teck Puat Hospital|hospital]] in Yishun is opened.<ref>{{cite news |title=New hospital in Woodlands |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/today20060327-1.2.10.4 |accessdate=11 August 2019 |publisher=Today (retrieved from NLB) |date=27 March 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190811112000/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/today20060327-1.2.10.4 |archive-date=11 August 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* 31 March - The [[Immigration and Checkpoints Authority]] launches the [[Singapore passport#Biometric passport|BioPass]], a biometric passport that promises higher security.<ref>{{cite web |title=Unveiling of \"BioPass\" - The Singapore Biometric Passport |url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/speeches/view-html?filename=20060331996.htm |publisher=NAS |accessdate=11 August 2019 |date=31 March 2006}}</ref> These passports were rolled out on 15 August.<ref>{{cite web |title=Public Introduction of Singapore Biometric Passport |url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/speeches/view-html?filename=20060725983.htm |publisher=NAS |accessdate=11 August 2019 |date=25 July 2006}}</ref>\n\n===April===\n* 1 April - \n**[[National University of Singapore]] and [[Nanyang Technological University]] become [[autonomous university|autonomous universities]], thus ceasing to be statutory boards. At the same time, [[Singapore Management University]] is given more autonomy. The changes are first announced on 12 April 2005.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/speeches/view-html?filename=20050412991.htm |title=NUS, NTU, SMU to become autonomous universities |website=NAS |accessdate=27 June 2019 |date=12 April 2005}}</ref>\n**The Deposit Insurance Scheme is launched to compensate deposits should a bank or finance company fail.<ref>{{cite web |title=Launch of Deposit Insurance Scheme in Singapore |url=https://www.mas.gov.sg/news/media-releases/2006/launch-of-deposit-insurance-scheme-in-singapore |website=MAS |accessdate=20 April 2020 |date=28 March 2006}}</ref>\n* 13 April - [[OCBC Bank]] proposes to sell its stake in [[Robinsons & Co.]] to Auric Pacific, a [[Lippo Group]] firm.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ocbc.com/download/media_releases/2006/April/Press%20Release%20130406.pdf |title=OCBC Group divests 29.9% stake in Robinsons for S$203 million to Red Oasis Pte. Ltd. |date=13 April 2006 |accessdate=25 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101128161519/http://ocbc.com/download/media_releases/2006/April/Press%20Release%20130406.pdf |archive-date=28 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bnpparibas.com.sg/en/2006/06/27/corporate-finance-lippo-group-consortium-acquires-29-90-of-robinson-and-company-limited-for-eur100m/ |title=Corporate Finance \u2013 Lippo Group consortium acquires 29.90% of Robinson and Company, limited for \u20ac100m |date=27 June 2006 |accessdate=22 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722023034/http://www.bnpparibas.com.sg/en/2006/06/27/corporate-finance-lippo-group-consortium-acquires-29-90-of-robinson-and-company-limited-for-eur100m/ |archive-date=22 July 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 16 April - Former [[National Kidney Foundation Singapore|National Kidney Foundation]]'s CEO [[T.T. Durai]] was arrested for fraud in the wake of the [[National Kidney Foundation Singapore scandal]]. [[Singapore Democratic Party]]'s secretary-general [[Chee Soon Juan]] and his party members went to make public backlash to the ruling [[People's Action Party]], but were sued for defamation by the latter on 22 April, and tasked to pay damages by 26 April.\n* 19 April - The [[Straits Times Index]] sets a high of 2585.84 points,<ref>{{cite web |title=ST Index at all-time high after 26-pt surge |url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes20060420-1.2.2 |website=The Straits Times (retrieved from NLB) |accessdate=28 January 2020 |date=20 April 2006}}</ref> surpassing the former record of 2582.94 points from 2000.<ref>{{cite web |title=STI blazes past 2,500 to new high |url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes20000104-1.2.2 |website=The Straits Times (retrieved from NLB) |accessdate=28 January 2020 |date=4 January 2000}}</ref> These record highs continued until 2007.\n* 22 April - The Heritage Trees Register and the Young Arborist Programme are launched for the public to learn about the histories of Heritage Trees and raise awareness on conservation, and foster appreciation of trees in the younger generation respectively. At the same time, the number of Heritage Trees has increased from 35 to 161.<ref>{{cite web |title=NParks Announces the New Heritage Trees Register |url=https://www.nparks.gov.sg/news/2006/4/nparks-announces-the-new-heritage-trees-register |website=NParks |accessdate=3 November 2019 |date=22 April 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Heritage Tree Scheme |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_2015-09-28_143310.html |website=NLB |accessdate=23 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n===May===\n* 6 May - Polling day for the [[2006 Singaporean general election]]:\n**The ruling [[People's Action Party]] winning 82 out of 84 seats (37 of which were [[walkover|uncontested]]) with a percentage of 66.6% of the total vote. This was the first election since the [[1988 Singaporean general election|1988 election]] more than a majority of seats were contested and the party did not control the government after Nomination Day (held on 27 April).\n**The remaining two seats for [[Hougang SMC]] and [[Potong Pasir SMC]], were retained by the [[Workers' Party (Singapore)|Workers' Party]] and [[Singapore Democratic Alliance]], respectively.\n**Workers' Party's leader [[Low Thia Khiang]] succeeds Singapore Democratic Alliance's leader [[Chiam See Tong]] as the [[Leader of the Opposition (Singapore)|Opposition Leader]] due to a higher party popular vote.\n* 7 May - Workers' Party's candidate [[James Gomez]] is detained in Singapore for further questioning, after trying to leave for [[Sweden]] to return to work. He was released a week later with a formal warning.\n* 15 May - [[Kallang]] body parts murder murderer Leong Siew Chor received a death sentence for murdering a 22-year-old Chinese national Liu Hong Mei.<ref>{{cite news|title=Other gruesome murders that took place in Singapore|url=http://news.asiaone.com/News/AsiaOne+News/Crime/Story/A1Story20120403-337375.html|accessdate=27 December 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150104164706/http://news.asiaone.com/News/AsiaOne+News/Crime/Story/A1Story20120403-337375.html|archivedate=4 January 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* 25 May - The 145 Squadron, which is the [[Republic of Singapore Air Force]]'s third generation of fighter planes and its first advanced pilot jet, was launched for the first time.\n* 26 May - The [[Government of Singapore|government]] selected [[Las Vegas Sands]] as its management for the [[Integrated Resort]] at [[Marina Bay, Singapore|Marina Bay]] among four [[casino]] operators. The project will be finished by 2009.<ref>{{cite web |title=Government Awards Marina Bay IR Project to Las Vegas Sands Corporation |url=https://www.stb.gov.sg/content/stb/en/media-centre/media-releases/government-awards-marina-bay-ir-project-to-las-vegas-sands-corporation.html |publisher=STB |accessdate=7 August 2019 |date=26 May 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190807193215/https://www.stb.gov.sg/content/stb/en/media-centre/media-releases/government-awards-marina-bay-ir-project-to-las-vegas-sands-corporation.html |archive-date=7 August 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Las Vegas Sands wins bid to build Singapore's first integrated resort |url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/210501/1/.html |accessdate=7 August 2019 |publisher=Channel NewsAsia |date=26 May 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060528204532/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/210501/1/.html |archivedate=28 May 2006}}</ref>\n* 29 May - \n**The [[Philippines|Filipino]] maid, Guen Aguilar was sentenced to ten years imprisonment for [[manslaughter]]ing her best friend.\n**Tripartite Alliance for Fair Employment Practices was formed to encourage fair [[employment]] outcomes in Singapore.\n\n===June===\n* 1 June - \n**[[my Paper]] is launched as a free Mandarin newspaper by [[Singapore Press Holdings]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sph.com.sg/media_releases/313|title=Singapore Press Holdings\u00b4 Chinese freesheet - my paper - hits the streets|date=31 May 2006|accessdate=22 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722015728/https://sph.com.sg/media_releases/313|archive-date=22 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n**The Community Court is set up as part of the [[State Courts of Singapore|Subordinate Courts]], dealing mainly with cases requiring community intervention.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.statecourts.gov.sg/cws/CriminalCase/Pages/CommunityCourt.aspx |title=Community Court |accessdate=17 September 2019}}</ref>\n* 8 June - [[Emperor of Japan]] [[Akihito]] visits Singapore for three days with [[Empress Michiko of Japan|Empress Michiko]].\n* 14 June - [[Straits Times Online Mobile Print|STOMP]] is launched as a citizen journalism service.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sph.com.sg/media_releases/318|title=The Straits Times extends its reach with bold new platform STOMP|date=14 June 2006|accessdate=22 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722015734/https://sph.com.sg/media_releases/318|archive-date=22 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 26 June - The first [[wheelchair]]-accessible bus service is launched.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sbstransit.com.sg/press/2006jun_26-1.aspx|title=SBS Transit Launches Singapore's First-Ever Wheelchair Accessible Buses, Offers One Month Free Rides|date=26 June 2006|accessdate=27 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160219234355/http://www.sbstransit.com.sg/press/2006jun_26-1.aspx|archive-date=19 February 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===July===\n* 6 July - The local free newspaper ''[[Today (Singapore newspaper)|Today]]'' suspends the column of [[mrbrown]] in a noted case of [[censorship in Singapore]] following a letter from a government official to the letters section of the paper.\n* 24 July - [[A*STAR]] stops its partnership with [[Johns Hopkins Medicine]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes20060725.2.39.5|title=Key dates|publisher=The Straits Times|date=25 July 2006|accessdate=22 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722015728/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/straitstimes20060725.2.39.5|archive-date=22 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===August===\n* 9 August - Singapore celebrates the last National Day Parade for the last time at the [[Former National Stadium, Singapore|National Stadium]] before it's closed for redevelopment.\n* 10 August - The [[Ministry of Home Affairs (Singapore)|Ministry of Home Affairs]] and [[Ministry of Health (Singapore)|Ministry of Health]] announced tough measures to curb [[Subutex]] abuse, originally allowed in 2000 to help heroin addicts kick the habit.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tougher action against Subutex abuse |url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/data/pdfdoc/20060810990.htm |website=NAS |accessdate=3 March 2020 |date=10 August 2006}}</ref> \n* 15 August - The JetQuay CIP Terminal began operations. \n* 23 August - Singapore announced that their [[A1 Team Singapore|Singapore team]] were to compete in the upcoming [[A1 Grand Prix]] season.\n\n===September===\n* 2 September - The [[Home Team Academy]] is officially opened.<ref>{{cite web |title=Official Opening Ceremony of The Home Team Academy |url=http://www2.mha.gov.sg/mha/detailed.jsp?artid=2074&type=4&root=0&parent=0&cat=0&mode=arc |website=MHA |accessdate=26 September 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070617020333/http://www2.mha.gov.sg/mha/detailed.jsp?artid=2074&type=4&root=0&parent=0&cat=0&mode=arc |archivedate=17 June 2007 |date=2 September 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Cheney |first1=Satish |title=New Home Team Academy to bring all agencies under one roof |url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/225578/1/.html |website=Channel NewsAsia |accessdate=26 September 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070311095411/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/225578/1/.html |archivedate=11 March 2007 |date=18 August 2006}}</ref>\n* 11\u201320 September - The [[Annual Meetings of the International Monetary Fund and the World Bank Group|61st Annual Meetings]] of the Boards of Governors of the [[International Monetary Fund]] and the [[World Bank Group]] took place at the [[Suntec Singapore International Convention and Exhibition Centre]].\n* 24 September - [[St James Power Station]] opens as a nightclub. \n* 28 September - The [[Ministry of Education (Singapore)|Ministry of Education]] announced that EM3 and other streams will be abolished, leading to Subject-Based Banding in primary schools. The change takes effect in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/data/pdfdoc/20060928996.pdf|title=Refining how we deliver ability-driven education|date=28 September 2006|accessdate=7 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190607132248/http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/data/pdfdoc/20060928996.pdf|archive-date=7 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===October===\n* 5 October - The [[Marina Bay Financial Centre]] is launched. It will be a [[mixed-use]] development with office buildings and a commercial district, making it the largest commercial centre in Singapore. The development will also have [[environmentally friendly]] features. Developed by [[Cheung Kong Holdings]], [[Hongkong Land]] and [[Keppel Land]], the development officially opened in 2013.<ref>{{cite web |title=Unveiling of the Marina Bay Financial Centre |url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/data/pdfdoc/20061005990.htm |website=NAS |accessdate=31 January 2020 |date=5 October 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Like S'pore's Canary Wharf (Page 6) |url=https://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Page/today20061006-1.1.6 |website=Today (retrieved from NLB) |accessdate=31 January 2020 |date=6 October 2006}}</ref>\n* 7 October - Singapore experiences the worst [[2006 Southeast Asian haze|haze]] since [[1997 Southeast Asian haze|1997]] with the [[Pollutant Standards Index]] reaching a high of 150.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/234369/1/.html|archive-url=https://archive.is/20061023005348/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/234369/1/.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=23 October 2006|accessdate=8 October 2006|title=Haze worsens in Singapore, PSI hits new high for the year|publisher=[[Channel NewsAsia]]}}</ref>\n* 12 October - [[REACH (Singapore)|REACH]] is formed to connect with citizens.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/today20061013-2.2.5.2|title=Reaching out better (Todayonline)|date=13 October 2006|accessdate=17 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190717040956/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/today20061013-2.2.5.2|archive-date=17 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 30 October - Phase 2 of [[Biopolis]] is opened, adding two buildings to the existing seven.<ref>{{cite news |title=Biopolis booster for local biomed scene |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/today20061031-2.2.9.3 |accessdate=2 August 2019 |publisher=Today (retrieved from NLB) |date=31 October 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190802054552/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/newspapers/Digitised/Article/today20061031-2.2.9.3 |archive-date=2 August 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n* 31 October - The Orchard Turn development (now [[ION Orchard]] and [[The Orchard Residences]]) starts construction as a mall-cum-residential development, jointly developed by [[CapitaLand]] and [[Sun Hung Kai Properties]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Orchard Turn Groundbreaking Ceremony |url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/data/pdfdoc/20061031989.pdf |publisher=NAS |accessdate=30 July 2019 |date=31 October 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190730110104/http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/data/pdfdoc/20061031989.pdf |archive-date=30 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===November===\n* 5 November - The first refurbished [[Kawasaki Heavy Industries C151|C151]] train enters service, with the whole project completed by 2008.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rajan |first=T. |title=MRT trains get $145m overhaul |work= The Straits Times |date = 5 November 2006}}</ref>\n* 30 November - [[IKEA]] opens a new store in Tampines Retail Park.<ref>{{cite web |title=Opening Ceremony of IKEA Tampines |url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/speeches/view-html?filename=20061130998.htm |publisher=NAS |accessdate=12 August 2019 |date=30 November 2006}}</ref>\n\n===December===\n* 1 December - \n**[[VivoCity]] is officially open to the public.\n**[[Wireless@SG]] is officially launched at several hotspots, allowing for free [[WiFi]] connections in public spaces.\n* 6 December - Phase 2A of [[Fusionopolis]] starts construction.<ref>{{cite web |title=Groundbreaking Ceremony of Fusionopolis Phase 2A Site |url=http://www.nas.gov.sg/archivesonline/speeches/view-html?filename=20061206996.htm |publisher=NAS |accessdate=2 August 2019 |date=6 December 2006}}</ref>\n* 8 December - \n**The [[National Museum of Singapore]] officially reopened.<ref>{{cite web |title=Opening Of The National Museum |url=https://www.mci.gov.sg/pressroom/news-and-stories/pressroom/2006/12/speech-by-dr-lee-boon-yang-at-the-opening-of-the-national-museum |publisher=MICA (now MCI) |accessdate=1 August 2019 |date=8 December 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190801185700/https://www.mci.gov.sg/pressroom/news-and-stories/pressroom/2006/12/speech-by-dr-lee-boon-yang-at-the-opening-of-the-national-museum |archive-date=1 August 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n**The [[Government of Singapore|government]] selects [[Genting Group]] and [[Star Cruises]] as its management for the [[Integrated Resort]] at [[Sentosa]] among three [[casino]] operators.<ref>{{cite web |title=Remarks by DPM Prof S Jayakumar at Press Conference on Award of Integrated Resort at Sentosa, 8 Dec |url=https://www.mlaw.gov.sg/content/minlaw/en/news/speeches/remarks-by-dpm-prof-s-jayakumar-at-press-conference-on-award-of-integrated-resort-at-sentosa-8-dec.html |publisher=MinLaw |accessdate=7 August 2019 |date=8 December 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190807193220/https://www.mlaw.gov.sg/content/minlaw/en/news/speeches/remarks-by-dpm-prof-s-jayakumar-at-press-conference-on-award-of-integrated-resort-at-sentosa-8-dec.html |archive-date=7 August 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Award of the Integrated Resort on Sentosa |url=https://www.mti.gov.sg/Newsroom/Speeches/2006/12/Transcript-of-Remarks-by-Mr-Lim-Hng-Kiang-Minister-for-Trade-_-Industry-at-the-Press-Conference-on-t |publisher=MTI |accessdate=7 August 2019 |date=8 December 2006}}</ref>\n* 16 December - [[Courts Singapore|Courts]] opens Courts Megastore in Tampines,<ref>{{cite web |title=Opening of Courts Megastore |url=https://m.facebook.com/COURTSSG/photos/a.239618166073522/1057021484333182/?type=3 |publisher=Courts Singapore (Facebook) |accessdate=12 August 2019 |date=28 July 2016}}</ref> followed by [[Giant Hypermarket]] opening in Tampines in 2007.\n\n==Deaths==\n* 22 February - [[Sinnathamby Rajaratnam]] (formally known as S Rajaratnam), former [[Deputy Prime Minister of Singapore|Deputy Prime Minister]] and [[Senior Minister]] (b. 1915).<ref>{{cite web |title=S. Rajaratnam |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_644_2005-01-10.html |publisher=NLB |accessdate=11 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190329103341/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_644_2005-01-10.html |archive-date=29 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* 19 June - [[Arthur Yap]], poet (b. 1943).<ref>{{cite web |title=Arthur Yap |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_641_2005-01-10.html |publisher=NLB |accessdate=11 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190412003713/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_641_2005-01-10.html |archive-date=12 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* 12 July - [[Humphrey Morrison Burkill]], director of [[Singapore Botanic Gardens]] from 1957-1969 (b. 1914).<ref>{{cite web |title=Humphrey Morrison Burkill |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1477_2009-02-26.html |publisher=NLB |accessdate=11 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181205200123/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1477_2009-02-26.html |archive-date=5 December 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* 20 July - [[Lim Kim San]], former Cabinet Minister (b. 1916).<ref>{{cite web |title=Lim Kim San |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_645_2005-01-11.html |publisher=NLB |accessdate=11 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721193803/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_645_2005-01-11.html |archive-date=21 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* 25 July - [[Chen Jin Lang]], former songwriter (b. 1961).\n* 2 September - [[Anthony Poon]], artist (b. 1945).<ref>{{cite web |title=Anthony Poon |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1356_2008-12-30.html |publisher=NLB |accessdate=11 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190718051108/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1356_2008-12-30.html |archive-date=18 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* 14 September - [[Elizabeth Choy]], educator, war heroine, politician (b. 1910).<ref>{{cite web |title=Elizabeth Choy |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_816_2005-01-25.html |publisher=NLB |accessdate=11 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417081245/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_816_2005-01-25.html |archive-date=17 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* 5 December - [[Lim Chor Pee]], lawyer, playwright (b. 1936).<ref>{{cite web |title=Lim Chor Pee |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1449_2009-02-11.html |website=NLB |accessdate=29 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Years in Singapore}}\n{{Year in Asia|2006}}\n\n[[Category:2006 in Singapore| ]]\n[[Category:Years of the 21st century in Singapore]]\n[[Category:2006 in Southeast Asia|Singapore]]\n[[Category:2006 by country|Singapore]]\n[[Category:2000s in Singapore]]\n", "name_user": "TheGreatSG'rean", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eApril", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2006_in_Singapore"}
{"title_page": "All's Well That Ends Well", "text_new": "{{about|Shakespeare's play}}\n{{short description|play by Shakespeare}}\n{{italic title}}\n{{use British English|date=August 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n[[File:First Folio, Shakespeare - 0248.jpg|thumb|The first page of ''All's Well, that Ends Well'' from the [[First Folio]] of Shakespeare's plays, published in 1623.]]\n\n'''''All's Well That Ends Well''''' is a play by [[William Shakespeare]], published in the ''[[First Folio]]'' in 1623, where it is listed among the [[Shakespearean comedy|comedies]]. There is a debate regarding the dating of the composition of the play, with possible dates ranging from 1598 to 1608.<ref>{{cite book|last=Snyder|first=Susan|title=The Oxford Shakespeare: All's Well That Ends Well|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford, England|date=1993|pages=20\u201324|chapter=Introduction|isbn=978-0-19-283604-5}}</ref><ref name=\"maguire\">{{cite news|title=Many Hands \u2013 A New Shakespeare Collaboration?|last=Maguire|first=Laurie|date=19 April 2012|newspaper=[[The Times Literary Supplement]]|access-date=|last2=Smith|first2=Emma}} also at [http://www.cems-oxford.org/many-hands Centre for Early Modern Studies], [[University of Oxford]] accessed 22 April 2012: \"The recent redating of All\u2019s Well from 1602\u201303 to 1606\u201307 (or later) has gone some way to resolving some of the play\u2019s stylistic anomalies\" ... \"[S]tylistically it is striking how many of the widely acknowledged textual and tonal problems of All\u2019s Well can be understood differently when we postulate dual authorship.\"</ref>\n\nThe play is considered one of Shakespeare's \"[[Shakespearean problem play|problem plays]]\"; a play that poses complex ethical dilemmas that require more than typically simple solutions.<ref>Snyder, Susan (1993). \"Introduction\". ''The Oxford Shakespeare: All's Well That Ends Well''. Oxford, England: Oxford University Press. pp.\u00a016\u201319. {{ISBN|9780192836045}}</ref>\n[[File:Helena and the Countess.jpg|thumb|right|A watercolour of Helena and the Countess, from Act I, Scene iii.]]\n\n==Characters==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[King of France]]\n* Duke of [[Florence]]\n* Bertram, [[Counts of Roussillon|Count of Roussillon]]\n* Countess of Roussillon, Mother of Bertram\n* Lavatch, a [[Clown]] in her household\n* Helena, a [[Gentlewoman]] protected by the Countess{{0|000}}\n* Lafew, an old Lord\n* Parolles, a follower of Bertram\n* An Old Widow of Florence, surnamed Capilet\n* Diana, Daughter of the Widow\n* Steward of the Countess of Roussillon\n* Violenta ([[ghost character]]) and Mariana, Neighbours and Friends of the Widow\n* A Page\n* Soldiers, Servants, Gentlemen, and Courtiers\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Synopsis==\n[[File:All's Well that Ends Well Lithograph.jpg|thumb|right|A lithograph depicting Act IV Scene III.]]\nHelena, the low-born [[Ward (law)|ward]] of a French-Spanish countess, is in love with the countess's son Bertram, who is indifferent to her. Bertram goes to Paris to replace his late father as attendant to the ailing King of France. Helena, the daughter of a recently deceased [[physician]], follows Bertram, ostensibly to offer the King her services as a healer. The King is sceptical, and she guarantees the cure with her life: if he dies, she will be put to death, but if he lives, she may choose a [[husband]] from the court.\n\nThe King is cured and Helena chooses Bertram, who rejects her, owing to her poverty and low status. The King forces him to marry her, but after the ceremony Bertram immediately goes to war in Italy without so much as a goodbye kiss. He says that he will only marry her after she has borne his child and wears his family ring. Helena returns home to the countess, who is horrified at what her son has done, and claims Helena as her child in Bertram's place.\n\nIn Italy, Bertram is a successful warrior and also a successful seducer of local virgins. Helena follows him to Italy, befriends Diana, a virgin with whom Bertram is infatuated, and they arrange for Helena to take Diana's place in bed. Diana obtains Bertram's ring in exchange for one of Helena's. In this way Helena, without Bertram's knowledge, consummates their marriage and wears his ring.\n\nHelena fakes her own death. Bertram, thinking he is free of her, comes home. He tries to marry a local lord's daughter, but Diana shows up and breaks up the engagement. Helena appears and explains the ring swap, announcing that she has fulfilled Bertram's challenge; Bertram, impressed by all she has done to win him, swears his love to her. Thus all ends well.\n\nThere is a subplot about Parolles\u2014a disloyal associate of Bertram's: Some of the lords at the court attempt to get Bertram to know that his friend Parolles is a boasting [[coward]]\u2014as Lafew and the Countess have also said. They convince Parolles to cross into enemy territory to fetch a drum that he left behind. While on his way, they pose as enemy soldiers, kidnap him, blindfold him, and, with Bertram observing, get him to betray his friends, and besmirch Bertram's character.\n\n[[File:All's Well That Ends Well Act V Scene iii.jpg|thumb|A 1794 print of the final scene]]\n\n==Sources==\n[[File:Decameron Title Page.jpg|thumb|A copy of Boccaccio's ''The decameron containing an hundred pleasant nouels. Wittily discoursed, betweene seauen honourable ladies, and three noble gentlemen'', printed by [[Isaac Jaggard]] in 1620.]]\nThe play is based on a [[Summary of Decameron tales#Ninth tale (III, 9)|tale (tale nine of day three)]] of [[Giovanni Boccaccio|Boccaccio]]'s ''[[The Decameron]]''. Shakespeare may have read an English translation of the tale in [[William Painter (author)|William Painter]]'s ''Palace of Pleasure''.<ref>[[F. E. Halliday]], ''A Shakespeare Companion 1564\u20131964,'' Baltimore, Penguin, 1964; p.&nbsp;29.</ref>\n\n==Analysis and criticism==\n\nThere is no evidence that ''All's Well That Ends Well'' was popular in Shakespeare's own lifetime and it has remained one of his lesser-known plays ever since, in part due to its unorthodox mixture of [[fairy tale]] logic, [[gender role]] reversals and [[Cynicism (contemporary)|cynical realism]]. Helena's love for the seemingly unlovable Bertram is difficult to explain on the page, but in performance it can be made acceptable by casting an actor of obvious physical attraction or by playing him as a [[naive]] and innocent figure not yet ready for love although, as both Helena and the audience can see, capable of emotional growth.<ref>{{cite book|last=McCandless|first=David |title=Gender and performance in Shakespeare's problem comedies|publisher=Indiana University Press|location=Bloomington, IN|date=1997|pages=57\u201359|chapter=All's Well That Ends Well|isbn=0-253-33306-7}}</ref> This latter interpretation also assists at the point in the final scene in which Bertram suddenly switches from hatred to love in just one line. This is considered a particular problem for actors trained to admire psychological realism. However, some alternative readings emphasise the \"if\" in his equivocal promise: \"If she, my liege, can make me know this clearly, I'll love her dearly, ever, ever dearly.\" Here, there has been no change of heart at all.<ref name=dickson>{{cite book|last=Dickson|first=Andrew|title=The Rough Guide to Shakespeare|publisher=Penguin|location=London|date=2008|pages=3\u201311|chapter=All's Well That Ends Well|isbn=978-1-85828-443-9}}</ref> Productions like the National Theatre's 2009 run, have Bertram make his promise seemingly normally, but then end the play hand-in-hand with Helena, staring out at the audience with a look of \"aghast bewilderment\" suggesting he only relented to save face in front of the King.<ref>{{cite news|last=Billington|first=Michael|authorlink=Michael Billington (critic)|title=Theatre review: All's Well That Ends Well / Olivier, London|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2009/may/29/theatre|accessdate=9 May 2011|newspaper=The Guardian|date=29 May 2009}}</ref> A 2018 interpretation from director [[Caroline Byrne (stage director)|Caroline Byrne]] at the [[Sam Wanamaker Playhouse]], London, effects Bertram's reconciliation with Helena by having him make good his vow (Act 2 Scene 2) of only taking her as his wife when she bears his child; as well as Bertram's ring, Helena brings their infant child to their final confrontation before the king.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Taylor|first1=Paul|title=All's Well That Ends Well, review: Eye-opening and vividly alive|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/theatre-dance/reviews/alls-well-that-ends-well-sam-wanamaker-playhouse-review-a8165611.html|website=[[The Independent]]|date=18 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nMany critics consider that the truncated ending is a drawback, with Bertram's conversion so sudden. Various explanations have been given for this. There is (as always) possibly missing text. Some suggest that Bertram's conversion is meant to be sudden and magical in keeping with the 'clever [[wench]] performing tasks to win an unwilling higher born husband' theme of the play.<ref>W. W. Lawrence, ''Shakespeare's Problem Comedies'' 1931.</ref> Some consider that Bertram is not meant to be contemptible, merely a callow youth learning valuable lessons about values.<ref>J. G. Styan ''Shakespeare in Performance'' 1984; Francis G Schoff ''Claudio, Bertram and a Note on Inerpretation'', 1959</ref> Contemporary audiences would readily have recognised Bertram's enforced marriage as a metaphor for the new requirement (1606), directed at followers of the Catholic religion, to swear an [[Oath of Allegiance (United Kingdom)#To James I|Oath of Allegiance]] to Protestant [[James I of England|King James]], suggests academic Andrew Hadfield of the [[University of Sussex]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hadfield|first1=Andrew|title=Bad Faith|journal=Globe|date=August 2017|pages=48\u201353|issn=2398-9483}}</ref>\n\nMany directors have taken the view that when Shakespeare wrote a comedy, he did intend there to be a [[happy ending]], and accordingly that is the way the concluding scene should be staged. [[Elijah Moshinsky]] in his acclaimed [[BBC]] version in 1981 had his Bertram ([[Ian Charleson]]) give Helena a tender kiss and speak wonderingly. Despite his outrageous actions, Bertram can come across as beguiling; the filming of the 1967 [[Royal Shakespeare Company|RSC]] performance with [[Ian Richardson]] as Bertram has been lost, but by various accounts (''The New Cambridge Shakespeare'', 2003 etc.) he managed to make Bertram sympathetic, even charming. Ian Charleson's Bertram was cold and egotistical but still attractive.\n\nOne character that has been admired is that of the old Countess of Roussillon, which [[George Bernard Shaw|Shaw]] thought \"the most beautiful old woman's part ever written\".<ref name=dickson /> Modern productions are often promoted as vehicles for great mature actresses; examples in recent decades have starred [[Judi Dench]] and [[Peggy Ashcroft]], who delivered a performance of \"entranc[ing]...worldly wisdom and compassion\" in [[Trevor Nunn]]'s sympathetic, \"[[Anton Chekhov|Chekhovian]]\" staging at [[Royal Shakespeare Company|Stratford]] in 1982.<ref name=dickson /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/2003/dec/14/features.review77|title=Judi...and the beast|last=Kellaway|first=Kate|date=14 December 2003|work=The Observer |location=UK|accessdate=5 July 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Billington|first=Michael|authorlink=Michael Billington (critic)|title=One Night Stands: a Critic's View of Modern British Theatre|publisher=[[Nick Hern Books]]|location=London|date=2001|edition=2|pages=174\u2013176|isbn=1-85459-660-8}}</ref> In the [[BBC Television Shakespeare]] production she was played by [[Celia Johnson]], dressed and posed as [[Rembrandt]]'s portrait of Margaretha de Geer.\n\nIt has recently been argued that [[Thomas Middleton]] either collaborated with Shakespeare on the play, or revised it at a later time.<ref name=\"maguire\"/><ref>Taylor, Gary; Jowett, John; Bourus, Terri; Egan, Gabriel, eds. (2016). ''New Oxford Shakespeare: Modern Critical Edition''. Oxford: Oxford University Press. p.&nbsp;2274. {{ISBN|978-0-19-959115-2}}. Accessed 27 January 2020: \"Shakespeare is undoubtedly  the original author. Thomas Middleton added new material for a revival after Shakespeare's death, including the virginity dialogue..., the Kings speech about status and virtue..., and the gulling of Paroles\".</ref>\n\n==Performance history==\n\nNo records of the early performances of ''All's Well That Ends Well'' have been found. In 1741 the work was played at [[Goodman's Fields Theatre|Goodman's Fields]], with a later transfer to [[Theatre Royal, Drury Lane|Drury Lane]].<ref name=\"JG\" /> Rehearsals at Drury Lane started in October 1741 but [[William Milward (actor)|William Milward]] (1702\u20131742), playing the king, was taken ill, and the opening was delayed until the following 22 January. [[Margaret Woffington|Peg Woffington]], playing Helena, fainted on the first night and her part was read. Milward was taken ill again on 2 February and died on 6 February.<ref>{{cite book|last=Highfill|first=Philip|title=A biographical dictionary of actors, actresses, musicians, dancers, managers and other stage personnel in London, 1660\u20131800|volume=10|year=1984|publisher=Southern Illinois University Press|location=Carbondale, IL|isbn=978-0-8093-1130-9|page=262}}</ref> This, together with unsubstantiated tales of more illnesses befalling other actresses during the run, gave the play an \"unlucky\" reputation, similar to that attached to ''[[Macbeth]]'', and this may have curtailed the number of subsequent revivals.<ref name = JG>{{cite book|last=Genest|first=John|authorlink=John Genest|title=Some account of the English stage: from the Restoration in 1660 to 1830|volume=3|year=1832|publisher=Carrington|location=Bath, England|pages=645\u2013647}}</ref><ref>Fraser (2003: 15)</ref>\n\nHenry Woodward (1714\u20131777) popularised the part of Parolles in the era of [[David Garrick]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Cave|first=Richard Allen|title=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|year=2004|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford, England|chapter=Woodward, Henry (1714\u20131777)|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/29944}}</ref> Sporadic performances followed in the ensuing decades, with an operatic version at [[Royal Opera House|Covent Garden]] in 1832.<ref>[[William Linley]]'s song \"Was this fair face\" was written for ''All's Well That Ends Well''.</ref>\n\nThe play, with plot elements drawn from [[Romance (heroic literature)|romance]] and the [[Ribaldry|ribald tale]], depends on gender role conventions, both as expressed (Bertram) and challenged (Helena). With evolving conventions of gender roles, Victorian objections centred on the character of Helena, who was variously deemed predatory, immodest and both \"really despicable\" and a \"doormat\" by [[Ellen Terry]], who also\u2014and rather contradictorily\u2014accused her of \"hunt[ing] men down in the most undignified way\".<ref>Ellen Terry (1932) Four Essays on Shakespeare</ref> Terry's friend [[George Bernard Shaw]] greatly admired Helena's character, comparing her with the [[New Woman]] figures such as Nora in [[Henrik Ibsen]]'s ''[[A Doll's House]]''.<ref name=dickson /> The editor of the Arden Shakespeare volume summed up 19th century repugnance: \"everyone who reads this play is at first shocked and perplexed by the revolting idea that underlies the plot.\"<ref>W. Osborne Brigstocke, ''ed. All's Well That Ends Well'', \"Introduction\" p. xv.</ref>\n\nIn 1896 [[Frederick S. Boas]] coined the term \"problem play\" to include the unpopular work, grouping it with ''[[Hamlet]]'', ''[[Troilus and Cressida]]'' and ''[[Measure for Measure]]''.<ref>{{cite book|last=Neely|first=Carol Thomas |title=Broken nuptials in Shakespeare's plays|location=New Haven, CT|date=1983|publisher=University of Yale Press|page=58|chapter=Power and Virginity in the Problem Comedies: All's Well That Ends Well|isbn=978-0-300-03341-0}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Evans, G. Blakemore, ''The Riverside Shakespeare'', 1974.\n* {{cite book|last=Fraser|first=Russell|title=All's Well That Ends Well|edition=2|series=The New Cambridge Shakespeare|year=2003|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge, England|isbn=978-0-521-53515-1}}\n* Lawrence, W. W., ''Shakespeare's Problem Comedies'', 1931.\n* Price, Joseph G., ''The Unfortunate Comedy'', 1968.\n* Schoff, Francis G., \"Claudio, Bertram, and a Note on Interpretation\", ''Shakespeare Quarterly'', 1959.\n* Styan, J. G., ''Shakespeare in Performance series'': All's Well That Ends Well, 1985.\n\n==External links==\n* {{gutenberg|no=1529|name=All's Well That Ends Well}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110217230733/http://www.folger.edu/template.cfm?cid=877 Folger Shakespeare Library: ''All's Well That Ends Well'']\n* [http://www.maximumedge.com/shakespeare/allwell.htm MaximumEdge.com Shakespeare: ''All's Well That Ends Well''] \u2013 searchable scene-indexed version of the play.\n* {{librivox book | title=All's Well That Ends Well | author=William Shakespeare}}\n\n{{Shakespeare}}\n{{Thomas Middleton}}\n{{All's Well That Ends Well}}\n{{Subject bar\n|portal1        =\n|commons        = y\n|q              = y\n|s              = y\n|s-search       = All's Well That Ends Well (Shakespeare)\n}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1600s plays]]\n[[Category:Adaptations of works by Giovanni Boccaccio]]\n[[Category:English proverbs]]\n[[Category:English Renaissance plays]]\n[[Category:British plays adapted into films]]\n[[Category:Plays by Thomas Middleton]]\n[[Category:Plays set in France]]\n[[Category:Shakespearean comedies]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|Shakespeare's play}}\n{{short description|play by Shakespeare}}\n{{italic title}}\n{{use British English|date=August 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n[[File:First Folio, Shakespeare - 0248.jpg|thumb|The first page of ''All's Well, that Ends Well'' from the [[First Folio]] of Shakespeare's plays, published in 1623.]]\n\n'''''All's Well That Ends Well''''' is a play by [[William Shakespeare]], published in the ''[[First Folio]]'' in 1623, where it is listed among the [[Shakespearean comedy|comedies]]. There is a debate regarding the dating of the composition of the play, with possible dates ranging from 1598 to 1608.<ref>{{cite book|last=Snyder|first=Susan|title=The Oxford Shakespeare: All's Well That Ends Well|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford, England|date=1993|pages=20\u201324|chapter=Introduction|isbn=978-0-19-283604-5}}</ref><ref name=\"maguire\">{{cite news|title=Many Hands \u2013 A New Shakespeare Collaboration?|last=Maguire|first=Laurie|date=19 April 2012|newspaper=[[The Times Literary Supplement]]|access-date=|last2=Smith|first2=Emma}} also at [http://www.cems-oxford.org/many-hands Centre for Early Modern Studies], [[University of Oxford]] accessed 22 April 2012: \"The recent redating of All\u2019s Well from 1602\u201303 to 1606\u201307 (or later) has gone some way to resolving some of the play\u2019s stylistic anomalies\" ... \"[S]tylistically it is striking how many of the widely acknowledged textual and tonal problems of All\u2019s Well can be understood differently when we postulate dual authorship.\"</ref>\n\nThe play is considered one of Shakespeare's \"[[Shakespearean problem play|problem plays]]\"; a play that poses complex ethical dilemmas that require more than typically simple solutions.<ref>Snyder, Susan (1993). \"Introduction\". ''The Oxford Shakespeare: All's Well That Ends Well''. Oxford, England: Oxford University Press. pp.\u00a016\u201319. {{ISBN|9780192836045}}</ref>\n[[File:Helena and the Countess.jpg|thumb|right|A watercolour of Helena and the Countess, from Act I, Scene iii.]]\n\n==Characters==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[King of France]]\n* Duke of [[Florence]]\n* Bertram, [[Counts of Roussillon|Count of Roussillon]]\n* Countess of Roussillon, Mother of Bertram\n* Lavatch, a [[Clown]] in her household\n* Helena, a [[Gentlewoman]] protected by the Countess{{0|000}}\n* Lafew, an old Lord\n* Parolles, a follower of Bertram\n* An Old Widow of Florence, surnamed Capilet\n* Diana, Daughter of the Widow\n* Steward of the Countess of Roussillon\n* Violenta ([[ghost character]]) and Mariana, Neighbours and Friends of the Widow\n* A Page\n* Soldiers, Servants, Gentlemen, and Courtiers\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Synopsis==\n[[File:All's Well that Ends Well Lithograph.jpg|thumb|right|A lithograph depicting Act IV Scene III.]]\nHelena, the low-born [[Ward (law)|ward]] of a French-Spanish countess, is in love with the countess's son Bertram, who is indifferent to her. Bertram goes to Paris to replace his late father as attendant to the ailing King of France. Helena, the daughter of a recently deceased [[physician]], follows Bertram, ostensibly to offer the King her services as a healer. The King is sceptical, and she guarantees the cure with her life: if he dies, she will be put to death, but if he lives, she may choose a [[husband]] from the court.\n\nThe King is cured and Helena chooses Bertram, who rejects her, owing to her poverty and low status. The King forces him to marry her, but after the ceremony Bertram immediately goes to war in Italy without so much as a goodbye kiss. He says that he will only marry her after she has borne his child and wears his family ring. Helena returns home to the countess, who is horrified at what her son has done, and claims Helena as her child in Bertram's place.\n\nIn Italy, Bertram is a successful warrior and also a successful seducer of local virgins. Helena follows him to Italy, befriends Diana, a virgin with whom Bertram is infatuated, and they arrange for Helena to take Diana's place in bed. Diana obtains Bertram's ring in exchange for one of Helena's. In this way Helena, without Bertram's knowledge, consummates their marriage and wears his ring.\n\nHelena fakes her own death. Bertram, thinking he is free of her, comes home. He tries to marry a local lord's daughter, but Diana shows up and breaks up the engagement. Helena appears and explains the ring swap, announcing that she has fulfilled Bertram's challenge; Bertram, impressed by all she has done to win him, swears his love to her. Thus all ends well.\n\nThere is a subplot about Parolles\u2014a disloyal associate of Bertram's: Some of the lords at the court attempt to get Bertram to know that his friend Parolles is a boasting [[coward]]\u2014as Lafew and the Countess have also said. They convince Parolles to cross into enemy territory to fetch a drum that he left behind. While on his way, they pose as enemy soldiers, kidnap him, blindfold him, and, with Bertram observing, get him to betray his friends, and besmirch Bertram's character.\n\n[[File:All's Well That Ends Well Act V Scene iii.jpg|thumb|A 1794 print of the final scene]]\n\n==Sources==\n[[File:Decameron Title Page.jpg|thumb|A copy of Boccaccio's ''The decameron containing an hundred pleasant nouels. Wittily discoursed, betweene seauen honourable ladies, and three noble gentlemen'', printed by [[Isaac Jaggard]] in 1620.]]\nThe play is based on a [[Summary of Decameron tales#Ninth tale (III, 9)|tale (tale nine of day three)]] of [[Giovanni Boccaccio|Boccaccio]]'s ''[[The Decameron]]''. Shakespeare may have read an English translation of the tale in [[William Painter (author)|William Painter]]'s ''Palace of Pleasure''.<ref>[[F. E. Halliday]], ''A Shakespeare Companion 1564\u20131964,'' Baltimore, Penguin, 1964; p.&nbsp;29.</ref>\n\n==Analysis and criticism==\n\nThere is no evidence that ''All's Well That Ends Well'' was popular in Shakespeare's own lifetime and it has remained one of his lesser-known plays ever since, in part due to its unorthodox mixture of [[fairy tale]] logic, [[gender role]] reversals and [[Cynicism (contemporary)|cynical realism]]. Helena's love for the seemingly unlovable Bertram is difficult to explain on the page, but in performance it can be made acceptable by casting an actor of obvious physical attraction or by playing him as a [[naive]] and innocent figure not yet ready for love although, as both Helena and the audience can see, capable of emotional growth.<ref>{{cite book|last=McCandless|first=David |title=Gender and performance in Shakespeare's problem comedies|publisher=Indiana University Press|location=Bloomington, IN|date=1997|pages=57\u201359|chapter=All's Well That Ends Well|isbn=0-253-33306-7}}</ref> This latter interpretation also assists at the point in the final scene in which Bertram suddenly switches from hatred to love in just one line. This is considered a particular problem for actors trained to admire psychological realism. However, some alternative readings emphasise the \"if\" in his equivocal promise: \"If she, my liege, can make me know this clearly, I'll love her dearly, ever, ever dearly.\" Here, there has been no change of heart at all.<ref name=dickson>{{cite book|last=Dickson|first=Andrew|title=The Rough Guide to Shakespeare|publisher=Penguin|location=London|date=2008|pages=3\u201311|chapter=All's Well That Ends Well|isbn=978-1-85828-443-9}}</ref> Productions like the National Theatre's 2009 run, have Bertram make his promise seemingly normally, but then end the play hand-in-hand with Helena, staring out at the audience with a look of \"aghast bewilderment\" suggesting he only relented to save face in front of the King.<ref>{{cite news|last=Billington|first=Michael|authorlink=Michael Billington (critic)|title=Theatre review: All's Well That Ends Well / Olivier, London|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2009/may/29/theatre|accessdate=9 May 2011|newspaper=The Guardian|date=29 May 2009}}</ref> A 2018 interpretation from director [[Caroline Byrne (stage director)|Caroline Byrne]] at the [[Sam Wanamaker Playhouse]], London, effects Bertram's reconciliation with Helena by having him make good his vow (Act 2 Scene 2) of only taking her as his wife when she bears his child; as well as Bertram's ring, Helena brings their infant child to their final confrontation before the king.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Taylor|first1=Paul|title=All's Well That Ends Well, review: Eye-opening and vividly alive|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/theatre-dance/reviews/alls-well-that-ends-well-sam-wanamaker-playhouse-review-a8165611.html|website=[[The Independent]]|date=18 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nMany critics consider that the truncated ending is a drawback, with Bertram's conversion so sudden. Various explanations have been given for this. There is (as always) possibly missing text. Some suggest that Bertram's conversion is meant to be sudden and magical in keeping with the 'clever [[wench]] performing tasks to win an unwilling higher born husband' theme of the play.<ref>W. W. Lawrence, ''Shakespeare's Problem Comedies'' 1931.</ref> Some consider that Bertram is not meant to be contemptible, merely a callow youth learning valuable lessons about values.<ref>J. G. Styan ''Shakespeare in Performance'' 1984; Francis G Schoff ''Claudio, Bertram and a Note on Inerpretation'', 1959</ref> Contemporary audiences would readily have recognised Bertram's enforced marriage as a metaphor for the new requirement (1606), directed at followers of the Catholic religion, to swear an [[Oath of Allegiance (United Kingdom)#To James I|Oath of Allegiance]] to Protestant [[James I of England|King James]], suggests academic Andrew Hadfield of the [[University of Sussex]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hadfield|first1=Andrew|title=Bad Faith|journal=Globe|date=August 2017|pages=48\u201353|issn=2398-9483}}</ref>\n\nMany directors have taken the view that when Shakespeare wrote a comedy, he did intend there to be a [[happy ending]], and accordingly that is the way the concluding scene should be staged. [[Elijah Moshinsky]] in his acclaimed [[BBC]] version in 1981 had his Bertram ([[Ian Charleson]]) give Helena a tender kiss and speak wonderingly. Despite his outrageous actions, Bertram can come across as beguiling; the filming of the 1967 [[Royal Shakespeare Company|RSC]] performance with [[Ian Richardson]] as Bertram has been lost, but by various accounts (''The New Cambridge Shakespeare'', 2003 etc.) he managed to make Bertram sympathetic, even charming. Ian Charleson's Bertram was cold and egotistical but still attractive.\n\nOne character that has been admired is that of the old Countess of Roussillon, which [[George Bernard Shaw|Shaw]] thought \"the most beautiful old woman's part ever written\".<ref name=dickson /> Modern productions are often promoted as vehicles for great mature actresses; examples in recent decades have starred [[Judi Dench]] and [[Peggy Ashcroft]], who delivered a performance of \"entranc[ing]...worldly wisdom and compassion\" in [[Trevor Nunn]]'s sympathetic, \"[[Anton Chekhov|Chekhovian]]\" staging at [[Royal Shakespeare Company|Stratford]] in 1982.<ref name=dickson /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/2003/dec/14/features.review77|title=Judi...and the beast|last=Kellaway|first=Kate|date=14 December 2003|work=The Observer |location=UK|accessdate=5 July 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Billington|first=Michael|authorlink=Michael Billington (critic)|title=One Night Stands: a Critic's View of Modern British Theatre|publisher=[[Nick Hern Books]]|location=London|date=2001|edition=2|pages=174\u2013176|isbn=1-85459-660-8}}</ref> In the [[BBC Television Shakespeare]] production she was played by [[Celia Johnson]], dressed and posed as [[Rembrandt]]'s portrait of Margaretha de Geer.\n\nIt has recently been argued that [[Thomas Middleton]] either collaborated with Shakespeare on the play, or revised it at a later time.<ref name=\"maguire\"/><ref>Taylor, Gary; Jowett, John; Bourus, Terri; Egan, Gabriel, eds. (2016). ''New Oxford Shakespeare: Modern Critical Edition''. Oxford: Oxford University Press. p.&nbsp;2274. {{ISBN|978-0-19-959115-2}}. Accessed 27 January 2020: \"Shakespeare is undoubtedly  the original author. Thomas Middleton added new material for a revival after Shakespeare's death, including the virginity dialogue..., the Kings speech about status and virtue..., and the gulling of Paroles\".</ref>\n\n==Performance history==\n\nNo records of the early performances of ''All's Well That Ends Well'' have been found. In 1741 the work was played at [[Goodman's Fields Theatre|Goodman's Fields]], with a later transfer to [[Theatre Royal, Drury Lane|Drury Lane]].<ref name=\"JG\" /> Rehearsals at Drury Lane started in October 1741 but [[William Milward (actor)|William Milward]] (1702\u20131742), playing the king, was taken ill, and the opening was delayed until the following 22 January. [[Margaret Woffington|Peg Woffington]], playing Helena, fainted on the first night and her part was read. Milward was taken ill again on 2 February and died on 6 February.<ref>{{cite book|last=Highfill|first=Philip|title=A biographical dictionary of actors, actresses, musicians, dancers, managers and other stage personnel in London, 1660\u20131800|volume=10|year=1984|publisher=Southern Illinois University Press|location=Carbondale, IL|isbn=978-0-8093-1130-9|page=262}}</ref> This, together with unsubstantiated tales of more illnesses befalling other actresses during the run, gave the play an \"unlucky\" reputation, similar to that attached to ''[[Macbeth]]'', and this may have curtailed the number of subsequent revivals.<ref name = JG>{{cite book|last=Genest|first=John|authorlink=John Genest|title=Some account of the English stage: from the Restoration in 1660 to 1830|volume=3|year=1832|publisher=Carrington|location=Bath, England|pages=645\u2013647}}</ref><ref>Fraser (2003: 15)</ref>\n\nHenry Woodward (1714\u20131777) popularised the part of Parolles in the era of [[David Garrick]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Cave|first=Richard Allen|title=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|year=2004|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford, England|chapter=Woodward, Henry (1714\u20131777)|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/29944}}</ref> Sporadic performances followed in the ensuing decades, with an operatic version at [[Royal Opera House|Covent Garden]] in 1832.<ref>[[William Linley]]'s song \"Was this fair face\" was written for ''All's Well That Ends Well''.</ref>\n\nThe play, with plot elements drawn from [[Romance (heroic literature)|romance]] and the [[Ribaldry|ribald tale]], depends on gender role conventions, both as expressed (Bertram) and challenged (Helena). With evolving conventions of gender roles, Victorian objections centred on the character of Helena, who was variously deemed predatory, immodest and both \"really despicable\" and a \"doormat\" by [[Ellen Terry]], who also\u2014and rather contradictorily\u2014accused her of \"hunt[ing] men down in the most undignified way\".<ref>Ellen Terry (1932) Four Essays on Shakespeare</ref> Terry's friend [[George Bernard Shaw]] greatly admired Helena's character, comparing her with the [[New Woman]] figures such as Nora in [[Henrik Ibsen]]'s ''[[A Doll's House]]''.<ref name=dickson /> The editor of the Arden Shakespeare volume summed up 19th century repugnance: \"everyone who reads this play is at first shocked and perplexed by the revolting idea that underlies the plot.\"<ref>W. Osborne Brigstocke, ''ed. All's Well That Ends Well'', \"Introduction\" p. xv.</ref>\n\nIn 1896 [[Frederick S. Boas]] coined the term \"problem play\" to include the unpopular work, grouping it with ''[[Hamlet]]'', ''[[Troilus and Cressida]]'' and ''[[Measure for Measure]]''.<ref>{{cite book|last=Neely|first=Carol Thomas |title=Broken nuptials in Shakespeare's plays|location=New Haven, CT|date=1983|publisher=University of Yale Press|page=58|chapter=Power and Virginity in the Problem Comedies: All's Well That Ends Well|isbn=978-0-300-03341-0}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Evans, G. Blakemore, ''The Riverside Shakespeare'', 1974\n* {{cite book|last=Fraser|first=Russell|title=All's Well That Ends Well|edition=2|series=The New Cambridge Shakespeare|year=2003|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge, England|isbn=978-0-521-53515-1}}\n* Lawrence, W. W., ''Shakespeare's Problem Comedies'', 1931\n* Price, Joseph G., ''The Unfortunate Comedy'', 1968\n* Schoff, Francis G., \"Claudio, Bertram, and a Note on Interpretation\", ''Shakespeare Quarterly'', 1959\n* Styan, J. G., ''Shakespeare in Performance series'': All's Well That Ends Well, 1985\n\n==External links==\n* {{gutenberg|no=1529|name=All's Well That Ends Well}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110217230733/http://www.folger.edu/template.cfm?cid=877 Folger Shakespeare Library: ''All's Well That Ends Well'']\n* [http://www.maximumedge.com/shakespeare/allwell.htm MaximumEdge.com Shakespeare: ''All's Well That Ends Well''] \u2013 searchable scene-indexed version of the play.\n* {{librivox book | title=All's Well That Ends Well | author=William Shakespeare}}\n\n{{Shakespeare}}\n{{Thomas Middleton}}\n{{All's Well That Ends Well}}\n{{Subject bar\n|portal1        =\n|commons        = y\n|q              = y\n|s              = y\n|s-search       = All's Well That Ends Well (Shakespeare)\n}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1600s plays]]\n[[Category:Adaptations of works by Giovanni Boccaccio]]\n[[Category:English proverbs]]\n[[Category:English Renaissance plays]]\n[[Category:British plays adapted into films]]\n[[Category:Plays by Thomas Middleton]]\n[[Category:Plays set in France]]\n[[Category:Shakespearean comedies]]\n", "name_user": "Stonedhamlet", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBibliography", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/All%27s_Well_That_Ends_Well"}
{"title_page": "Giant mouse lemur", "text_new": "{{short description|Genus of small primates from Madagascar}}\n{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{featured article}}\n{{Automatic taxobox\n|image=Mirza zaza, Madagascar, April 2006.jpg\n|image_caption=[[Northern giant mouse lemur]] ''(M.&nbsp;zaza)''\n|status=CITES_A1\n|status_system=CITES\n|status_ref={{R|CITES}}\n|taxon=Mirza\n|authority=[[John Edward Gray|Gray]], 1870\n|type_species=''[[Mirza coquereli|Cheirogalus coquereli]]''\n|type_species_authority=[[Alfred Grandidier|A. Grandidier]], 1867\n|subdivision_ranks=[[Species]]\n|subdivision={{plainlist|\n* ''[[Coquerel's giant mouse lemur|Mirza coquereli]]''\n* ''[[Northern giant mouse lemur|Mirza zaza]]''}}\n|range_map=Mirza range map.svg\n|range_map_caption=Distribution of ''Mirza'':\n'''{{color|#e41a1c|red}}'''=''M.&nbsp;coquereli'';{{R|IUCN_Mirza_coquereli}} '''{{color|#4daf4a|green}}'''=''M.&nbsp;zaza''{{R|IUCN_Mirza_zaza}}\n|range_map_alt=Map of Madagascar, off the southeast coast of Africa, with a range covering parts of the west and northwest.\n}}\n\nThe '''giant mouse lemurs''' are members of the [[Strepsirrhini|strepsirrhine]] primate [[genus]] '''''Mirza'''''. Two [[species]] have been formally described; the [[northern giant mouse lemur]] (''Mirza zaza'') and [[Coquerel's giant mouse lemur]] (''Mirza coquereli''). Like all other [[lemur]]s, they are native to [[Madagascar]], where they are found in the [[Madagascar dry deciduous forests|western dry deciduous forests]] and further to the north in the [[Sambirano River|Sambirano Valley]] and [[Sahamalaza National Park|Sahamalaza Peninsula]]. First [[Species description|described]] in 1867 as a single species, they were grouped with [[mouse lemur]]s and [[dwarf lemur]]s. In 1870, British zoologist [[John Edward Gray]] assigned them to their own genus, ''Mirza''. The classification was not widely accepted until the 1990s, which followed the revival of the genus by American paleoanthropologist [[Ian Tattersall]] in 1982. In 2005, the northern population was declared a new species, and in 2010, the [[World Wide Fund for Nature]] announced that a southwestern population might also be a new species.\n\nGiant mouse lemurs are about three times larger than mouse lemurs, weighing approximately {{convert|300|g|oz|abbr=on}}, and have a long, bushy tail. They are most closely related to mouse lemurs within [[Cheirogaleidae]], a [[Family (biology)|family]] of small, [[Nocturnality|nocturnal]] lemurs. Giant mouse lemurs sleep in nests during the day and forage alone at night for fruit, [[Natural gum|tree gum]], insects, and small [[vertebrate]]s. Unlike many other cheirogaleids, they do not enter a state of [[torpor]] during the dry season. The northern species is generally more social than the southern species, particularly when nesting, though males and females may form [[pair bond]]s. The northern species also has the largest [[testicle]] size relative to its body size among all primates and is atypical among lemurs for breeding year-round instead of [[Seasonal breeder|seasonally]]. [[Home range]]s often overlap, with related females living closely together while males [[Biological dispersal|disperse]]. Giant mouse lemurs are vocal, although they also [[Territory (animal)|scent mark]] using saliva, urine, and secretions from the [[Scent gland|anogenital scent gland]].\n\nPredators of giant mouse lemurs include the [[Madagascar buzzard]], [[Madagascar owl]], [[Fossa (animal)|fossa]], and the [[narrow-striped mongoose]]. Giant mouse lemurs reproduce once a year, with two offspring born after a 90-day [[gestation]]. Babies are initially left in the nest while the mother forages, but are later carried by mouth and parked in vegetation while she forages nearby. In captivity, giant mouse lemurs will breed year-round. Their lifespan in the wild is thought to be five to six years. Both species are listed as [[Endangered species|endangered]] due to [[habitat destruction]] and hunting. Like all lemurs, they are protected under [[CITES|CITES Appendix I]], which prohibits commercial trade. Despite breeding easily, they are rarely kept in captivity. The [[Duke Lemur Center]] coordinated the [[captive breeding]] of an imported collection of the northern species, which rose from six individuals in 1982 to 62&nbsp;individuals by 1989, but the population fell to six by 2009 and was no longer considered a breeding population.\n\n==Taxonomy==\n[[File:Mirza coquereli 1868.jpg|thumb|upright|right|alt=Artistic illustration of a giant mouse lemur climbing on a branch|The giant mouse lemur described by [[Hermann Schlegel|Schlegel]] and [[Fran\u00e7ois Pollen|Pollen]] in 1868 (illustrated above) was considered [[Synonym (taxonomy)|synonymous]] with the species described by [[Alfred Grandidier|Grandidier]] (1867), but was shown to be a distinct species in 2005.]]\nThe first species of giant mouse lemur was [[Species description|described]] by the French naturalist [[Alfred Grandidier]] in 1867 based on seven individuals he had collected near [[Morondava]] in southwestern Madagascar. Of these seven specimens, the [[Type (biology)#Lectotype|lectotype]] was selected in 1939 as MNHN&nbsp;1867\u2013603, an adult skull and skin. Naming the species after the French entomologist [[Charles Coquerel]],{{Sfn|Beolens|Watkins|Grayson|2009|pp=85\u201386}} Grandidier placed [[Coquerel's giant mouse lemur]] (''M.&nbsp;coquereli'') with the [[dwarf lemur]]s in the [[genus]] ''Cheirogaleus'' (which he spelled ''Cheirogalus'') as ''C.&nbsp;coquereli''. He selected this generic assignment based on similarities with [[fork-marked lemur]]s (''Phaner''), which he considered to also be members of ''Cheirogaleus''. The following year, the German naturalist [[Hermann Schlegel]] and Dutch naturalist [[Fran\u00e7ois Pollen]] independently described the same species and coincidentally gave it the same specific name, ''coquereli'', basing theirs on an individual from around the [[Bay of Ampasindava]] in northern Madagascar. Unlike Grandidier, they placed their specimen in the genus ''Microcebus'' ([[mouse lemur]]s); however, these authors also listed all ''Cheirogaleus'' under ''Microcebus'' and based the classification of their species on similarities with the [[greater dwarf lemur]] (''M.&nbsp;typicus'', now ''C.&nbsp;major'').{{Sfn|Tattersall|1982|pp=127\u2013128}}\n\nIn 1870, the British zoologist [[John Edward Gray]] placed Coquerel's giant mouse lemur into its own genus, ''Mirza''. This classification was widely ignored and later rejected in the early 1930s by zoologists [[Ernst Schwarz (zoologist)|Ernst Schwarz]], [[Guillaume Grandidier]], and others, who felt that its longer fur and bushy tail did not merit a separate genus and instead placed it in ''Microcebus''.{{Sfn|Osman Hill|1953|p=325}} British anatomist [[William Charles Osman Hill]] also favored this view in 1953, noting that despite its larger size (comparable to ''Cheirogaleus''), its first upper [[premolar]] was proportionally small as in ''Microcebus''.{{Sfn|Osman Hill|1953|p=333}} In 1977, French zoologist [[Jean-Jacques Petter]] also favored the ''Microcebus'' classification, despite the threefold size difference between Coquerel's giant mouse lemur and the other members of the genus.{{LoM3 Sfn|p=160}}\n\nThe genus ''Mirza'' was resurrected in 1982 by American paleoanthropologist [[Ian Tattersall]]{{Sfn|Tattersall|1982|pp=127\u2013128}}{{LoM3 Sfn|p=160}}{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|p=1316}} to represent an intermediate branch between ''Microcebus'' and ''Cheirogaleus'',{{Sfn|Tattersall|1982|pp=127\u2013128}} citing the Coquerel's giant mouse lemur's significantly larger size than the largest ''Microcebus'' and [[Animal locomotion|locomotor behavior]] more closely aligned with ''Cheirogaleus''.{{Sfn|Tattersall|1982|pp=127\u2013128}}{{LoM3 Sfn|p=160}} Adoption of ''Mirza'' was slow,{{Sfn|Harcourt|1990|p=47}} though in 1994 it was used in the first edition of ''[[Lemurs of Madagascar (book)|Lemurs of Madagascar]]'' by [[Conservation International]].{{Sfn|Nowak|1999|p=67}}{{LoM1 Sfn|p=80}} In 1993, primatologist [[Colin Groves]] initially favored the ''Microcebus'' classification in the second edition of ''[[Mammal Species of the World]]'',{{Sfn|Nowak|1999|p=67}} but began supporting the resurrection of ''Mirza'' in 2001.{{LoM3 Sfn|p=160}}{{Sfn|Groves|2001|pp=70\u201371}} In 1991, prior to adopting ''Mirza'', Groves was the first to use the [[common name]] \"giant mouse lemur\". Prior to that, they were popularly referred to as \"Coquerel's mouse lemur\".{{Sfn|Dunkel|Zijlstra|Groves|2012|p=67}}\n\nIn 2005, Peter M. Kappeler and Christian Roos described a new species of giant mouse lemur, the [[northern giant mouse lemur]] (''M.&nbsp;zaza'').{{LoM3 Sfn|p=160}}{{Sfn|Kappeler|Rasoloarison|Razafimanantsoa|Walter|2005|p=3}} Their studies compared the [[Morphology (biology)|morphology]], [[behavioral ecology]], and [[Cytochrome b|mitochondrial cytochrome b]] [[Sequencing|sequences]] of specimens from both [[Kirindy Forest]] in central-western Madagascar and around [[Ambato, Madagascar|Ambato]] in northwestern Madagascar,{{LoM3 Sfn|p=160}}{{Sfn|Kappeler|Rasoloarison|Razafimanantsoa|Walter|2005|p=3}} part of the [[Sambirano River|Sambirano valley]].{{LoM3 Sfn|p=160}} Their study demonstrated distinct differences in size, [[sociality]], and [[Reproduction|breeding]], as well as sufficient [[genetic distance]] to merit specific distinction between the northern and central-western populations. Because Grandidier's description was based on a southern specimen, they named the northern population as a new species.{{Sfn|Kappeler|Rasoloarison|Razafimanantsoa|Walter|2005|p=3}}\n\nThe [[World Wide Fund for Nature]] (WWF) announced in 2010 that a [[biodiversity]] study from 2009 in the [[gallery forest]] of [[Ranobe, Madagascar|Ranobe]] near [[Toliara]] in southwestern Madagascar revealed a population of giant mouse lemurs previously unknown to science, and possibly a new species. They noted a significant difference in coloration between the two known species and the specimen they observed. However, further testing was required to confirm the discovery.{{r|WWF_25Mar2010}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{cladogram|title=Competing phylogenies\n|caption=''Mirza'', ''Microcebus'', and ''Allocebus'' form a [[Cladistics|clade]] within Cheirogaleidae, regardless of whether ''Phaner'' is a [[sister group]] (top\u2014Weisrock ''et al.'' 2012){{Sfn|Weisrock|Smith|Chan|Biebouw|2012|p=1626}} or more closely related to ''Lepilemur'' (bottom\u2014Masters ''et al.'' 2013).{{Sfn|Masters|Silvestro|G\u00e9nin|DelPero|2013|p=209}}\n|cladogram={{Clade|style=font-size:85%; line-height:75%; width:34em;\n|1={{Clade\n   |label1=Lepilemuridae&nbsp;\n   |1=''Lepilemur'' ([[sportive lemur]]s)\n   |label2=[[Cheirogaleidae]]&nbsp;\n   |2={{Clade\n      |1=''Phaner'' ([[fork-marked lemur]]s)\n      |2={{Clade\n         |1=''Cheirogaleus'' ([[dwarf lemur]]s)\n         |2={{Clade\n            |1=''Allocebus'' ([[hairy-eared dwarf lemur]])\n            |2={{Clade\n               |1='''''Mirza''''' ('''giant mouse lemurs''')\n               |2=''Microcebus'' ([[mouse lemur]]s)\n               }}\n            }}\n         }}\n      }}\n   }}\n}}\n|cladogram2={{Clade|style=font-size:85%; line-height:75%; width:32em;\n|label1=[[Cheirogaleidae]]&nbsp;\n|1={{Clade\n   |1={{Clade\n      |1=''Phaner'' (fork-marked lemurs)\n      |2=''Lepilemur'' (sportive lemurs)\n      }}\n   |2={{Clade\n      |1=''Cheirogaleus'' (dwarf lemurs)\n      |2={{Clade\n         |1=''Allocebus'' (hairy-eared dwarf lemur)\n         |2={{Clade\n            |1='''''Mirza''''' ('''giant mouse lemurs''')\n            |2=''Microcebus'' (mouse lemurs)\n            }}\n         }}\n      }}\n   }}\n}}\n}}\nThe etymology of ''Mirza'' puzzled researchers for many years. Gray often created mysterious and unexplained [[Taxonomy (biology)|taxonomic names]]\u2014a trend continued with his description of not only ''Mirza'' in 1870, but also the genera ''Phaner'' (fork-marked lemurs) and ''Azema'' (for ''[[Brown mouse lemur|M.&nbsp;rufus]]'', now a synonym for ''Microcebus''), both of which were described in the same publication. In 1904, American zoologist [[Theodore Sherman Palmer]] attempted to document the etymologies of all mammalian taxa, but could not definitively explain these three genera. For ''Mirza'', Palmer only noted that it derived from the [[Persian language|Persian]] title [[Mirza|m\u00eerz\u00e2]] (\"prince\"), a view tentatively supported by Alex Dunkel, Jelle Zijlstra, and Groves in 2012. However, because the reference to Persian princes might have come from ''[[One Thousand and One Nights|Arabian Nights]]'', a popular piece of literature at the time, Dunkel ''et al.'' also searched the general literature published around 1870. The origin of all three names was found in a British comedy ''[[The Palace of Truth]]'' by [[W. S. Gilbert]], which premiered in London on 19&nbsp;November&nbsp;1870, nearly one and a half weeks prior to the date written on the preface of Gray's manuscript (also published in London). The comedy featured characters bearing all three names: King Phanor (''sic''), Mirza, and Azema. The authors concluded that Gray had seen the comedy and then based the names of three lemur genera on its characters.{{Sfn|Dunkel|Zijlstra|Groves|2012|pp=66\u201367}}\n\n===Evolution===\nBased on studies using morphology, [[immunology]], [[Repeated sequence (DNA)|repetitive DNA]], [[Retrotransposon#SINEs|SINE]] analysis, [[Locus (genetics)|multilocus]] phylogenetic tests,{{Sfn|Weisrock|Smith|Chan|Biebouw|2012|p=1626}} and [[Mitochondrial DNA|mitochondrial genes]] (mtDNA),{{Sfn|Masters|Silvestro|G\u00e9nin|DelPero|2013|pp=203\u2013204}} giant mouse lemurs are most closely related to mouse lemurs within the family Cheirogaleidae, and together they form a [[Cladistics|clade]] with the [[hairy-eared dwarf lemur]] (''Allocebus''). Both dwarf lemurs and fork-marked lemurs are more distantly related,{{Sfn|Weisrock|Smith|Chan|Biebouw|2012|p=1626}}{{Sfn|Masters|Silvestro|G\u00e9nin|DelPero|2013|p=209}}{{Sfn|Roos|Schmitz|Zischler|2004|p=10653}} with fork-marked lemurs being either a [[sister group]] of all cheirogaleids,{{Sfn|Weisrock|Smith|Chan|Biebouw|2012|p=1626}}{{Sfn|Roos|Schmitz|Zischler|2004|p=10653}} or more closely related to [[sportive lemur]]s (''Lepilemur'').{{Sfn|Masters|Silvestro|G\u00e9nin|DelPero|2013|p=209}}\n\nAlthough ''Mirza'', ''Microcebus'', and ''Allocebus'' form a clade within Cheirogaleidae, the three lineages are thought to have [[Genetic divergence|diverged]] during a narrow window of time, so the relationships within this clade are difficult to determine and may change with further research.{{Sfn|Weisrock|Smith|Chan|Biebouw|2012|pp=1627\u20131628}} All three are thought to have diverged at least 20&nbsp;[[myr|mya]] (million years ago),{{Sfn|Masters|Silvestro|G\u00e9nin|DelPero|2013|p=209}} although another estimate using mtDNA places the divergence between ''Mirza'' and ''Microcebus'' at 24.2&nbsp;mya. Divergence between the two recognized species of giant mouse lemur is estimated at 2.1&nbsp;mya.{{Sfn|Kappeler|Rasoloarison|Razafimanantsoa|Walter|2005|p=15}}\n\n==Description==\nThough giant mouse lemurs are relatively small cheirogaleids,{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|p=1316}} they are more than three times larger than the smallest members of the family, the mouse lemurs.{{LoM3 Sfn|p=160}} Their body weight averages {{convert|300|g|oz|abbr=on}}.{{LoM3 Sfn|p=160}}{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|p=1316}} At around {{convert|300|mm|in|abbr=on}}, their bushy and long tail is longer than their head-body length, which averages {{convert|233|mm|in|abbr=on}}.{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|p=1316}} Their forelimbs are shorter than the hind limbs (with an [[intermembral index]] of 70), a trait shared with mouse lemurs.{{Sfn|Fleagle|2013|pp=60\u201361}} The skull is similar to that of dwarf and mouse lemurs,{{Sfn|Tattersall|1982|p=127}} and the [[Tympanic part of the temporal bone|auditory bullae]] are small.{{Sfn|Groves|2001|p=70}}\n\nLike other cheirogaleids, the [[Dentition#Dental formula|dental formula]] for giant mouse lemurs is {{DentalFormula|upper=2.1.3.3|lower=2.1.3.3|total=36}}; on each side of the mouth, top and bottom, there are two [[incisor]]s, one [[Canine tooth|canine]], three premolars, and three [[Molar (tooth)|molars]]\u2014a total of 36&nbsp;teeth.{{Sfn|Swindler|2002|p=73}} Their upper teeth converge towards the front of the mouth, but are straighter than those in mouse lemurs.{{Sfn|Groves|2001|p=70}} The first upper premolar (P<sup>2</sup>) is relatively small, but nearly as tall as the next premolar (P<sup>3</sup>). Unlike mouse lemurs and more like dwarf lemurs, giant mouse lemurs have a prominent [[Anatomical terms of location#anterior and posterior|anterior]] lower premolar (P<sub>2</sub>). Also more aligned with dwarf lemurs, the first two upper molars (M<sup>1\u20132</sup>) have a more anterior [[Molar (tooth)|hypocone]] that sits opposite the [[Molar (tooth)|metacone]], compared to the mouse lemurs' more [[Anatomical terms of location#anterior and posterior|posterior]] hypocone, which is presumably a [[Symplesiomorphy|symplesiomorphic (ancestral) trait]].{{Sfn|Tattersall|1982|p=127}} Also on M<sup>1</sup> and M<sup>2</sup>, the cingulum (a crest or ridge on the tongue side) comprises two small [[Cusp (anatomy)|cuspules]].{{Sfn|Groves|2001|p=70}} In all other dental characteristics, giant mouse lemurs are noticeably similar to both dwarf and mouse lemurs.{{Sfn|Tattersall|1982|p=127}}\n\nGiant mouse lemurs have two pairs of [[Mammary gland|mammae]], one on the chest (pectoral) and one on the [[abdomen]] (abdominal).{{Sfn|Tattersall|1982|p=128}} Their fur is typically grayish-brown on the [[Anatomical terms of location#Dorsal and ventral|dorsal]] (back) side and more gray in color on the [[Anatomical terms of location#Dorsal and ventral|ventral]] (front) side.{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|p=1316}}{{Sfn|Kappeler|Rasoloarison|Razafimanantsoa|Walter|2005|p=18}} The tail is typically black-tipped.{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|p=1316}} The new population found by WWF in 2010 has an overall lighter color, along with reddish or rusty patches near the hands and feet on the dorsal side of the arms and legs. This population also has a red tail, which darkens at the end.{{r|WWF_25Mar2010}} [[Whiskers|Vibrissae]] are found above the eyes (superciliary), above the mouth (buccal), under the lower jaw (genal), near the [[Ramus of the mandible|top of the jaw]] (interramal), and on the wrist (carpal).{{Sfn|Tattersall|1982|p=129}} Like mouse lemurs, the ears are large and membranous.{{Sfn|Fleagle|2013|pp=60\u201362}}\n\nEar size is one differentiating factor between the northern giant mouse lemur and Coquerel's giant mouse lemur, with the former having shorter, rounded ears,{{Sfn|Kappeler|Rasoloarison|Razafimanantsoa|Walter|2005|p=18}} while the latter has relatively large ears.{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|p=1316}} The northern giant mouse lemur is generally larger and also has a shorter tail and shorter canine teeth.{{Sfn|Kappeler|Rasoloarison|Razafimanantsoa|Walter|2005|p=18}} This species also has the largest [[testicle]]s relative to body size of any living primate, with an average volume of {{convert|15.48|cm3|abbr=on}},{{Sfn|Rode\u2010Margono|Nekaris|Kappeler|Schwitzer|2015}}{{R|BBC_03Jul2015}} corresponding to 5.5% of its body weight. If human males had comparably sized testes, they would weigh {{convert|4|kg|lbs|abbr=on}} and be the size of a [[grapefruit]].{{R|BBC_03Jul2015}}\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\n[[File:Namoroka Tsingy.jpg|thumb|alt=Karst topography at Tsingy de Namoroka National Park in northwestern Madagascar|Coquerel's giant mouse lemur can be found at [[Tsingy de Namoroka Strict Nature Reserve|Tsingy de Namoroka National Park]].]]\nCoquerel's giant mouse lemur has a spotty distribution across [[Madagascar dry deciduous forests|western Madagascar's dry deciduous forests]] due to the [[forest fragmentation]] throughout the region.{{LoM3 Sfn|p=164}} The dry forests in this lowland region vary in elevation from sea level to {{convert|700|m|ft|abbr=on}}.{{R|IUCN_Mirza_coquereli}}{{LoM3 Sfn|p=164}} The range of this species is divided into northern and southern subpopulations,{{R|IUCN_Mirza_coquereli}} which are separated by several hundred kilometers. Both historical and current populations between these ranges are uncertain.{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|p=1316}} The southern region is bound by the [[Onilahy River]] in the south and the [[Tsiribihina River]] in the north, while the northern population is found in the northwestern corner of the island at [[Tsingy de Namoroka Strict Nature Reserve|Tsingy de Namoroka National Park]].{{R|IUCN_Mirza_coquereli}}{{LoM3 Sfn|p=164}}{{Sfn|Markolf|Kappeler|Rasoloarison|2008|pp=39\u201340}} They are most commonly found in forests near rivers and ponds.{{Sfn|Nowak|1999|p=67}}{{Sfn|Harcourt|1990|p=45}}\n\nThe northern giant mouse lemur is found in isolated forest patches along the northwest coast{{Sfn|Markolf|Kappeler|Rasoloarison|2008|p=37}} in both the more humid Sambirano valley{{R|IUCN_Mirza_coquereli}}{{Sfn|Harcourt|1990|p=45}} and [[Sahamalaza Peninsula]], as well as the [[Ampasindava Peninsula]].{{R|IUCN_Mirza_zaza}} Its range extends from the [[Maeverano River]] in the south to the [[Mahavavy River]] in the north.{{Sfn|Markolf|Kappeler|Rasoloarison|2008|p=37}} The new population reported by the WWF in 2010 is found in the gallery forests of Ranobe near Toliara in southwestern Madagascar.{{R|WWF_25Mar2010}}\n\n==Behavior==\nGiant mouse lemurs were first studied in the wild by Petter and colleagues in 1971.{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|p=1316}}{{Sfn|Pages|1980|p=97}} His observations were secondary to his primary research interest, the fork-marked lemurs north of Morondava. Both northern and southern populations were studied intermittently between 1978 and 1981, and in 1993, long-term social and genetic studies began in Kirindy Forest. Behavioral studies of captive individuals have also been performed at the [[Duke Lemur Center]] (DLC) in [[Durham, North Carolina]] during the 1990s.{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|p=1316}}\n\n===Population density and territory===\nBefore the recognition of more than one species, differences in [[population density]] were noted between southern forests like Kirindy and northern forests near [[Ambanja]].{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|p=1316}} Later, it was recognized that Coquerel's giant mouse lemur was found in lower densities than the northern giant mouse lemur.{{LoM3 Sfn|pp=168\u2013170}} The former range between 30 and 210&nbsp;individuals per square kilometer (250&nbsp;acres),{{LoM3 Sfn|pp=165\u2013166}} with lower densities in open areas of the forest,{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|p=1316}} while the latter has been recorded with 385 to 1,086&nbsp;individuals per km<sup>2</sup>. However, in the case of the northern giant mouse lemur, populations were found in more isolated forest fragments and it is thought that their consumption of [[Introduced species|introduced]] cashew and [[mango]] help sustain these higher populations.{{LoM3 Sfn|pp=168\u2013170}}\n\nAccording to studies of Coquerel's giant mouse lemur, [[home range]]s of both sexes vary from {{convert|1|to|4|ha|acre|sigfig=1|abbr=off}} with frequent overlap,{{LoM3 Sfn|pp=165\u2013166}}{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|p=1317}}{{Sfn|Fleagle|2013|p=62}} particularly on the periphery of their range.{{Sfn|Harcourt|1990|p=46}} Individuals most heavily use and aggressively defend a smaller core area within their range.{{LoM3 Sfn|pp=165\u2013166}}{{Sfn|Harcourt|1990|p=46}} Individuals can have up to eight neighbors.{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|p=1317}} Home ranges of males tend to overlap with those of both females and other males,{{LoM3 Sfn|pp=165\u2013166}} and typically expand to four times the size during the mating season.{{LoM3 Sfn|pp=165\u2013166}}{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|p=1317}} Female home ranges show no variability in size, and can remain stable for years. At Kirindy Forest, genetic studies showed that the home ranges of related females tend to clump closely together, while unrelated males may overlap their range, suggesting male [[Biological dispersal|dispersal]] and migration is responsible for [[gene flow]].{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|p=1317}}\n\n===Activity patterns===\nBoth species are strictly [[Nocturnality|nocturnal]],{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|p=1316}} leaving their nests around sunset to stretch and [[Personal grooming|self-groom]] for a few minutes.{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|p=1317}}{{LoM3 Sfn|p=167}}{{Sfn|Pages|1980|p=101}} Both species typically forage between {{convert|5|and|10|m|ft|abbr=on}} above the forest floor, though Coquerel's giant mouse lemur has been observed on the ground.{{LoM3 Sfn|p=167}} They primarily move by [[Quadrupedalism|quadrupedal]] running and occasionally leaping between branches, and use the same feeding postures as mouse lemurs, such as clinging to tree trunks.{{Sfn|Fleagle|2013|p=62}} When moving through the trees, giant mouse lemurs scurry rapidly like mouse lemurs, unlike dwarf lemurs, which use more deliberate movement.{{Sfn|Tattersall|1982|p=127}} Slow movements are usually seen in lower, denser foliage when hunting for insects, while more rapid motion and leaping is typically seen at moderate heights of {{convert|2|\u2013|5|m|ft|abbr=on|sigfig=2}}. Surveillance of the home range involves slower movements in lighter foliage near the tops of large trees, while movements along the border of a home range is more rapid and occurs at a lower height. Similar movement patterns have been observed in captivity as well.{{Sfn|Pages|1980|p=102}}\n\nGiant mouse lemurs begin foraging moments before the sun disappears,{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|p=1317}} occasionally participate in social activities during the last half of the night,{{LoM3 Sfn|p=167}}{{Sfn|Pages|1980|p=102}} and return to one of their nests prior to sunrise.{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|p=1317}} Cold temperatures cause them to leave the nest later and return early, sometime during the second half of the night.{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|p=1317}}{{LoM3 Sfn|p=167}}{{Sfn|Pages|1980|p=101}} During the first half of the night, giant mouse lemurs are more likely to rest for an hour or more, usually at the expense of social activities, but not feeding time. Rest periods are longer when temperatures are low.{{Sfn|Pages|1980|p=101}} Unlike many other cheirogaleids, they remain active all year and do not enter daily or seasonal [[torpor]].{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|p=1317}}{{LoM3 Sfn|p=167}}{{Sfn|Fleagle|2013|p=62}}\n\n===Nesting===\nBoth species sleep in round nests up to {{convert|50|cm|in|abbr=on}} across made of interlaced [[liana]]s, branches, leaves, and twigs gathered from nearby trees and woven using the mouth and hands. Nests are typically between {{convert|2|and|10|m|ft|sigfig=2|abbr=on}} above the ground in the fork of large tree branches or surrounded by dense lianas.{{Sfn|Pages|1980|p=101}}{{LoM3 Sfn|p=166}}{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|pp=1316\u20131317}} Trees covered in thick lianas as well as trees with year-round leaf cover (e.g. [[Euphorbiaceae]]) are favored for nest construction, though large bare trees may be used by building the nest higher.{{Sfn|Pages|1980|p=101}} In addition to nesting in dense lianas, individual giant mouse lemurs will rotate between 10 and 12&nbsp;nests every few days to avoid predators.{{LoM3 Sfn|p=166}}{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|pp=1316\u20131317}} Only females have been observed building nests in the wild,{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|pp=1316\u20131317}} though males, females, and young have been observed building nests in captivity.{{Sfn|Pages|1980|p=101}} Multiple nests are sometimes built in the same tree or in nearby trees and are shared by neighboring giant mouse lemurs, fork-marked lemurs, and the introduced [[black rat]] (''Rattus rattus''). Unlike most other nocturnal lemurs, giant mouse lemurs do not appear to sleep in tree holes.{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|pp=1316\u20131317}}\n\n===Social structure===\nBoth species usually are solitary foragers,{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|p=1317}}{{LoM3 Sfn|p=166}}{{LoM3 Sfn|p=170}} although the northern giant mouse lemur tends to be the most social, possibly due to its higher population density.{{LoM3 Sfn|p=171}} Up to eight (typically four) adult males, adult females, and juveniles may be found in a northern giant mouse lemur nest,{{Sfn|Kappeler|Rasoloarison|Razafimanantsoa|Walter|2005|p=3}}{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|p=1317}}{{LoM3 Sfn|pp=170\u2013171}} whereas Coquerel's giant mouse lemurs do not nest communally, except when females share their nest with their offspring.{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|p=1317}}{{LoM3 Sfn|p=166}} Males do groom and call to females when they come into contact, and according to [[Telemetry|radio-tracking]] and direct observations at [[Analabe]] near Kirindy, they form [[pair bond]]s,{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|p=1317}} sometimes briefly traveling together during the dry season.{{LoM3 Sfn|pp=165\u2013166}} However, most interactions between adults are infrequent and typically occur later at night and particularly during the dry season in overlapping core areas, often involving chases and other [[agonistic behavior]], and only rarely [[social grooming]].{{Sfn|Fleagle|2013|p=62}}{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|p=1318}} During the mating season, males act aggressively towards one another, pulling out fur around the head and shoulders and biting the head.{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|p=1318}}\n\nGiant mouse lemurs use at least eight vocalizations, the most common of which are contact calls, which sound like \"hum\" or a \"hein\" and are used when moving and when meeting familiar individuals. A \"mother-infant meeting call\" used at dawn before returning to the nest consists of short, modulated whistles. Both males and females have distinct single note calls used in territorial behavior; the female call sounds like \"pfiou\" and the male call is a short, loud whistle. Both sexes use an alarm call, which sounds like a \"croak\", and an agonistic call, which consists of repeated \"tisk-tisk-tisk\" sounds.{{Sfn|Pages|1980|p=108}} Females exhibit a \"waking call sequence\",{{Sfn|Pages|1980|pp=108\u2013109}} sometimes referred to as \"loud calls\", which start when foraging commences and then switch to quieter \"hon\" calls possibly to indicate their position to their neighbors.{{LoM3 Sfn|p=167}}{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|p=1318}}{{Sfn|Pages|1980|pp=108\u2013109}} A long \"sexual call sequence\" consisting of soft whistle and several modulated, hoarse \"brroak\" calls is used by both sexes during [[Estrous cycle|estrus]].{{Sfn|Pages|1980|pp=108\u2013109}} Studies of captive individuals have found other vocalizations, but their purpose has not been determined.{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|p=1318}} The northern giant mouse lemur appears to be the most vocal of the two species.{{LoM3 Sfn|p=171}} Although vocalizations are the primary form of social communication,{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|p=1318}} they also [[Territory (animal)|scent mark]] using saliva, urine, and secretions from the [[Scent gland|anogenital scent gland]] on small branches and other objects.{{LoM3 Sfn|p=167}}{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|p=1318}}\n\n===Reproduction===\n[[File:Taking measurements of a male Mirza zaza.JPG|thumb|right|Measurements are taken on a northern giant mouse lemur of its testicle size, which relative to its body size is the largest among living primates.|alt=Male northern giant mouse lemur being held while calipers are used to measure its testicle size.]]\nReproduction starts in November for Coquerel's giant mouse lemur at Kirindy Forest;{{LoM3 Sfn|p=167}} the estrous cycle runs approximately 22&nbsp;days, while estrus lasts only a day or less.{{Sfn|Nowak|1999|p=67}} The mating season in this southern population is limited to a few weeks, whereas the northern giant mouse lemur is thought to breed throughout the year, a trend seen in only two other species of lemur: the [[aye-aye]] (''Daubentonia madagascariensis'') and the [[red-bellied lemur]] (''Eulemur rubriventer'').{{Sfn|Rode\u2010Margono|Nekaris|Kappeler|Schwitzer|2015}} The northern giant mouse lemur had been observed breeding year-round in captivity if their litter did not survive or was removed,{{Sfn|Nowak|1999|p=67}} but at the time this population was thought to be Coquerel's giant mouse lemur.{{Sfn|Rode\u2010Margono|Nekaris|Kappeler|Schwitzer|2015}}\n\nOne to three offspring (typically two) are born after 90&nbsp;days of [[gestation]],{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|p=1317}}{{Sfn|Fleagle|2013|p=62}}{{LoM3 Sfn|p=167}} weighing approximately {{convert|12|g|oz|abbr=on}}. Because they are poorly developed, they initially remain in their mother's nest for up to three weeks, being transported by mouth between nests.{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|p=1317}}{{Sfn|Fleagle|2013|p=62}} Once they have grown sufficiently, typically after three weeks, the mother will park her offspring in vegetation while she forages nearby.{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|p=1317}}{{LoM3 Sfn|p=167}} After a month, the young begin to participate in social play and grooming with their mother, and between the first and second month, young males begin to exhibit early sexual behaviors (including mounting, neck biting, and pelvic thrusting).{{Sfn|Pages|1980|p=112}} By the third month, the young forage independently, though they maintain vocal contact with their mother{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|p=1317}}{{LoM3 Sfn|p=167}}{{Sfn|Pages|1980|p=112}} and use a small part of her range.{{Sfn|Pages|1980|p=112}}\n\nFemales start reproducing after ten months, while males develop functional testicles by their second mating season.{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|p=1317}} Testicle size in the northern giant mouse lemur does not appear to fluctuate by season,{{Sfn|Rode\u2010Margono|Nekaris|Kappeler|Schwitzer|2015}} and is so large relative to the animal's body mass that it is the highest among all [[primate]]s.{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|p=1317}}{{Sfn|Rode\u2010Margono|Nekaris|Kappeler|Schwitzer|2015}} This emphasis on sperm production in males, as well as the use of [[Mating plug|copulatory plugs]], suggests a mating system best described as [[Polygynandry|polygynandrous]]{{Sfn|Rode\u2010Margono|Nekaris|Kappeler|Schwitzer|2015}} where males use [[scramble competition]] (roaming widely to find many females).{{Sfn|Fleagle|2013|p=62}}{{Sfn|Rode\u2010Margono|Nekaris|Kappeler|Schwitzer|2015}} In contrast, male Coquerel's giant mouse lemurs appear to fight for access to females (contest competition) during their breeding season.{{Sfn|Rode\u2010Margono|Nekaris|Kappeler|Schwitzer|2015}} Males disperse from their natal range, and the age at which they leave varies from two years to several. Females reproduce every year, although postpartum estrus has been observed in captivity. In the wild, the lifespan of giant mouse lemurs is thought to rarely exceed five or six years,{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|p=1317}} though in captivity they can live up to 15&nbsp;years.{{Sfn|Nowak|1999|p=67}}\n\n==Ecology==\n[[File:Madagascar buzzard.jpg|thumb|upright|alt=Madagascar buzzard sitting on a branch|The [[Madagascar buzzard]] preys on giant mouse lemurs.]]\nBoth species are [[Omnivore|omnivorous]], eating fruit, flowers, buds, insect excretions, [[Natural gum|tree gums]], large insects, spiders, frogs, chameleons, snakes, small birds,{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|p=1317}}{{Sfn|Fleagle|2013|p=62}}{{LoM3 Sfn|p=167}} and eggs.{{Sfn|Pages|1980|p=98}} Coquerel's giant mouse lemur is thought to opportunistically prey on mouse lemurs{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|p=1317}}{{LoM3 Sfn|p=167}} after an individual was found with a half-eaten [[gray mouse lemur]] (''M.&nbsp;murinus'') in a trap.{{Sfn|Goodman|2003|p=1222}} During June and July, at the peak of the dry season, this species relies on sugary excretions from the [[larva]]e of [[hemiptera]]n and [[cochineal]] insects as well as tree gums.{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|p=1317}}{{LoM3 Sfn|p=167}} The sugary excretions are obtained by either licking them from the back of the insect or collecting the crystallized sugars that accumulate beneath the insect colony.{{Sfn|Pages|1980|p=98}} During this time of year, feeding on insect secretions can account for 60% of feeding activity.{{Sfn|Fleagle|2013|p=62}} In contrast, the northern giant mouse lemur relies on [[cashew]] fruits during the dry season.{{LoM3 Sfn|p=171}}\n\nGiant mouse lemurs are often [[Sympatry|sympatric]] with mouse lemurs, such as ''M.&nbsp;murinus'', though they are typically found higher in the canopy and favor thicker, taller gallery forests.{{Sfn|Fleagle|2013|p=62}} At the [[Marosalaza]] forest (north of Morondava), Coquerel's giant mouse lemur is sympatric with four other nocturnal lemurs (mouse lemurs, sportive lemurs, dwarf lemurs, and fork-marked lemurs), but manages [[niche differentiation]] by feeding at different times and specializing on insect secretions during the dry season.{{Sfn|Pages|1980|p=115}}\n\n[[Diurnality|Diurnal]] [[Bird of prey|birds of prey]] such as the [[Madagascar buzzard]] (''Buteo brachypterus'') are their most significant predators. Other documented predators of giant mouse lemurs include the [[Fossa (animal)|fossa]] (''Cryptoprocta ferox''), [[Madagascar owl]] (''Asio madagascariensis''), and the [[narrow-striped mongoose]] (''Mungotictis decemlineata'').{{Sfn|Goodman|2003|pp=1222\u20131223}}\n\n==Conservation==\nIn 2012, the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] (IUCN) assessed both Coquerel's giant mouse lemur and the northern giant mouse lemur as [[Endangered species|endangered]]. Prior to that, both species had been listed as [[Vulnerable species|vulnerable]]. Populations of both species are in decline due to [[habitat destruction]], primarily for [[Slash-and-burn|slash-and-burn agriculture]] and [[charcoal]] production. Also, they are both hunted for [[bushmeat]].{{R|IUCN_Mirza_coquereli|IUCN_Mirza_zaza}} The population announced by the WWF in 2010 was found outside the limits of a nearby protected area, PK32-Ranobe, which was granted temporary protection status in December 2008 and is co-managed by the WWF. Its forests were not included in the protected area due to existing [[Concession (contract)|concessions]] for [[mining]] activities.{{r|WWF_25Mar2010}}\n\nAs with all lemurs, giant mouse lemurs were first protected in 1969 when they were listed as \"Class A\" of the [[African Convention on the Conservation of Nature and Natural Resources]]. This prohibited hunting and capture without authorization, which would be given only for scientific purposes or the national interest. In 1973, they were also protected under [[CITES#Appendix I|CITES Appendix I]], which strictly regulates their trade and forbids commercial trade. Although enforcement is patchy, they are also protected under Malagasy law.{{Sfn|Harcourt|1990|p=47}}\n\nGiant mouse lemurs are rarely kept in captivity, though they breed easily. In 1989, the Duke Lemur Center held more than 70% of the captive population (45 of 62&nbsp;individuals). At the time, the DLC was coordinating a [[captive breeding]] program for Coquerel's giant mouse lemur, and all individuals kept at American facilities were descended from six individuals imported by the DLC in 1982{{Sfn|Harcourt|1990|p=47}} from the region around Ambanja.{{Sfn|Kappeler|2003|p=1316}} As of 2009 the [[International Species Information System]] (ISIS) recorded only six remaining individuals registered in the United States and Europe, all reclassified as northern giant mouse lemurs and considered a non-breeding population;{{LoM3 Sfn|p=167}} in 2015 only a single female remained on record.{{R|ISIS_Mirza_2015}}\n\n==References==\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em|refs=\n<ref name=\"WWF_25Mar2010\">{{cite web |url=http://www.wwf.mg/news.cfm?uNewsID=191725 |title=New population of rare giant-mouse lemurs found in Madagascar |date=25 March 2010 |publisher=[[World Wide Fund for Nature|World Wildlife Fund]] |accessdate=1 January 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150101100750/http://www.wwf.mg/news.cfm?uNewsID=191725 |archivedate=1 January 2015 |url-status=dead 